<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneCrashes 1stLd-Writethru a0785 06-20 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Crashes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0785,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Killed in Two Small Plane Crashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with three more bodies found in South Carolina.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine airplane en route from North Carolina to the
Bahamas crashed in rainy weather Tuesday, killing four people, and
three others died when a small plane crashed in the rugged White
Cloud Mountains in Idaho.
   The Beechcraft Duke en route to the Bahamas crashed about 5 p.m.
near Interstate 26 on the 2,300-acre site of the Carolina Eastman
Kodak plant in central South Carolina, said Sharon Kelly, a
spokeswoman for the Lexington County Fire Department.
   ``Everything was routine,'' said Federal Aviation Administration
spokesman Roger Myers in Atlanta. ``All of a sudden, they lost radar
contact.''
   One body was found within an hour of the crash and rescue workers
found the other three bodies in the plane about 9 p.m., Ms. Kelly
said. The rescue workers waited for FAA investigators to arrive on
the scene before entering the wreckage.
   ``We had pieces of the plane scattered a quarter-mile away,'' she
said.
   The victims had not been identified late Tuesday, Ms. Kelly said.
   In Idaho, the twin-engine, six-seat Piper Aztec was en route to
Challis when it crashed in mid-afternoon. The flight had originated
in Alaska and stopped in Wenatchee, Wash., said William Miller,
chief of the Idaho Division of Aeronautics in Boise.
   The cause of the crash was not immediately known, but snow, hail,
wind and rainstorms were reported in parts of central Idaho at the
time.
   The names of the victims were being withheld until relatives
could be notified.
</TEXT>
