<DOCNO> AP890620-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-PolishPolitician     06-20 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polish Politician,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Stopped Solidarity Juggernaut Admired for Making Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PILA, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took a free-spending entrepreneur to
deprive Solidarity of a clean sweep of the East bloc's first freely
elected legislative chamber. A Communist-backed businessman.
   Henryk Stoklosa, who has made millions processing dead animals,
edged out Piotr Baumgart, an activist of the independent farmers'
union Rural Solidarity, in Sunday's runoff, unofficial returns
showed Monday.
   Stoklosa had drawn the Communist coalition's biggest pre-election
crowd _ 50,000 people at Pila stadium for free sausages and beer and
a drawing with prizes including a tractor, a color television and a
videocassette recorder.
   Tickets for the drawing had been handed out free in the
province's myriad small agricultural villages beforehand.
   Stoklosa will be a minority of one in the new 100-member Senate
that is to convene next month along with the more powerful lower
house, or Sejm, which the ruling Communists dominate because
opposition candidates were only allowed to run for one-third of its
seats.
   A visit to Pila on Sunday gave some hint of Stoklosa's assets.
   On the streets of the 70,000-resident western provincial town _
unusually prosperous- and tidy-looking by Polish standards _
soldiers from nearby military bases strolled arm-in-arm with
girlfriends eating ice cream cones.
   Stoklosa's moustachioed face stared out at passers-by from
election posters plastered nearly everywhere, in store windows,
walls and road overpasses. There were also posters attacking
Baumgart as an interloper because he comes from Szczecin, about 90
miles away.
   A journalist for Solidarity's Election Gazette estimated Stoklosa
put 200 million zlotys ($235,000) into the campaign. It was believed
to be the most expensive political campaign ever launched for an
individual in postwar Poland.
   In the nearby town of Smilowo, where Stoklosa's Farmutil company
is headquartered, the polling station was doing a brisk business
Sunday in an apparent show of local pride in the town's favorite son.
   But Stoklosa himself was absent. Attending to business first, he
was at an international trade fair in Poznan.
   His Farmutil company, located on 345 acres at the end of a
specially built road in Smilowo, gives a shiny neat appearance.
   But it belches an obnoxious odor over the rolling landscape, as
dead farm animals and meat plant scraps are boiled down into fats
and fodders for delivery by Stoklosa's truck fleet to customers
around Poland.
   An employee, speaking as flies buzzed around, said the stench
would disappear as soon as a new hermetically sealed processing
system is completed.
   The 210-worker plant has sprung up in the past seven years.
Stoklosa left his job as Pila tourism director and was kicked out of
the Communist Party during Solidarity's 1980-81 heyday for alleged
mismanagement.
   The plant now produces mainly fodder for animals, but plans are
for it to expand into poultry raising, fertilizer production and
slaughtering.
   The company makes an estimated 3 billion zlotys ($3.5 million)
annually and published reports say Stoklosa as a result can tool
around town in either one of two new Mercedes.
   ``He's got everything he could want in life, and now he wants
other people to have more too,'' said Henryk Mocho, a Stoklosa
campaign worker.
   ``He has very good organizing ability. He is the man who started
this whole enterprise from nothing, and now people can make a good
living here.''
   Marian Malecki of the Pila Solidarity Citizens Committee passed
Sunday afternoon quietly at the opposition's empty campaign office
with Leszek Woznicki, his former jailmate from 1982, the year
thousands of Solidarity activists spent time in jail after
authorities crushed their movement.
   They anticipated Stoklosa's win, but treated it philosophically.
   ``We are aware that Poland does not begin and end at Pila,''
Malecki said. No matter what the outcome, the local committee would
share in Solidarity's ``great success'' because it elected one other
Senate candidate and two members to the Sejm from the city, he said.
   Wozniaki, a Solidarity activist at the town's largest industry, a
light-bulb factory, said his forces were outgunned by Stoklosa's
massive poster campaign and Western-style gimmicks.
   He blamed a lack of money, paper and printing machines and
suggested Polish-Americans send more material aid to Solidarity next
time.
   ``Tell them that a free Poland depends on them too,'' he said,
only half-jokingly.
</TEXT>
