<FIRST>r a PM-JuneauGoats     06-20 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Juneau Goats,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mountain Goat Herd to be Returned to Mount Juneau</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of absence, mountain goats will
be returned to the steep slopes of Mount Juneau with the help of
tranquilizers, helicopters and thousands of dollars in donations.
   Volunteers plan to relocate at least 10 wild goats from a remote
site south of Juneau or the Olympic Peninsula of Washington in late
summer or early fall.
   The goal is to restore a herd of goats that can be viewed by
residents and tourists in downtown Juneau, which sits in the narrow
valley between Mount Juneau and Mount Roberts.
   ``If all goes well, in a year or two or five we'll have a
population that will create splinter groups to proliferate in
valleys from Taku Inlet to Berners Bay,'' said project coordinator
Joel Bennett, a member of the state Fish and Game Board.
   ``Mount Juneau used to be goat habitat,'' Bennett said Monday.
``Goats were there quite commonly back in the mining days, the early
days of Juneau.''
   However, overhunting led to the goats' disappearance near the
Southeast Alaska city. Although goat hunting has been banned in the
area for several years, the goats have never returned.
   Since the Juneau Audubon Society began soliciting money for the
project in February, it has collected about $9,500 in money and
services _ enough to start the project, Bennett said.
   Bennett hopes to have $12,000 by the time the relocation begins,
and said he has been encouraged by the public response. Donations
have included helicopter time from a local charter outfit, a $1,000
check and $30 worth of quarters that a little girl collected in a
bag.
   If the goats cannot be captured south of Juneau near Whiting
River, the volunteers will turn to the Olympic Peninsula where the
goat population has become a nuisance.
   ``We actally gave the goats to the Olympic Peninsula in the first
place. We would be getting the same stock back,'' Bennett said.
   State wildlife officials will tranquilize the goats, which will
be transported to the mountain by helicopters. Officials hope to get
at least three males and seven females to ensure that the population
grows.
   Radio collars will be put on some of the goats so their movement
can be monitored.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
