<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     06-20 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the belief that these are vinegar's salad
days, a bus driver has brought out a book entirely on the
centuries-old food seasoning.
   ``Vinegar is something more than just to put in your salad,''
Lawrence J. Diggs said at a news conference Monday flanked by
various vinegars. One displayed was the gourmet's balsamic, which
can cost up to $30 for a few ounces.
   Diggs believes his 259-page book ``Vinegar'' is the most complete
ever written on the subject.
   Vinegar, from the French word for ``sour wine,'' is the end
product of fermentation. Anything that can be fermented into alcohol
_ including fruits, grains, orange juice, molasses, honey _ can be
made into vinegar.
   The tome covers vinegar's history, commercial production, how to
make it at home, and medicinal uses.
   ``To remove a freckle, apply vinegar,'' the author prescribes.
Soda mixed with vinegar will deal with heartburn, while hay fever
can be combated by inhaling horseradish and vinegar several times a
day.
   Diggs even has a chapter on vinegar trivia. ``If one dreams about
vinegar, it signifies jealousy or a quarrel,'' he advises, and
``Never give vinegar away or your luck will go with it.''
   The author, a Zen Buddhist, said he planned to use profits from
the $24.95 book to establish a monastic hermitage. He also expressed
gratitude to San Francisco's Municipal Railway for helping make his
book possible.
   ``I wrote a lot of the book on the bus,'' he confided.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Summer is coming to central Idaho's Camas
Prairie, and Harold Stroud once again has his eye on Soldier
Mountain's last patch of snow _ and on his friends Bill Stewart and
Wes Fields.
   As they have for more than a decade, the three have placed bets
on when the final remnant of winter will disappear. With dinner for
the winner at stake, it's a bet that nature has not always been
allowed to settle.
   Stroud is betting again that the snow will still being visible on
Aug. 10, but he knows a lot can happen by then.
   Faced with losing several years ago when the snow was nearly gone
days before his target date, Stroud sent his two sons up the
mountain to stretch white sheets on the ground. Sheets can look a
lot like snow from 10 miles away, but someone picked them up early
and Stroud lost.
   Another year, Stroud was ready to collect a free meal because a
tiny patch of snow was visible the afternoon before the day of
reckoning. But the next day, the mountain looked bare. As it turned
out, Stewart had driven into the high country with Fields to shovel
dirt over the snow patch.
   Winning that bet cost them about $500, but as Fields said,
``Winning is the thing, you see.''
</TEXT>
