<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     06-20 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worst Wind Erosion in 30 Years Sweeps Over Great Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wind erosion over the winter inflicted its
worst damage in three decades on the Great Plains, ripping away
topsoil over 14.3 million acres, the Agriculture Department says.
   ``The big reason for the increase is the drought,'' soil
conservation service chief Wilson Scaling said Monday. ``Not only
was it dry but it meant we went into the wind erosion season with
inadequate vegetative cover and little residue to protect the soil
from blowing.''
   He said the last time the May-November wind erosion season
wrought so much damage on the Great Plains was when 15 million acres
were damaged in 1954-55, when the department first began to keep
such records.
   In the worst day of the season, winds of up to 80 miles an hour
swooped through on Kansas on March 14, damaging 4.8 million acres.
   Kansas was the hardest hit state, with more than 5 million acres
damaged. It was a record for the state. North Dakota was second with
2.3 million acres harmed and Texas followed with almost 2 million
acres damaged.
   More than 90 percent of the damage is on lands being used for
crops. The rest is on rangeland.
   Wind erosion damage last year uprooted soil from some 12 million
acres.
   The department said farmers used emergency tillage on 3 million
acres, a system under which topsoil with sufficient moiture is
roughened to prevent blowing. More than half of the emergency
tillage was in Texas.
   Here is a list of the amount of acres damaged in each Great
Plains state:
   Montana 1,832,000; Nebraska 191,600; North Dakota 2,297,700;
South Dakota 678,600; Wyoming 552,700; Colorado 1,403,700; Kansas
5,126,300; New Mexico 118,000; Oklahoma 111,900; Texas 1,979,600.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat production in the United States and
Europe should fall slightly below previous estimates for the next
year, suggesting supplies already reduced by last year's drought
will remain tight, the USDA says.
   With world stocks already at their lowest in more than a decade,
prices could be somewhat skittish in the crop year that began June
1, responding sharply to changes in growing conditions and import
demand, the department said.
   A drop of $10 a ton in the price of U.S. wheat in recent weeks
represents an example of this sensitivity, the Agriculture
Department said in its monthly World Grain Situation and Outlook
report.
   Despite such fluctuations, however, prices should remain strong
on the whole, the department said. It said the overall strength in
prices combined with an improvement in crop prospects in some of the
traditional importing countries is expected to reduce world demand
from the level of a year earlier.
   The USDA said the major change will come in the Soviet Union,
where wheat imports are expected to decline by around 20 percent to
12 million tons.
   Estimated exports by the European Community remain the same as
previously, but the forecast of production has been lowered to
reflect a smaller than expected crop of durum, the wheat used for
pasta. The report said that might mean increased EC imports of North
American durum and might even trigger a cutback in Italian semolina
exports to North Africa.
   The European Community estimate was for 77.8 million metric tons,
down from 78.5 million last month.
   The estimate of U.S. production was 55.2 million, down from 55.8
million in last month's report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parrot lovers and other buyers of exotic birds
are getting a stern warning from the Department of Agriculture to
make certain their pets meet federal import requirements.
   The warning has been brought on by an outbreak of exotic
Newcastle disease among 17 Amazon parrots, sun cockatoos and other
birds owned by a Connecticut collector. Seven of the parrots were
purchased from a Houston dealer on May 19 and became ill. They and
12 other birds were dead by June 14.
   Meanwhile, the collector had sold some of the birds to five pet
stores and a number of individual purchasers.
   The birds were tested by the National Veterinary Services
Laboratories in Ames, Iowa, operated by USDA's Animal and Plant
Health Inspection Service. They were found to have exotic Newcastle
disease.
   To prevent further spread of the disease, the collector's 60
remaining birds were destroyed, the department said. It said it will
pay the collector more than $45,000 in indemnities for the
destruction of his collection.
   Exotic Newcastle disease is a virus that is deadly to all birds
and could be a major problem for the commercial poultry industry,
although no commercial flocks have been infected yet.
   Larry B. Slagle, acting director of the inspection service, said
smuggled birds enter the United States by the hundreds following the
winter breeding season and often carry exotic Newcastle disease
without showing symptoms.
   He said exotic birds imported into the United States must be
declared to federal inspectors, carry appropriate permits and enter
a mimimum 30-day quarantine. The Agriculture Department tests them
for disease during that time.
</TEXT>
