<FIRST>r w PM-OrganizedCrime     06-20 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Organized Crime,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Will Merge Strike Forces Into U.S. Attorneys' Offices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh says his
decision to merge the Justice Department's organized crime strike
forces into U.S. attorneys' offices will eliminate confusion and
duplication in the current system.
   Thornburgh said Monday the 14 strike forces will be abolished and
organized crime units will be created in 23 U.S. attorneys' offices
around the country by Oct. 1.
   The plan, which the attorney general earlier said he was
considering, has drawn fire from some in Congress who contend it
would blunt an effective weapon against organized crime.
   Thornburgh, a former U.S. attorney in Pittsburgh, said in a
statement the changes ``are designed to ensure that the department's
resources are more comprehensively directed against organized
crime.''
   ``They will help reduce confusion and overlapping jurisdiction
among federal investigators and prosecutors as well as making more
resources available by shutting down duplicate offices,'' Thornburgh
said.
   Congressional hearings are planned on the issue, including one
scheduled today by the House Judiciary criminal justice subcommittee.
   Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., called Thornburgh's announcement
on the eve of the subcommittee's hearing ``sort of a slap in the
face to the many senators and representatives who asked him to wait
until we could really discuss this.''
   Schumer said the subcommittee he chairs has taken no position on
the issue but has heard good arguments both for keeping and for
abolishing the strike forces.
   If lawmakers determine Thornburgh made a wrong decision ``we will
consider introducing legislation to preserve the strike forces,'' he
said.
   The strike forces were conceived in the 1960s by then-Attorney
General Robert F. Kennedy.
   Since 1984, members of the top echelon of organized crime
families in Boston, Buffalo, N.Y.; Chicago, Kansas City, Cleveland,
Brooklyn and Philadelphia, were convicted as a result of strike
force prosecutions.
   The debate over the strike forces is not new. But it flared up
earlier this year when Thornburgh disclosed he was considered a plan
to abolish them.
   Several senators, including Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.; Strom
Thurmond, R-S.C., and Sam Nunn, D-Ga., urged Thornburgh not to
abolish the strike forces.
   In an article published in Monday's editions of The New York
Times, Nunn and Kennedy argued that ``there is no justification for
such a step.''
   They suggested that Thornburgh was responding to the traditional
hostility to strike forces by U.S. attorneys who are protective of
their turf.
   ``Ending all strike forces to assuage U.S. attorneys' egos would
be a triumph of ideology over common sense and could destroy the
federal organized-crime program,'' the senators wrote.
   Thomas Puccio, a former Abscam prosecutor, said it would be ``a
mistake to abolish them.''
   ``You won't have a group that's permanently dedicated to
organized crime,'' said Puccio, a New York defense lawyer.
   ``You also develop a certain amount of professionalism and
although there are some outstanding U.S. attorneys, those selections
are still made politically to some degree,'' he said.
   Thornburgh said he would create an organized crime council within
the Justice Department to coordinate the fight against such criminal
activity.
   Beg Your Pardon ?
</TEXT>
