<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-MIAs     06-20 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-MIAs,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese to Return 28 Sets Of Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam will on Wednesday turn over the
remains of what it believes are 28 American servicemen missing from
the Vietnam War, a U.S. military spokesman said.
   Maj. Dan Trout said today that a U.S. military team is to fly to
Hanoi, the Vietnamese capital, for a turn-over ceremony before the
remains are flown to the United States.
   The repatriation is to be the 10th since August 1987, when the
United States made a special effort to get Vietnamese help in
resolving the missing in action, or MIA, issue. Since then, 184
remains have been returned and 56 to date identified as those of
American servicemen, Trout said.
   A C-141 transport aircraft will fly a team from the U.S. Joint
Casualty Resolution Center to Hanoi airport. It will be headed by
Lieut. Col. James D. Spurgeon, who is the JCRC representative in
Bangkok.
   Trout said the remains would be flown via Guam to Hawaii, where
the U.S. military maintains a laboratory for the identification of
MIA remains.
   Official statistics show 2,353 Americans still listed as missing
from the Indochina war, including 1,719 in Vietnam, 545 in Laos, 83
in Cambodia and six in China.
   Some Americans believe Vietnam is also holding live Americans but
Hanoi has denied this and concrete evidence has yet to surface from
independent sources.
   A group of 40 U.S. congressmen is asking the Bush administration
to investigate a Japanese monk's claims that he shared a prison cell
with three captive U.S. soldiers and saw as many as 10 American
prisoners while in Vietnam.
   The reported POW sightings came from Iwanobu Yoshida, a
65-year-old Buddhist monk imprisoned for 14 years before his release
in January.
   In a letter sent last week to Bush, the congressmen urged ``a
thorough investigation of this recent account of American POWS in
Vietnam.''
</TEXT>
