<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonBriefs     06-20 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington Briefs,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Would Cover More Pregnant Women, Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen is sponsoring legislation to
expand government health-care coverage to an additional 300,000
low-income pregnant women and 1.6 million children under the age of
six.
   Co-sponsored by Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., the legislation would
cost an estimated $1 billion a year, Bentsen's office said.
   The measure would provide Medicaid coverage to pregnant women and
children under age six in families whose income is at 185 percent of
the poverty level _ $22,385 for a family of four.
   Under legislation enacted last year and being phased in this year
and next, Medicaid coverage is guaranteed to pregnant women and
infants under age 1 in families whose income is at the poverty level
_ $12,100 for a family of four.
   The estimated cost of phasing in Medicaid coverage under
Bentsen's bill would be $790 million in fiscal 1990, and $1.2
billion in 1991, when the legislation is fully in place.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Boating Deaths At Record Low</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recreational boating fatalities continued to
drop last year to a record low of 946 deaths while the number of
registered boats increased, according to the Transportation
Department.
   Coast Guard officials said the decline was the result of
increased awareness of the danger of drinking while boating.
   Fatalities declined to 946 in 1988 from 1,036 in 1987, 1,066 in
1986 and 1,116 in 1985, the department said. The 1988 figure, which
amounted to 5.5 deaths per 100,000 boats, was the lowest since the
Coast Guard began keeping track of boating fatalities 28 years ago.
   The Coast Guard estimates that there were 17.3 million boats on
the nation's waterways in 1988, an increase of 400,000 over the
previous year.
