<HEAD>Seattle Teen-Agers Win Trouble-Shooting Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two recent high school graduates from Seattle
have won a trophy which says they are the best high school auto
technicians in the nation.
   The victory came Monday when the pair took slightly more than 36
minutes to assemble a car distributor, find a fault in the new
assembly and fix it, repair a fuel-injector cap, made a faulty
headlight work and made instrument and dashboard lights work
properly.
   Mike Seresun, 17, and Walter Yagen, 18, of Ingraham High School
in Seattle beat out 49 other state finalist teams in the 40th annual
trouble-shooting contest, sponsored jointly by the American
Automobile Association and Plymouth. It was the second consecutive
victory for a Washington team.
