<FIRST>r a PM-FantasyCanyonVandalism     06-20 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fantasy Canyon Vandalism,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vandals Destroy Fragile Rock Formations; Reward Offered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VERNAL, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals have shattered eight ancient rock
formations in eastern Utah's Fantasy Canyon and a $500 reward is
being offered for information leading to convictions.
   The fragile formations of sandstone were among about 50 carved
through the millenia by water erosion in the desert about 40 miles
southeast of here, said Ray Tate of the federal Bureau of Land
Management.
   ``Fantasy Canyon has a lot of the most unique rock formations
you've ever seen in your life,'' he said. ``They're very fragile.''
   The damage occurred between April 1, when agency employees were
in the area, and the third week of April, when the damage was
discovered, Tate said.
   He said one damaged formation called Camel Rock was about 16 feet
high and looked like the animal.
   ``The head came out, and it looked like it was looking back at
you,'' he said.
   Another formation resembled a thin sheet of plywood about 6 feet
high and 4 feet wide, Tate said.
   ``That was shattered,'' he said. ``You just don't see rock eroded
like that.''
   He said the formations, created between 38 million and 50 million
years ago, once were beneath a sea. Turtle fossils and dinosaur
bones have been found in the area.
   There were no signs that vandals used tools, but Tate said
physical strength would have been enough.
   ``If a person put their mind to it, they could break them pretty
good,'' he said.
   Tate said the area isn't well known or advertised, but is revered
by Vernal residents who take visitors there.
   ``They're really unhappy about it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
