<FIRST>r w PM-JailedMother     06-20 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jailed Mother,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Must Remain Jailed in Custody Dispute, Judge Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother jailed since August 1987 in a child
custody dispute may not be freed until she produces her daughter for
visits with her ex-husband or turns the child over to public
authorities, a judge says.
   District of Columbia Superior Court Judge Herbert Dixon refused
on Monday to release Dr. Elizabeth Morgan, a Washington plastic
surgeon who was jailed 22 months ago on civil contempt of court
charges.
   Morgan has refused to allow court-ordered visits between her
daughter Hilary and Eric Foretich, Morgan's ex-husband and the
girl's father, contending that Foretich sexually abused the girl.
Foretich has repeatedly denied those charges, and Hilary's
whereabouts have been unknown.
   An appeals court had directed Dixon to review his December 1988
decision to keep Morgan in jail.
   Stephen Sachs, Morgan's attorney, has argued that jailing her
failed to coerce her into producing her daughter, and that the
purpose has turned from coercion to punishment.
   But Dixon's ruling said, ``The order which causes (Morgan's)
incarceration was and continues to be for coercive purposes only,
and this has not changed due solely to the passage of time.
   ``No credible evidence has been received concerning the child's
present condition or circumstances, notwithstanding Morgan's
declaration that the the child is healthy, happy and healing,'' the
judge's ruling said.
   Dixon ruled that Morgan should remain in jail because she has not
taken the opportunity to go free by turning the child over to the
District of Columbia's child custody division.
   Sachs called Dixon's ruling ``flat-out wrong,'' adding that
Morgan ``feels the social services arrangement a booby trap by which
the child can be turned over to the father.''
   Foretich said he hopes the ruling will force Morgan to produce
their daughter.
   ``What he's done here is that he has stated that there is an
alternate method by which Elizabeth Morgan can comply,'' Foretich
said. ``This option was always available to her, and he has made
that possibility very clear.''
   The House District of Columbia Committee today was to review a
bill to limit civil contempt jailings in the district.
   The bill, sponsored by Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., would alter
charges of civil contempt to criminal contempt after a person has
been jailed for 12 months. The measure would be applied
retroactively to Morgan's case and would guarantee her a jury trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
