<SECOND>PM-Hijack Attempt,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airport Guard Shot During Hijacking Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who said he wanted to hijack a plane
to Cuba shot an airport security guard in the leg with a
semiautomatic rifle before being overpowered and arrested, according
to authorities.
   Gary Thompson, 39, of Cornelius, was arrested on charges of
attempted murder and attempted air piracy, said Doug Roberts, a
spokesman for Portland International Airport.
   Donald Hudson, 70, was listed in satisfactory condition at
Providence Hospital with a leg wound.
   The shooting occurred Monday night at an airport security
checkpoint.
   Roberts said that Thompson told authorities he brought a
disassembled .22-caliber semiautomatic rifle to the airport and put
it together in a restroom.
   Thompson then approached a security checkpoint on a concourse
leading to flight gates, pointed the rifle at Hudson, told him he
would be taken hostage and demanded a flight to Cuba, Roberts said.
   Thompson shot the guard through the right thigh, Roberts said.
Police rushed to the scene and overpowered Thompson.
   Witnesses reported that Thompson yelled, ``You want to be a
hero!'' before he opened fire.
   One guard reported that during the struggle, Thompson tried to
fire the weapon again, but it didn't shoot. Thompson had apparently
inadvertently released the clip from the weapon, Roberts said.
   Roberts said Thompson bought the rifle at a sporting goods store
in Cornelius and lied on the portion of the form asking if the buyer
had ever been in a mental hospital.
   Roberts said Thompson, a Vietnam veteran, had spent time in
Dammasch State Hospital.
</TEXT>
