<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--AlaskaQuake     06-20 0129</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Alaska Quake,0132</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Quake Rattles Alaska</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALMER, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake jolted Shemya Air Force
Base in the Aleutian Islands. No injuries or serious damage was
reported.
   The quake struck at 9:42 p.m. Monday (1:42 a.m. EDT today) and
measured 5.1 on the Richter scale. It was centered 50 miles
southwest of the base, said Alec Medbery, a spokesman at the Alaska
Tsunami Warning Center in Palmer.
   He said the quake was felt sharply at the base, which is in the
western Aleutians, and knocked books off a shelf, but no injuries
were reported.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one means a tenfold increase in
magnitude.
   A magnitude 5 quake can cause considerable damage.
</TEXT>
