<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua-US     06-20 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-US,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua's Ortega Seeks Talks With Bush to Improve Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega is seeking
talks with the Bush administration to cool Nicaragua's mounting
friction with the United States and help pull the economy out of its
nosedive.
   Ortega announced the offer Monday after a 1{-hour meeting with
Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo. He asked the Roman Catholic
archbishop of Managua to carry the request for opening negotiations
to Washington.
   Obando y Bravo, a sharp critic of Ortega's leftist Sandinista
government, said he was ``going to think about this and will give an
answer'' but refused to go into details.
   There was no immediate reaction from Washington.
   The cardinal and Ortega, standing side by side, talked to
reporters after their meeting.
   ``We have asked Cardinal Obando y Bravo to ... take steps and
mediate with President Bush so that a fluid dialogue can develop,''
Ortega said. ``We are willing to develop a dialogue with the North
American government so foundations can be laid for normalizing
relations between Nicaragua and the United States.''
   The last time Nicaragua and the United States held talks on
improving relations was in June 1984 in Mexico and they ended in
deadlock.
   Many of Nicaragua's difficulties stem from a 1981 U.S. decision
to support Contra rebels and cut off all financial aid to Managua.
In 1985, Washington prohibited U.S. companies from doing business
with Nicaragua.
   Ortega said Monday he much appreciated an open letter in which
about 800 Latin American bishops recently asked Washington to lift
the embargo.
   The United States has argued that the Sandinistas' military ties
with the Soviet bloc, their purported failure to carry out
democratic reforms and their support of leftist rebels in
neighboring El Salvador endanger security in Central America.
   Nicaragua claims its support of the Salvadoran guerrillas has
only been moral _ not material.
   On June 12, the State Department accused Nicaragua of trying to
restrict foreign monitoring of February's presidential elections by
requiring Americans _ for the first time _ to acquire entry visas as
of July 1.
   On May 26, Nicaragua expelled two U.S. diplomats, accusing them
of helping incite a wildcat strikes by teachers demanding higher pay
and better working conditions.
   It was Nicaragua's second big strike in three weeks.
   Taxi drivers stopped working in many cities when prices of
gasoline _ along with most other goods _ more than doubled following
a sharp devaluation June 12 of the cordoba currency.
   The devaluation of the cordoba _ the 20th this year _ was part of
an asuterity program announced by Ortega Jan. 30 to try and check
skyrocketing inflation that surpassed 20,000 percent last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
