<DOCNO> AP890620-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-20 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen Tuesday,
while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose sharply.
   The dollar closed at 143.80 yen, down 1.70 yen from Monday's
145.50-yen close. It opened at 143.75 yen and ranged between 143.25
yen and 144.00 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed at
33,233.47, up 220.29 points, or 0.67 percent. The index had lost
41.99 points the previous day.
   Yoshio Shimoyama, a dealer with Nikko Securities in Tokyo, said
the index rose on its own energy within the market.
   ``Prices were higher almost across the board, mainly because of
the yen's upswing,'' he said.
   ``But many market players were still inactive, trying to figure
out the possible direction of the foreign exchange trading,''
Shimoyama said. ``Because of the uncertainites, a majority of
institutional investors remained on the sidelines.''
   In currency dealings, the Bank of Japan reportedly sold dollars
in small amounts at about 143.60 yen to 143.70 yen, traders said.
The amount of intervention was not clear. The central bank does not
comment on its monetary activities.
   An analyst with the Bank of Tokyo said anonymously that the
currency market was nervous as participants tried to figure out the
direction of trading.
   He said the dollar-yen rate fluctuated as investors made position
adjustments.
   Meanwhile, Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita told a monthly
economic meeting that the yen's foreign exchange, which had been
fluctuating wildly due to speculative dealings, had stabilized after
a series of joint interventions with other nations, Kyodo News
Service reported.
</TEXT>
