<SECOND>PM-Korea-Shooting,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korean Fisherman Apparently Shot by U.S. Helicopter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South Korean fisherman was apparently
hit by gunfire from a U.S. Marine helicopter taking part in gunnery
practice, the U.S. military said in a statement today.
   The fisherman, Sohn Dal-gun, was hit by a bullet Monday while
fishing with two other men in the Yellow Sea off the west coast, the
statement said. The bullet apparently came from a Marine helicopter
practicing at the Koon-ni military target range on the nearby shore,
it said.
   A U.S. officer, who declined to be named, said the fisherman was
hit in the hand and the foot, but was not seriously hurt. The two
other fishermen in the boat were not hurt.
   The incident was under investigation, the statement said.
   Koon-ni Range, which is under U.S. military control, has been at
the center of a dispute with local farmers demanding the facility be
closed and the land turned over to them. Ten U.S. Air Force
personnel were hurt last month when about 150 South Koreans stormed
the range to demand it be closed.
   The United States has some 43,000 troops based in South Korea
under a joint defense treaty.
</TEXT>
