<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0501EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChildrenShot     06-20 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children Shot,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Senate Passes Child-Gun Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Florida Senate approved a bill that
would jail gun owners who don't secure their loaded weapons. The
action came in response to accidental shootings that killed three
children and wounded four this month.
   ``The nation is watching to see what Florida does,'' Sen. Jeanne
Malchon, a co-sponsor of the legislation, said before Monday's 32-4
vote sent the bill to the House.
   ``It's probably at this point one of the first bills in the
nation aimed at safety of children in access to guns,'' Senate
President Bob Crawford said.
   ``It didn't do everything that I wanted it to, but it's a bill
that will significantly encourage safety, so I'm very pleased that
we passed it.''
   A House committee was scheduled to consider the bill this morning
as the Legislature began the second day of a three-day special
session called by Gov. Bob Martinez.
   Accidental gunshots are the fifth-leading cause of death of U.S.
children under age 14, and Florida has one of the three highest
rates of accidental shootings in the country, according to Malchon,
who proposed similar legislation two years ago.
   Under the bill, adults who fail to secure a loaded weapon that is
used by a minor in an accidental shooting could be charged with a
felony and sentenced to five years in prison and fined $5,000. It
would be a misdemeanor if a minor displayed the gun or threatened
someone with it.
   Opponents narrowed the bill's scope by exempting unloaded
firearms and guns kept in cars or boats, and dropping the age of
minors to under 16 from under 18.
   Senators also decided to require the state Department of
Education to come up with a gun safety education plan by next spring
rather than adding such a provision to the bill itself.
   Marion Hammer, the National Rife Association's Florida
spokeswoman, said the legislation was ``phony, unreal and a
disservice to the people of Florida.'' She blamed the controversy on
the media.
   ``The Legislature felt that it needed to do something so that you
folks would shut up,'' she told reporters.
   The House had approved a version of the bill during the regular
session, but the Senate failed to act on it.
   In addition to taking up the Senate version, the House also was
scheduled to consider a bill that would punish anyone selling or
loaning a weapon to an unsupervised minor without parental
permission. The bill also would require gun owners to keep their
firearms locked and empty.
   Another House proposal would require gun stores to post signs to
warn gunowners about leaving loaded firearms within reach of
children.
   A rash of accidental shootings this month prompted Martinez to
include the bill in the special session, which originally was called
over a $2.4 billion turnpike expansion plan.
   Silvio Claud Pierre, 4, died Saturday a week after he had shot
himself at his family's home. The Tampa boy found a .25-caliber
semiautomatic handgun under a couch while his mother was in the
shower. His father was not at home.
   On June 6, a 10-year-old Orlando boy was killed by a playmate. On
June 5, an 8-year-old Miramar girl was killed by her 10-year-old
brother who thought his father's gun was unloaded.
   Four children, ages 4 to 16, were accidentally wounded this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
