<FIRST>r i PM-China-Journalist     06-20 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Journalist,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Journalist Says China Movement Still Alive</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British journalist arrested twice for
violating Chinese martial law said today that the pro-democracy
movement remains alive in China despite the government's efforts to
suppress it.
   Brian Barron made the comments after arriving in Hong Kong from
China.
   Barron, Asian correspondent for the British Broadcasting Corp.,
said Chinese authorities returned his passport Monday after holding
it for a week following his second arrest. He was required to write
a ``self-criticism'' for violating martial law restrictions on
reporting.
   However, the 49-year-old journalist said he had not been expelled
and was free to return to China any time. He was accompanied by his
wife, daughter and three members of his television crew.
   ``We were free to leave when we liked, and we chose to leave
today,'' he said. ``After our holiday, I hope to go back to China
and continue reporting.''
   On Monday, Beijing ordered the expulsion of the sixth foreign
journalist in 10 days. Given 72 hours to leave was Joseph Kahn, an
American working part-time for the Dallas Morning News. He was in
China on a tourist visa.
   Last week, China expelled two Beijing-based American
correspondents on charges of violating martial law. In addition,
three journalists of Britain's Independent Television News, who were
not based in China, have been deported.
   After arriving in Hong Kong, Barron said he believes the
pro-democracy movement, which the government has tried to put down
beginning with the military assault in Beijing on June 3-4, still
has broad popularity.
   ``I don't think the pro-democracy movement in the sense of mass
feelings of change has been crushed,'' he told reporters at Hong
Kong airport after arriving from Beijing. Barron is based in Hong
Kong.
   ``In fact, when we drove to the airport this morning, we did see
a few truckloads of troops, but we also saw at least one individual
pass our bus and give the ``V'' sign ... the symbol of the
pro-democracy movement.
   ``We interpreted it as a gesture of defiance ... or support for
the pro-democracy movement,'' he said.
   Barron said he has covered China off and on for 15 years.
   He said he was first detained June 8 while he and his crew were
filming a burned-out tank in the capital.
   He said they were forced to kneel on the road at gunpoint. Their
equipment was seized and parts were smashed.
   His second detention a week ago was entirely different: ``We did
self-criticisms, we were not abused in any way, and after three
hours of interrogation, we were allowed to go to our hotel.''
   Under martial law, foreign reporters are barred from talking to
Chinese about martial law or taking pictures of soldiers.
Journalists generally have ignored the regulations, however.
   Barron said he continued reporting after the second arrest, and
no effort was made to stop him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
