<FIRST>u w PM-ToxicHotSpots 1stLd-Writethru a0442 06-20 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Toxic Hot Spots, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0442,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Deletes extraneous matter at end.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cancer Chemicals, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Utah County Leads List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More toxic chemicals are released into the air
in Toole County, Utah, than any other county in the United States,
the Environmental Protection Agency says.
   In fact, the 68 million pounds of toxic chemicals released in
that county each year account for all the toxic chemical releases
into the air in Utah that were reported to the EPA, the federal
agency said Monday.
   Other county hot spots for toxic industrial air pollution with
more than 45 million tons of hazardous chemical released were:
Warren County in Virginia, Mobile County in Alabama and Ascension
County in Louisiana.
   The county breakdown was included in a report that showed 2.7
billion pounds of toxic chemicals are released by industry into the
air annually. The overall figure had been reported before, but the
detailed breakdown by counties had not previously been available.
   The EPA provided no industrial plants in its summary, referring
only to the individual counties.
   But the Natural Resources Defense Council, citing the EPA report
and other agency documents, said that Amax Corp. in Rowley, Utah,
accounted for all of the reported toxic pollutants in Tooele County.
   The NRDC also cited these companies:
   _Avtex Fibers of Front Royal, Va., 50.1 million pounds, in Warren
County.
   _Courtaulds North America Inc. of LeMoyne, Ala., 42 million
pounds, in Mobile County.
   _Triad Chemical, Donaldsonville, La., 19.8 million pounds, and
C.F. Industries, also of Donaldsonville, 16.2 million pounds, in
Ascension County.
   Meanwhile, the EPA said that 25 counties accounted for two-thirds
of the discharges of toxic chemicals into surface water.
   San Bernardino County in California had by far the largest
volume, nearly 3.7 billion pounds, about two-thirds of which came
from a single company. The chemical involved was usually sodium
sulfate, which the EPA said it is planning soon to take off the
toxic chemical list on the grounds that it poses no serious health
threat.
   Harrison County in Mississippi had the next largest volume of
discharges into surface water with 369 million pounds, followed by
Harris County in Texas with 296 million pounds, according to EPA.
   Here are the 25 counties listed by EPA as having the highest
releases of toxic chemicals in the air and surface water:
</TEXT>
