<FIRST>r a PM-VanCliburn     06-20 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Van Cliburn,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Van Cliburn Returns After 11 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON BEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A standing ovation at the end of
Tchaikovsky's Piano Concerto No. 1, 13 curtain calls and four
encores marked Van Cliburn's triumphant return to the concert stage
after 11 years.
   The Tchaikovsky was Cliburn's signature number after he won the
first Tchaikovsky Competition in Moscow in 1958. He was an instant
celebrity at age 23 and the first classical musician ever given a
ticker-tape parade in New York.
   Two decades later, he began an 11-year hiatus saying his schedule
of up to 100 concerts a year was too grueling.
   He has given two private performances since 1978 _ at the White
House in December 1987 during Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's
visit, and January 1988 and the Bob Hope Cultural Center in Palm
Springs, Calif.
   Monday night, a crowd estimated at between 10,000 and 12,000
welcomed him back at the Mann Music Center open-air amphitheater.
Tickets sold for up top $125 each.
   ``It's so good to be back with the Philadelphia Orchestra,''
Cliburn said following Monday morning's rehearsal. ``It seems like I
never left.''
   In addition to the Tchaikovsky, Cliburn performed Liszt's Piano
Concerto No. 1 with Stanislaw Skrowaczewski guest conductor.
   Cliburn's piano was brought on stage and an uncustomary hush fell
on the audience as they waited for the tall, lanky Texan to appear.
He walked out and stood before a microphone.
   ``This is a very sentimental evening for me, an evening of
remembrance of two old friends,'' he said.
   He was referring to Eugene Ormandy, Hungarian-born music director
of the Philadelphia Orchestra for 44 years, and impressario Fredric
R. Mann, a former U.S. ambassador, who ran the Music Center in
Philadelphia's Fairmount Park from 1949 until his death in 1987. The
name was changed from Robin Hood Dell in 1980 to honor Mann.
   Cliburn joined forces with Ormandy and the Philadelphia musicians
within weeks of his Moscow triumph.
   ``I remember that time so well. We were all together then. Not
just for one concert, but several concerts,'' he said.
   The relationship continued through years of concerts and
recordings. Mann became a close friend and was later an associate
when Cliburn moved into the business world.
   Ormandy retired in 1980 and died five years later.
   Mann worked hard to build the summer classical concert season,
attended on each of the 18 concert dates by up to 10,000 people who
only had to mail in a newspaper coupon for free tickets.
   Tickets sold for up to $125, with proceeds going to the summer
classical program. General admission tickets for spots on the grassy
hillside behind the covered covered ampitheater sold for $12.50.
   Mann ``wanted everyone on the face of the Earth to believe in
classical music,'' Cliburn said, which was why the Philadelphia
Orchestra summer series was so important to him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0048 </DOCNO>
