<FIRST>r a PM-Newspage-Switzer     06-20 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspage-Switzer,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oklahoma Coach Resigns, Cites Frustration With NCAA Rules</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KO4, NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORMAN, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   University of Oklahoma coach Barry Switzer
bid an emotional farewell to college football, ending turmoil over
recruiting violations and the arrests of five players on rape,
shooting and drug charges.
   ``I finally decided the time has come for new leadership,''
Switzer said Monday. ``I will never coach at another institution. I
will never coach at another college level. I promise you that.''
   His resignation ended a 16-year career in which he brought the
Sooners three national titles and established the fourth best
all-time winning percentage.
   Officials scheduled a news conference today to name a successor.
   Gov. Henry Bellmon issued a statement praising Switzer for
posting ``an unparalleled record of success in college football
history.''
   Switzer, 52, had been under pressure since the school's football
program was placed on three years' probation by the National
Collegiate Athletics Association in December and after five players
were charged with felonies.
   One player was charged with wounding another in a dormitory
shooting, three players were charged with raping a woman in a
dormitory and one player was charged with conspiracy to distribute
cocaine.
   The state's three largest newspapers and the school's student
paper had called for Switzer's resignation, and the 1949 team
canceled a 40-year reunion because of the problems.
   
   ``It's no fun anymore. I'm drained. I don't have the energy level
to compete in this arena today,'' said Switzer, who has complained
recently about the impact of drugs on college athletics.
   Switzer also said he was frustrated by NCAA rules that do not
``recognize the financial needs of young athletes.
   ``We have created a system that does not permit me or the program
to buy a pair of shoes or a decent coat for a player whose family
can't afford these basic necessities.
   ``How can any coach stick to these rules when a young man's
father dies many miles away and the son has no money for a plane
ticket home to the funeral?''
   Switzer finished with a 157-29-4 record, an .844 winning
percentage. His teams won national championships in 1974, 1975 and
1985.
</TEXT>
