<DOCNO> AP890620-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0530EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AMAConvention     06-20 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AMA Convention,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMA Urged to Back Mandatory Cholesterol Labels on Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food labels would be required to include the
product's cholesterol content, caloric value and the specific source
of all vegetable oils used under a proposal presented to the
American Medical Association.
   The plan, offered by California delegates to the AMA's annual
policymaking convention, also would mandate saturated fat content
listings on labels. Cholesterol and such fats have been linked to
cardiovascular problems.
   A related resolution presented Monday asked the association to
seek truthful labeling of food products, along with warnings
regarding sodium, cholesterol and the additive content of packaged
food products.
   The AMA would call upon the Federal Trade Commission to
investigate the advertising practices of food manufacturers who
present their products as low in sodium or cholesterol under the
second plan, submitted by Dr. Louis F. Alfano, a delegate from the
American Society of Abdominal Surgeons.
   Both resolutions were referred to an AMA committee that was to
vote on whether to recommend that the association's House of
Delegates adopt them as policy.
   A critic said the measures were vague and would provide useless
and misleading information to millions of people over age 60 whose
cholesterol levels cannot be altered by what they eat.
   But supporters say many other consumers would be well-served by
such labeling.
   ``Health conscious consumers are often misled by the advertising
and labeling of common food products such as canned soups labeled as
`low sodium' which contain a substantial sodium content but are only
lower in sodium than the manfacturer's regular line of soups,''
Alfano said.
   The AMA can clear up the confusion by asking the U.S. Food and
Drug Administration to assist the consumer by requiring more
specific food labeling, he told committee members.
   Dr. Arnold Briet, an alternate delegate, presented the California
plan and said he supported Alfano's resolution.
   Cholesterol is a waxy substance that can contribute to clogged
arteries and heart disease, depending on what type of fatty proteins
carry it through the blood.
   It is produced naturally in the body and develops from eating
food with saturated fats or pure cholesterol, such as eggs, butter
and animal fat.
   The FDA has implemented labeling standards that allow foods to be
billed as cholesterol-reduced even though they still have large
amounts of cholesterol, Briet said.
   ``Nowhere do they require the source of the oils to be labeled,''
he said.
   Some plant fats, such as coconut and palm oils, contain high
amounts of saturated fatty acids that can help cholesterol form, and
food manufacturers like Nabisco Brands Inc. and Quaker Oats Co. have
taken steps to remove such oils from their products.
   Dr. Henry Mineur, an internist and delegate from New Jersey,
noted that there is an ongoing debate over so-called ``good'' and
``bad'' cholesterol. He said the proposals would be useless unless
they called for labels to differentiate between the two.
   ``Quit this damn hype'' that all types of cholesterol are bad for
everybody, Mineur told the committee.
   ``Bad'' cholesterol is carried through the bloodstream by
low-density lipoproteins linked to the buildup of harmful deposits
in the arteries.
   ``Good'' cholesterol is carried by high-density lipoproteins that
researchers believe suck up excess cholesterol in the bloodstream.
   Furthermore, Mineur argued, reducing cholesterol consumption is
only useful for those under age 60. There's no evidence that people
older than that can lower their risk of heart disease by altering
their intake of fats, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CustomsInvestigation     06-20 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Customs Investigation,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Investigation Targets U.S. Customs Auctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEAUMONT, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company handling auctions for the
federal government is under investigation for the loss of millions
of dollars in profits, reports said.
   An investigation by federal authorities centers on allegations
that Northrop Worldwide Aircraft Services Inc. took auction profits
through bill padding and fraud, NBC News reported Monday evening.
   The Crescent City, Calif.-based company has a contract with the
U.S. Customs Service to recover, maintain and sell seized or
forfeited personal property, usually through auctions.
   U.S. Attorney Bob Wortham is presenting his findings to a federal
grand jury here, The Beaumont Enterprise reported.
   Wortham said the Department of Justice prohibited him from
discussing any investigation.
   Northrop spokesman Tony Canpafio said the company is working with
the government in the investigation.
   ``We've been subpoenaed and we've provided documents,'' Canpafio
said.
   First word on the investigation was in April at a hearing before
a U.S. House Ways and Means Committee subcommittee chaired by Rep.
J.J. Pickle, D-Texas.
   Pickle said lax accounting controls account for the loss of
millions of dollars in the Customs' auctions. In fiscal 1988,
Customs agents made more than 53,000 property seizures with a
domestic value of about $1.1 billion.
   The investigation began after area banker George Talbert
complained of fees charged by Northrop to sell a vehicle seized in a
drug-related arrest in Lumberton in 1987.
   The First State Bank of Lumberton had a lien of $4,700 to $5,000
on the Chevrolet Suburban, Talbert said. Talbert, who worked at the
bank, said Customs offered to buy the car for $4,500 but later told
him it would be auctioned and money left after expenses would go to
the bank.
   Customs estimated the vehicle's value at about $8,500. Northrop
auctioned it in Houston for $4,300, and charged $700 to tow the
vehicle 90 miles to the auction and a $1,400 commission. The bank
was left with about $1,900.
   ``I was mad,'' Talbert said. ``I wrote to the company, asking for
a detailed statement of their expenses.''
   Talbert also wrote Wortham. After Wortham's office investigated
the sale, the company sent the bank an additional $1,000, he said.
   The investigation widened in January when authorities obtained a
search warrant for Northrop's Lawton, Okla., offices to obtain
transcripts on all Customs auctions for the past three years.
   In affidavits, Customs agents said Northrop employees contended
the company billed Customs for maintaining and storing seized
property for as long as three months after the property was disposed.
   Agents also reported Northrop withheld information stored in one
computer when agents served a subpoena issued by a grand jury in
Beaumont requesting all business records concerning Northrop's
contract with Customs.
   Its commissioner, William Von Raab, said the agency loses money
on its auctions because Customs warehouses store more than just
fancy cars and boats.
   ``When you lump all of our forfeitures together including those
made let's say of fruit that doesn't meet FDA (Food and Drug
Administration) rules or blue jeans that violate a quota or mismark,
then we don't make a profit,'' he said.
   Some in Congress say there is no excuse for Customs to lose money
on their auctions, especially when the seized property is acquired
at no cost.
   ``Either the auctions are rigged or else they're being very
poorly run,'' said Rep. Richard Schulze, R-Pa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0051 </DOCNO>
