<FIRST>r p PM-WrightSeat     06-20 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Seat,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Senator Declines Run for Wright's Seat, Says Wright Should
Keep It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man mentioned as Jim Wright's most
likely congressional successor urged the former House speaker to try
to retain his seat, saying he was still the best representative for
the district.
   ``Nobody has a right to tell the people of Fort Worth and this
community who their congressman ought to be,'' state Sen. Hugh
Parmer told reporters Monday.
   ``The people of this community ought to make that choice. And I
am persuaded, having talked to them, that if they have that option
they will overwhelmingly re-elect Jim Wright as the congressman from
the 12th District.'' Parmer said his fellow Fort Worth Democrat and
longtime friend either should remain in Congress or, if he fulfills
his promise to resign, run again for the seat in a special election.
   About 30 supporters at a Saturday breakfast urged Wright to put
his name on the ballot in a special election for the 12th District
seat, the Fort Worth Star-Telegram reported today.
   The newspaper said Wright neither encouraged nor discouraged the
effort to draft him but told supporters he ``would think about
running,'' according to some who were at the meeting.
   Wright spokesman Mark Johnson said the congressman was gratified
by supporters' suggestions, but ``is not encouraging this and his
plans have not changed.''
   Wright resigned May 31 as speaker and said he'd give up his House
seat by the end of June to end a furor over allegations he violated
House ethics rules.
   ``He is proceeding with the transition'' into private life by the
end of June, Johnson said, though no resignation date has been set.
   Parmer had been mentioned most often as the likeliest Democrat to
run for the post Wright has held since 1954.
   But at a news conference in Austin earlier Monday, Parmer said he
was sticking with his announced plan to challenge Republican U.S.
Sen. Phil Gramm in 1990. Parmer waited for his afternoon appearance
at Fort Worth's Meacham Field airport to throw his support behind
Wright.
   ``The vast majority of people in Fort Worth believe that while
Jim may have made some mistakes of judgment, as Jim has admitted ...
it did not warrant the kind of penalty or price that he is talking
about paying,'' he said.
   Asked whether Wright still planned to leave office, Parmer said,
``I would say that he said neither yes, nor no. He simply listened
to what I had to say.''
</TEXT>
