<FIRST>r a PM-NightStalker     06-20 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Night Stalker,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Rests in Night Stalker Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents of 3rd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for Richard Ramirez rested their
case after calling 35 witnesses but passing up the chance to have
the defendant testify in the 5-month-old ``Night Stalker'' murder
trial.
   Defense attorney Ray Clark said Monday the decision on whether to
testify was left to Ramirez and he decided not to take the witness
stand.
   The 29-year-old drifter from El Paso, Texas, is charged with 13
murders and 30 related felonies in a crime wave that terrorized
California during the summer of 1985. Pentagrams, a symbol of devil
worship, were found at some murder scenes and the assailant gouged
out the eyes of one victim.
   Ramirez is a self-proclaimed devil worshiper who once shouted
``Hail Satan'' in court. A jailer testified that he used his own
blood to draw a pentagram on the floor of his cell.
   During the defense's month-long presentation, attorneys called
witnesses who gave Ramirez alibis for some of the killings. Most
notably, Ramirez' father testified that the defendant was home in El
Paso when two of the slayings occurred.
   The defense also entered 65 pieces of evidence and attacked the
credibility of witnesses who identified Ramirez as the shaggy haired
killer who entered homes through unlocked windows and doors.
   Deputy District Attorney P. Philip Halpin said he planned to
begin presenting rebuttal witnesses today. He said his rebuttal
should take about a week. The prosecution has presented 137
witnesses and 521 pieces of evidence.
   Clark said it was unlikely the defense would call any more
witnesses after rebuttal.
   Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan scheduled final arguments to
begin July 10, after the jury takes a week vacation.
   The case appears headed for a conclusion far sooner than the two
years anticipated when the trial began.
   But Halpin said he was still disturbed by the four years that
have elapsed since Ramirez was arrested. The trial followed years of
pretrial motions and a lengthy preliminary hearing.
   ``We have not done this efficiently,'' Halpin said, adding he
hoped the court system would learn from the case that ``we can't
take forever to try these cases.''
</TEXT>
