<FIRST>r i PM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru a0497 06-20 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0497,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma Changes Name, Reopens Schools</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to CORRECT that `socialist' dropped from
name last September. Picks up 13th pvs, `The act ...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma has officially changed its name in
English to the Union of Myanmar and renamed the capital of Rangoon
to Yangon, the state-run Working People's Daily said.
   Also Monday, the military government tightened controls on
political literature and reopened primary schools nationwide, one
year after all classrooms were closed in the wake of pro-democracy
demonstrations.
   The government said it would reopen junior high schools, high
schools and universities but has not given specific dates.
   In the law changing Burma's name, the nationality _ Burmese _
also was changed to Myanmar. The word for Burma and Burmese in the
Burmese language are both pronounced Myanmar.
   The names of states, towns and other geographical sites are to be
written in English according to the Burmese pronunciation, the law
says. Rangoon, for example, is to be written as Yangon, which is the
Burmese pronunciation of the capital.
   The military rulers who seized power in September while brutally
putting down the popular uprising for democratic reforms had already
dropped the term ``Socialist Republic,'' calling the country the
Union of Burma in English.
   The move was an apparent attempt to appease a populace angered by
a quarter century of ruinous socialist policies.
   The latest change in the country's name, government officials
say, is to better reflect Burma's ethnic diversity. The term Burma
connotes Burman _ the dominant race in the country _ to the
exclusion of ethnic minorities.
   Several minority groups have been fighting for greater autonomy
from the central government for four decades.
   The government on Monday increased penalties against violators of
a 1962 law on publications, increasing maximum prison terms from
three to seven years and fines from $320 to $4,800 for those who
publish material without proper registration.
   The act says printing presses must be registered with authorities
and forbids falsification of facts in declarations by printers and
publishers.
   Saw Muang's military council has promised general elections next
year and allowed the formation of opposition political parties, and
many of the 200 parties have published anti-government pamphlets
without official permission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
