<FIRST>r a PM-SlayingsTape     06-20 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Slayings Tape,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Hears Tape from Double Homicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors in the trial of a man charged with stabbing
his wife to death heard a tape recording of the woman's plea for
help, followed by her husband telling her she was ``bleeding just
like a stuck hog.''
   Alfred Lavers, 48, is charged with murder in the May 13, 1988,
stabbing deaths of his wife, Mary, and 11-year-old stepdaughter,
Jennifer Burns.
   The tape played Monday was found by police in a recorder under
pillows in the stepdaughter's room. It contained a 90-minute
recording of the domestic dispute that culminated in Mrs. Lavers'
terrifying screams.
   ``I'm dying,'' Mrs. Lavers was heard saying, just after she
allegedly was stabbed by her husband.
   ``I know you are,'' he said.
   ``Please help me,'' she said.
   ``You're bleeding just like a stuck hog. I love you so much,'' he
said.
   The victims' relatives sat fighting back emotion in the front row
of the spectators' section as the tape was played. An elderly woman
later identified as one of Mrs. Lavers' relatives broke down in
tears and was led out.
   There was no discernible reaction by jurors, who followed the
tape with a transcript.
   Lavers, 48, voluntarily removed himself from the Maricopa County
Superior courtroom while the tape was played.
   He returned for the defense portion of the case, in which public
defender Roland Steinle called only one witness _ a police officer
who said Lavers appeared ``out of it'' when he was arrested and
booked.
   Steinle is attempting to show that Lavers was intoxicated when he
stabbed the women, acted without premeditation and should be found
guilty of a lesser crime.
   The trial resumes Wednesday.
</TEXT>
