<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain in Southeast; Flash Flood Warnings in Five States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms produced more heavy rain in sections of
the Southeast, and flash flood watches remained in effect today for
parts of Alabama, Georgia, North Carolina, Ohio and Pennsylvania.
   About 1{ inches of rain fell in 45 minutes at Mount Sterling,
Ky., flooding streets and basements and backing up sewers, and more
than three-quarters of an inch fell in an hour at Louisville, Ky.
   On Monday, Alabama farmers moved livestock to higher ground and
riverfront homeowners set out sandbags as weather officials warned
of more rainfall and the expected cresting of the Alabama and
Tallapoosa rivers.
   A storm that dumped more than an inch of rain an hour in east
Alabama flushed creeks across rural roads Monday and forced
officials to open rarely used flood gates on Lake Martin.
   In Kentucky, Gov. Wallace Wilkinson toured flood-damaged eastern
sections of the state and predicted federal officials would declare
the area a disaster. State officials said damage from torrential
rains that fell last week was in the millions of dollars.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered across western
portions of the northern Plains. Winds gusted to 60 mph in Miles
City, Mont. Thunderstorms erupted Monday night across the eastern
slopes of the Rockies, where winds gusted to 60 mph at Vedauwoo, Wyo.
   Other thunderstorms were scattered from north-central Nebraska
into the northern Plains, and light rain dampened the Pacific
Northwest.
   Intense heat in the Southwest contributed to the heat stroke
death of a 5-year-old girl who became locked in a car trunk in her
driveway Sunday as the outdoor temperature climbed to 104 degrees,
police said. Authorities said the death appears to be an accident.
   Today's forecast calls for numerous showers and thunderstorms
from the central Gulf Coast through much of the Ohio Valley, and in
the Middle Atlantic and Southeast states; showers and a few
thunderstorms scattered from Washington across central Montana; and
widely scattered showers and thunderstorms mainly in the higher
elevations of the northern and central Rockies.
   Predicted highs: in the 70s and 80s east of the Mississippi
River, and from the central and northern coasts of California across
northern Nevada to eastern Montana; the 60s over the Pacific
Northwest and Idaho; the 90s over the central Rockies, the Plains
and much of the Mississippi Valley; and over 100 degrees in the
central Plains, and from the Desert Southwest to southwest Texas.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 41 degrees at Missoula,
Mont., to 93 degrees at Valentine, Neb., Las Vegas, and Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 68 rain; Boston 62 foggy; Buffalo 63 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C., 71 cloudy; Cincinnati 67 foggy; Cleveland 63
cloudy; Detroit 64 foggy; Miami 80 fair; New York 67 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 69 foggy; Pittsburgh 66 showers; Portland, Maine, 56
foggy; Washington 71 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 80 windy; Chicago 62 foggy; Dallas-Fort Worth
75 fair; Denver 74 partly cloudy; Des Moines 67 fair; Indianapolis
67 foggy; Kansas City 68 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 71 fair;
Nashville 68 partly cloudy; New Orleans 70 partly cloudy; St. Louis
71 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 84 partly cloudy; Anchorage 59 fair; Los
Angeles 64 fair; Salt Lake City 69 partly cloudy; San Diego 69
cloudy; San Francisco 53 windy; Seattle 51 showers.
   _Canada: Montreal 61 partly cloudy; Toronto 63 showers.
</TEXT>
