<DOCNO> AP890620-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PhiladelphiatoPhiladelphia     06-20 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philadelphia to Philadelphia,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northerners Head South to Mark Civil Rights Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Northerners have embarked on a
pilgrimage to one of the shrines of the civil rights movement of the
1960s to commemorate the slayings of three young men in
Philadelphia, Miss.
   A 13-bus convoy carrying about 500 Northerners left here Monday
for ceremonies marking the 25th anniversary of the slayings.
   ``I expect to learn about how they got involved, why they got
involved,'' said Craig Johnson, 21, an Antioch College student who
is working as a summer intern in Philadelphia city government. ``It
will help us to appreciate what they endured.''
   The buses, including three from New York City, were scheduled to
arrive today in Meridian, Miss., near the small town of
Philadelphia, where ceremonies Wednesday will honor James Earl
Chaney, Andrew Goodman and Michael Schwerner.
   The three men were shot to death June 21, 1964, after they had
gone to inspect a church burned by the Ku Klux Klan. Their bodies
were found 44 days later in an earthen dam.
   ``It is important to commemorate the sacrifices that were made in
the civil rights movement,'' said Larry Pitt, 37. The Philadelphia,
Pa., attorney came up with the idea for the convoy last winter after
watching the movie ``Mississippi Burning,'' a dramatization of the
slayings and the resulting investigation.
   ``It gives us the opportunity to bring into the consciousness of
the whole country the need for a continuing commitment to civil
rights,'' Pitt said.
   Seven men eventually were convicted in federal court of violating
the three men's civil rights. Another defendant pleaded guilty,
eight were acquitted and the cases against the three others ended in
mistrials. Murder charges were dropped in state court.
   The Philadelphia to Philadelphia Project is sponsored by the
Chaney, Goodman, Schwerner Memorial Coalition, which is co-chaired
in Pennsylvania by Mayor W. Wilson Goode, U.S. Rep. William H. Gray
III, Pitt and seven others, and in Mississippi by Secretary of State
Dick Mopus.
   Goode, the first black mayor of the nation's fifth-largest city,
will fly to Mississippi with about 150 people Wednesday to address a
``commemoration of the past'' at Mount Zion Methodist Church in
Philadelphia.
   James Farmer, former executive director of the Congress of Racial
Equality, and members of the victims' families also will speak.
   The Pennsylvania convoy will leave Mississippi on Thursday as
will a south-to-north convoy that will stop in Washington for
meetings with members of Congress and a rally at the Capitol Friday.
The convoy will go to New York Saturday for a ceremony at St. John
the Divine Church.
   Several participants said the trip will provide valuable insight.
   ``To know where you're going, you've got to know where you came
from,'' said Jack Franklin, 67, a curator at the Afro-American
Historical and Cultural Museum in Philadelphia, Pa.
   He said he was struck by the small proportion of whites boarding
the buses in Pennsylvania.
   ``When Martin Luther King marched, there was 25 to 30 percent
whites,'' he said. ``Here, it's maybe 1 percent. That will give you
something to think about. That will give you an idea where the
country is headed. I'm not being bitter. I'm just telling you the
truth.''
   But Pitt, the organizer, said he hoped the trip would demonstrate
that the civil rights legacy belongs to all Americans.
   ``The lessons we intend to present this week are lessons which
the country must learn, which is that the price of liberty is
eternal vigilance, that the civil rights movement, though it was
focusing on the rights of blacks, was an American movement, a
patriotic movement.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0060 </DOCNO>
