<FIRST>r i PM-Afghan-USPhotographer     06-20 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghan-US Photographer,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Say Afghan Government Holding American Photographer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan government forces have seized
an American free-lance photographer who was traveling with Moslem
guerrillas on assignment for Life magazine, resistance sources say.
   He is the first American believed captured by Afghans during the
civil war.
   Guerrillas sources identified him Monday as Tony O'Brien, 42, a
photographer from Santa Fe, N.M. He had been covering the Afghan war
based in the Pakistan frontier city of Peshawar.
   The Afghan government did not confirm the arrest immediately.
   U.S. Embassy officials in Pakistan cited the U.S. Privacy Act and
said they could not comment on such a capture.
   O'Brien was seized last Wednesday in Kabul, the Afghan capital,
guerrilla sources in Pakistan said on condition of anonymity. He is
being held in Kabul and is reported in good condition, they said.
   At least three Western correspondents and two foreign aid workers
have been captured in the past while traveling with the guerrillas.
All were later released unharmed.
   O'Brien had made several forays into Afghanistan with the
guerrillas. His photographs have appeared in major U.S.
publications, including The New York Times and Time magazine.
   ``He had snuck into the country disguised as a Moslem guerrilla.
I saw photos of him in that garb,'' said free-lance writer William
Hart, who has known O'Brien for 15 years.
</TEXT>
