<FIRST>r a PM-SubAccident     06-20 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sub Accident,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sub Cuts Fishing Net Two Days After Sinking Tug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear submarine that pulled a tugboat
under, killing a crewman, cut a fishing boat's net two days later,
the Navy said.
   The USS Houston sliced the net Friday night outside Los Angeles
Harbor as the craft headed home on the surface for San Diego after
taking part in filming of the movie ``The Hunt for Red October,''
said Lt. Sonja Hedley, a Navy spokeswoman.
   Hedley would not give the sub's precise location but said the
fishing boat ``was in the traffic lane you shouldn't be in ...
trawling.''
   However, she added: ``If we cut his net, we'll pay for his net
and that's all there is to it. People cross fishing nets like that
and clip them all the time.''
   Capt. James C. Card, commander of the Coast Guard's Marine Safety
Office, said the fisherman's description of his location would have
placed the trawler in a legal spot just outside the shipping
channels.
   On Wednesday, the fast-attack sub snagged a tow cable and pulled
a tugboat to the ocean bottom, killing a tug pilot.
   John M. Emirzian, skipper of the 33-foot trawler, said the sub
cut a new $3,800 net and cost him a two-day catch.
   ``There was a million deck lights on,'' he said. ``It looked like
Chicago out there. All they had to do was look.''
