<DOCNO> AP890620-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0856EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChildTestimony     06-20 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Testimony,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court: Videotape-Testimony Law Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS CONRAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Illinois Supreme Court has struck
down a law allowing videotaped testimony by child victims of sexual
abuse.
   The court Monday declared the 1987 law unconstitutional because
it deprives the accused of the right to confront their accusers at
trial.
   The law, enacted by the Legislature over Gov. James R. Thompson's
veto, allows the defense to cross-examine the child witness about
the videotaped testimony during the trial but not during the taping
itself.
   ``Cross-examination often depends for its effectiveness on the
ability of counsel to punch holes in a witness' testimony at just
the right time, in just the right way,'' said Justice John Stamos,
citing a 1988 U.S. Supreme Court ruling in a case from Iowa.
   Illinois is one of several states that have adopted so-called
``child shield'' laws intended to protect young victims of sexual
abuse from the trauma of testifying in open court and to minimize
their fright and confusion.
   The law applied only to certain sexual offenses committed against
a child 12 or younger, but in declaring it unconstitutional the
justices said they were worried it would be expanded to include the
elderly or handicapped.
   In vetoing it, the governor predicted it would be declared
unconstitutional.
   Last year, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of an
Iowa man who was made to testify behind a one-way screen to prevent
his accusers from seeing him. He had been found guilty of molesting
two 13-year-old girls.
   The high court said the man's rights to a fair trial and to
confront his accusers appeared to have been violated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Greece     06-20 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitsotakis Given Three Days to Form Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative leader Constantine Mitsotakis
today was given three days to form a new government, and a leftist
alliance rejected his offer to join a coalition.
   Mitsotakis' center-right New Democracy Party finished first in
Sunday's elections, defeating Premier Andreas Papandreou's
Panhellenic Socialist Movement. But New Democracy failed to win a
majority needed to govern.
   President Christos Sartzetakison, as outlined by the
constitution, today gave Mitsotakis three days to form a governing
coalition. If he is unable to form a government, Papandreou's party
will be given the same opportunity.
   The Coalition of Left and Progress, a leftist-communist coalition
that finished third, said it would consider a governing coalition
with Papandreou's party if the premier resigned as party leader. But
the leftists rejected an offer from Mitsotakis to form a new
government.
   Mitsotakis refused to say what he planned to do following the
rejection of his coalition offer.
   If neither of the top two finishers in the election can form a
government, the president will ask the third place Coalition of Left
and Progress to form a government.
   If all three fail, the president appoints a caretaker government
to prepare for new elections.
   The Panhellenic Socialist Movement has hinted it would seek to
lead a leftist coalition if it was offered the exploratory mandate.
   New Democracy gained 44.37 percent of Sunday's vote and 144
seats, seven short of a majority in the 300-member Parliament.
Papandreou's party took 39 percent and 125 seats. The Coalition of
Left and Progress, an alliance of Communist and Greek Left parties,
received 13 percent and 29 seats.
   On Monday, Mitstotakis asked the leftist alliance to join him in
an interim government with a limited mandate confined to cleaning up
the financial scandals that have tainted the Papandreou government.
   Mitsotakis said the partnership would last ``only a few months,''
until those guilty of involvement in the scandals were punished.
Then he would call new elections.
   ``I hope that all other parties will do all in their power to
prevent the scandals from being written off,'' Mitsotakis said.
   But Harilaos Florakis, the leader of the Greek Communist Party
and president of the leftist alliance, said his group wants to form
a leftist government that would exclude people tainted by scandal.
   Florakis said it would consider forming a government with the
Panhellenic Socialist Movement if Papandreou, who has ruled since
1981, resigned as its leader.
   Papandreou and senior members of his party have been accused of
being involved in the $200 million fraud, forgery and embezzlement
scheme at the Bank of Crete. George Koskotas, the owner of the bank,
is detained in prison in the United States pending the hearing of an
extradition request by the Greek government.
   The socialsts have also been accused of widespread corruption and
of involvement in a series of arms scandals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
