<FIRST>r a PM-FlatsWater     06-20 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flats Water,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Of Flats Water Challenged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Denver suburbs downstream from
Rocky Flats want the government to cover the cost of testing their
drinking water and stopping the flow of water from the weapons plant
into their reservoirs.
   Officials from Broomfield, Westminster, Thornton and Northglenn
met on Monday with Ed Goldberg, the Department of Energy's top
official at Rocky Flats, to press their concerns. The session was
organized by U.S. Rep. David Skaggs.
   ``Local governments shouldn't suffer any additional costs from
living downstream from Rocky Flats,'' said Skaggs, a Democrat.
   Goldberg noted that Skaggs and his congressional colleagues have
more say than he does over whether the suburbs get reimbursed.
   ``We can ask and we will ask, but it's up to Congress to
appropriate the money in the end,'' he said.
   Fears over the safety of the water surfaced earlier this month
with a U.S. Justice Department probe of alleged dumping of hazardous
wastes at Rocky Flats.
   Walnut and Woman creeks cross the site before entering the water
supplies of more than a quarter-million residents.
   Tests by the state and the four suburbs found no detectable
levels of pollutants in drinking water sources. But the suburbs said
they don't want to have to worry about the possibility of pollutants
flowing their way.
   Broomfield is digging a ditch to take Walnut Creek water around a
reservoir. A diversion of Woman Creek is under study. The creek
flows into a lake that provides drinking water to Westminster,
Thornton and Northglenn.
</TEXT>
