<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SteelPlantCleanup     06-20 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Plant Cleanup,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bethlehem Steel, Maryland Agree on $92 Million Cleanup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bethlehem Steel Corp. has agreed to spend $92
million over five years to curb toxic releases from a plant that has
piled up $150,000 in pollution fines over the past year.
   The agreement, announced Monday, expands on a $15.2 million air
pollution cleanup promised by the steelmaker in 1987.
   Officials said that the agreement, the largest ever negotiated by
the state with an industrial polluter, is legally binding and that
Bethlehem could be fined more than $100,000 for failing to maintain
the cleanup schedule.
   Bethlehem Steel's Sparrows Point complex at Baltimore Harbor
employs 8,000 workers and produces steel for ships, bridges,
buildings, autos and appliances.
   The plant is the third-largest source of cancer-causing chemicals
in Maryland and one of the state's leading industrial sources of
sulfur dioxide emissions, which have taken the principal blame for
acid rain.
   Buoyed by its first profitable year since 1981, Bethlehem pledged
in 1987 to reduce emissions. The new agreement calls for more
extensive measures, including a $40 million modernization of a
chemical recovery plant to reduce emissions of sulfur dioxide and
toxic pollutants, mainly benzene and hydrogen cyanide.
   Benzene can cause leukemia and other cancers, anemia and other
health problems. Hydrogen cyanide can kill if inhaled in high
concentrations.
   Bethlehem also promised to repair leaking walls and flues at a
cost of $24 million to cut down on the black smoke belching from
three smokestacks.
   By 1994, the cleanup should result in reductions of 54 percent in
particulates, 67 percent in sulfur dioxide, 50 percent in volatile
organic compounds that create ozone, and 30 percent in benzene,
officials said.
</TEXT>
