<FIRST>r a PM-CollegeCorner     06-20 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-College Corner,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Magistrate Temporarily Preserves College Corner School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school that has straddled the Indiana-Ohio
border for nearly 100 years, a center stripe in the gymnasium
marking the state line, must continue to accept students from both
states, a U.S. magistrate said.
   Magistrate Michael Merz on Monday blocked an attempt by Indiana
officials to close Union School to Ohio students and force them to
attend another school miles from home.
   Merz's preliminary injunction forces the Union County (Ind.)
School Corp. to abide by a 1964 court order that bars it from
altering operation of the school with the College Corner (Ohio)
school board without consent of both boards.
   ``While the joint operation may be cumbersome, it is not
impossibly so and has worked for almost 100 years,'' Merz wrote.
``It is needed to provide a school for the children of College
Corner. It is needed to uphold the obligation of defendants to obey
their own solemn undertakings and the judgment of this court.''
   The school was built by the Ohio and Indiana districts so that
children from either state could attend.
   Last week, Richard Amick, superintendent of the Union County
corporation, said the Indiana board has voted to sever its
relationship with the College Corner board because of conflicting
state laws that jeopardize state money for Indiana students. He also
cited a poor relationship with members of the College Corner board.
   About 280 Indiana students attend Union School, comprising about
75 percent of the enrollment.
   College Corner officials say that without the arrangement, Ohio
pupils will be forced to attend school miles away because the
community doesn't have enough students to operate its own school.
</TEXT>
