<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0541 06-20 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0541,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Palestinians Arrested in Deadly Encounter With Settler</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with settler firing on Arabs in
Tel Aviv; picks up 6th graf pvs, `Another Palestinian...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Palestinians said they met a Jewish
settler who was hiking in the occupied West Bank, chatted with him,
posed for a picture and then stabbed him to death, Israeli officials
said today.
   The men were arrested during the night by agents of the Shin Bet
security service in the death Saturday of Frederick Steven
Rosenfeld, 48, of the West Bank settlement of Ariel, the officials
said. They insisted on anonymity.
   Shortly after Rosenfeld's funeral service in Ariel, a settler
opened fire with an Uzi submachine gun on a group of Arabs waiting
at major intersection near Tel Aviv, said police spokeswoman Dalia
Gilad.
   Two Palestinians were wounded, one of them seriously, she said.
The assailant was apprehended after being chased by police and
residents. Police had no motive for the attack.
   The army blew up the homes of the suspects in Rosenfeld's
slaying, who are from the nearby village of Burkin, Israel radio
said. Their names were not released.
   Also today, Fahad Fawzi Madi, a 27-year-old Palestinian suspected
of collaborating with Israel, was found beaten and stabbed to death
in the town of Khan Yunis in the occupied Gaza Strip, Arab and
Israeli news reports said.
   Another Palestinian, Samir Mohammed Antiz, 19, was found dead in
his tent at the Ketziot detention center in the Negev desert, where
he had been held without charge since February, an army spokesman
said.
   Israel radio said Antiz apparently was killed by fellow prisoners
who accused him of collaborating with the authorities.
   The army said police were investigating Madi's death and checking
reports on Antiz's death.
   Also, a 34-year-old Palestinian postal worker from the West Bank
town of Jenin was hospitalized with two broken legs and a broken arm
after he was beaten by masked Arabs who suspected him of
collaborating with Israel, Arab reports said.
   More than 50 Palestinians suspected of cooperating with Israeli
authorities have been killed since the start of the 18-month
Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule of the occupied lands.
   The deaths raised to at least 526 the number of Palestinians
killed since the revolt began. Twenty-three Israelis also have died.
   The three Palestinians accused of slaying Rosenfeld came upon the
settler Saturday while he was hiking on a barren hillside near the
Arab village of Burkin, about three miles from Ariel, the security
officials said.
   They said the Arabs, who are from Burkin, told agents during
interrogation that Rosenfeld chatted with them, took their pictures
with his camera, and asked them to take a photograph of him.
   One of them then grabbed Rosenfeld's knife and stabbed him in the
back, said the official.
   They said the three Arabs were taken to the scene today to
re-enact the slaying.
   Other Palestinian shepherds found Rosenfeld's body Sunday
morning. An empty pistol holster, two spent cartridges, a map and
binoculars were found near the body.
   There was no explanation of how the settler's gun might have been
fired.
   According to Ariel settlers, Rosenfeld was a nature lover and
apparently was mapping a hiking route for residents when he was
killed. Rosenfeld, who was raised in Washington, D.C., came to
Israel in 1968 and had lived in Ariel for 18 months. He was not
married.
   About 70,000 Jews live in 131 settlements in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, alongside 1.7 million Palestinians. Relations between
the two groups have worsened since the start of the uprising.
   Rosenfeld's death provoked public protests in Jerusalem, Tel
Aviv, and the West Bank and calls from right-wing legislators for
harsher measures to quell the Palestinian revolt.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir vowed Monday to ``uproot the
violence with an iron fist.''
   In other developments, troops used bulldozers to demolish two
houses of Palestinians suspected of throwing firebombs at military
patrols in the West Bank town of Qalqilya, army radio said.
   In Gaza City, military authorities fired the director of the
Israeli-run Shifa Hospital, accusing him of belonging to the
mainstream Fatah faction of the outlawed PLO and of maintaining
contacts with Fatah leaders in Jordan.
   Dr. Ahmed Al Yazgi denied the accusations, the Jerusalem Post
reported. Yazgi was quoted as saying he believed his activities with
Israeli peace activists had angered Israeli authorities.
</TEXT>
