<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today put off until Thursday a hearing
on Pete Rose's request to stop Baseball Commissioner A. Bartlett
Giamatti from deciding whether to ban the Cincinnati Reds manager
from the sport.
   After a hearing in his chambers, Common Pleas Judge Norbert Nadel
also said the commissioner's office agreed not to take action
against Rose until at least Sunday.
   Rose sued on Monday to block Giamatti from holding a hearing on
allegations of gambling June 26. The ballplayer contended he was
being judged by a ``prejudiced commissioner.''
   The lawsuit also confirmed for the first time that Ronald Peters,
who claims he is Rose's former bookmaker, accused Rose of betting on
Reds games. If the allegations prove true, Giamatti could ban Rose
from baseball for life.
   Giamatti said in a statement Monday that his lawyers had reviewed
the court papers ``advised me that Mr. Rose's lawsuit is wholly
without merit.''
   ``I trust the court will permit me to proceed with my hearing,''
he said.
