<SECOND>AM-BRF--Career Suspect,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Seeking Police Job Jailed for Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALATKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who walked into a police station to
ask about a career in law enforcement was arrested for allegedly
robbing a convenience store a few minutes earlier.
   A police dispatcher took a call about a robbery only a few blocks
away as she chatted with David Ferrell Marshall, 25.
   While police gathered information on the robbery, Marshall was
referred to Chief Dan Thies to discuss his qualifications.
   As he spoke with Marshall, Thies received a phone call from a
lieutenant with a description of the robbery suspect. The suspect
wore a pair of pink-and-gray shorts matching those worn by Marshall.
   ``The lieutenant on the phone says, `Does that look familiar to
you?' and I'm sitting here looking at the guy,'' Thies recalled
Monday.
   He escorted Marshall to the lobby as the store clerk was brought
into the station.
   ``That's him,'' she said, pointing to Marshall.
   Marshall was arrested on a charge of strong-armed robbery and
violation of probation. He was held in the Putnam County Jail.
   ``I didn't give him an application,'' Thies said.
