<FIRST>r a AM-MovieScheme     06-20 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Movie Scheme,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prisoner to Write Letters of Apology for Movie Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood hopefuls duped into sending
photographs to a prison will get them back, along with a letter of
apology from the inmate who conducted a movie-recruitment scheme
from his cell, a prison investigator said.
   The scheme came to light two weeks ago when authorities in
southwest Alabama warned residents that telephone calls about a
possible filming by Paramount Pictures were untrue.
   The calls were made by inmate James Mills, said Bill Dury, a
prison investigator at Staunton Correctional Center in Staunton, Va.
Mills, 29, is serving nine years there for attempted larceny.
   ``He admitted the whole thing,'' Dury said in a telephone
interview Monday. ``I think it was kind of an ego-satisfying thing
to have these beautiful young women sending photographs to him.''
   Mills called high school students in Alabama, West Virginia,
South Carolina and Arizona about being in a movie, Dury said.
Inmates routinely are allowed only collect phone calls; Dury
declined to say how Mills bypassed the prison's phone system.
   The Hollywood hopefuls mailed photos of themselves to Mills, who
used several aliases, Dury said. A search of his cell last week
recovered 15 or 20 photos from six or seven people. None of the
subjects was nude.
   Mills had tried, however, to obtain nude photos of students,
Mobile County investigators said last week.
   Dury said there was no evidence that Mills was selling or trading
the photos. He described the photos as portrait-type pictures from
high school.
   ``One family did send photographs in bikinis. It appeared to be
an older woman and two young girls,'' Dury said.
   No charges were immediately filed against Mills, Dury said.
Mobile County authorities asked federal officials to investigate,
since the scheme crossed state lines.
</TEXT>
