<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-YellowstoneExhibit     06-20 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yellowstone Exhibit,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Park Pulls Together a Fire Exhibit to Meet Public Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yellowstone has added an
exhibit on the devastating fires of 1988, intended to help visitors
drive through the park's charred areas _ as well as the unscarred
half _ with more understanding.
   ``I hope people will learn enough to have a choice of what they
think,'' said Betty Knight, a park naturalist. ``They still might be
mad, but that's their choice.''
   Knight directed planning and construction of the exhibit, which
opened Saturday in the visitors center at Grant Village.
   The $136,000 production was an unusual crash program for the
National Park Service, which usually requires at least two years of
planning on a major exhibit, she said.
   The motivation was an unprecedented public interest, Knight said.
   ``It was a Vietnam of forest fires,'' she said. ``It was the
first time fire was brought into people's living rooms on a steady
basis.''
   The exhibit, she said, shows the short-term effects of the fires,
from five to 25 years from now, and explores the long-range future
of Yellowstone.
   The causes _ drought, lightning storms, the park's geography _
are explained, as well as recent history of fire supression that
contributed to the build-up of fuel.
   The exhibit includes murals, portraits of firefighters, a video
recouting the fury of the fires and presentations about animals.
   Grant Village survived a seige of fire in late July, although
fast-running flames came within feet of staff dormitories. Now the
area is an almost surreal scene: blackened trees interspersed with
orange lodgepole pines that are dead but still have their needles.
   Except in the badly charred stands, there is a lush carpet of
green grass growing through the soot and ash. And to the north and
east, around Yellowstone Lake, there is no evidence of the fires
that swept through half the 2.2 million acre park.
   Knight, 44, typifies those who believe the fires were, in
historical terms, good for the country's first national park, with
long-term benefits for vegetation and wildlife.
   The exhibit does not, however, address the decision to allow many
fires to burn naturally until late July, or refer to disputes
between firefighters and park rangers that hampered some efforts to
quell the flames until it was too late.
   ``We're not touching policy,'' said Knight, who has been with the
park service for 22 years. ``We're trying to get across that all of
Yellowstone is not the same, that it won't recover the same.''
   The exhibit she coordinated will take most visitors about 20
minutes to tour, although Knight said there is enough information
available for extremely interested tourists to spend more than two
hours.
   Design costs ran $16,000 and production $120,000, Knight said,
not including the salaries and overtime required.
   The exhibit closes with writings by Bob Marshall, a
conservationist who remarked in 1927 that in fire-blackened forests,
``There were some scenes of desolation that pretty nearly drive an
unimaginative person crazy.''
   Marshall concluded that ``an optimist could go surging through
that blackened, misshapened world rejoicing because the forest will
look just as beautiful as before _ in two or three centuries.''
   Knight, like most other park employees, takes Marshall's view.
   ``It's always a changing park,'' she said. ``It wasn't the same
park in 1988 as it was in 1953 when I first saw it.
   ``The difference, obviously, is that this change is much more
dramatic.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
