<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Posters Bjt   06-20 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Posters, Bjt,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Price of Pluralism: Cleaning Up From Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With an exuberance matched only by the
novelty of their new democratic parliamentary elections, Poles
plastered campaign posters across the country over the last month.
   Now the time has come to pay the price of pluralism: cleaning up.
   With the signs of Poland's fledgling venture into free elections
looking a bit tattered, the question remains: Who should scrub,
scrape and wash away the campaign posters, and who should pay for it?
   An estimated 700,000 posters went up in Warsaw alone in an
astounding display of uncensored campaigning unseen in Poland during
45 years of communist rule.
   That represented about 40 tons of paper, a significant amount in
a country where university students sometimes don't have anything
suitable on which to type their theses.
   Most of the posters came from the independent Solidarity
movement, which went on to win all but one of the 261 seats
available to opposition candidates and hand the government a
stinging rebuke in two rounds of voting that started June 4 and
ended Sunday.
   Now, however, the posters such as those featuring gallant Gary
Cooper in cowboy gear and a Solidarity button that says, ``High noon
is June 4,'' are peeling off apartment block walls.
   Rain has smeared the sentiments of support for a communist
coalition candidate whose banner hung along a main city thoroughfare.
   ``The emotions subsided, the litter remained ... Who is going to
clean it up?'' asked the daily Solidarity newspaper.
   Jan Litynski, head of the Solidarity campaign in Warsaw, promised
in the article that the union would work on the cleanup with city
authorities.
   ``But we do not have the money to hire people. We have only
debts,'' Litynski said. ``So those who were putting up the posters
for free now will to clean them off, too.''
   Another issue of the newspaper carried a call from 12-year-old
Mikolaj Bober, who put up posters all over the Zoliborz section of
Warsaw.
   ``We have to clean it up,'' he said. ``I am eager to do this ...
and I count on the help of other boys and girls.''
   The director of the Warsaw municipal cleaning enterprise, Leszek
Swierczynski, said the city will clean the sites it administers, but
building janitors, the bus and tramway services and others will have
to take care of their areas.
   ``There is quite a lot to do ... and the whole (cleanup) campaign
will surely take a lot of extra money,'' said Swierczynski, making
it clear that the expenses of Western-style electioneering were not
anticipated in his department's budget.
   ``The scale of the poster phenomenon in Warsaw is
extraordinary,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Solstice     06-20 0115</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Solstice,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solstice Marks Longest Day of the Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wednesday is the summer solstice, the longest
day of the year in the Northern Hemisphere.
   The solstice occurs at 5:53 a.m. EDT, according to astronomers at
the U.S. Naval Observatory here. The moment marks the time during
the summer when the sun is farthest from the equator.
   The date, known in folklore as Midsummer, had been a time for
parties and frivolity to celebrate the season.
   Listing the date as the start of summer has become a popular
convention among calendar makers in recent years, but the
designation carries no official weight. Meteorologists, for example,
consider summer to have begun June 1.
</TEXT>
