<FIRST>u a PM-SwindallTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0575 06-20 0851</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Swindall Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0575,0871</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Rep. Swindall Convicted of Perjury</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with quotes from Swindall, details on money
deal. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Pat Swindall was convicted of nine
counts of perjury today for lying to a federal grand jury about a
money-laundering scheme.
   The 38-year-old Republican, who served two terms in Congress from
Atlanta's suburbs before being defeated in November, could receive
up to five years in prison plus fines of $250,000 on each count at
sentencing Aug. 25.
   The jury deliberated 17 hours over four days after nearly four
weeks of testimony. Swindall was indicted in October on 10 counts of
perjury. U.S. District Judge Richard C. Freeman dismissed one count
during the trial.
   The former congressman was accused of lying to a grand jury in
1988 about his 1987 negotiations with an IRS agent posing as a
drug-money launderer and with Swindall associate Charles LeChasney,
later convicted of money laundering.
   Among other things, Swindall was found guilty of perjury for
denying that he had been told that the $850,000 he was seeking from
the agent to finish building his luxurious home contained proceeds
from drug trafficking.
   Swindall looked on impassively as the verdict was read, his
wife's hand on his back.
   At a news conference, he said he was confident he would be
vindicated on appeal _ ``not vindicated in the sense that I did no
wrong, but vindicated in the sense that I never perjured myself
before the grand jury.''
   His chief attorney, Richard Hendrix, said Swindall, who did not
take the stand at trial, will appeal.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Barr said, ``The jury has very obviously
spoken today. ... (Swindall) violated the integrity of the grand
jury process.''
   Swindall, a lanky, boyish lawyer, went to Congress in 1984 from
the city's affluent eastern suburbs as a conservative,
fundamentalist Christian. Under the cloud of the perjury indictment,
he lost to Democrat Ben Jones, a former TV actor from ``The Dukes of
Hazzard.''
   The jury heard secretly taped conversations with the undercover
agent, Mike Mullaney, in which Swindall was told that the $850,000
``certainly'' included drug money and that he would be part of an
operation to ``wash'' cash. Swindall proposed that a mortgage
company be set up by LeChasney as a ``buffer'' to allow him to
``borrow'' the agent's money.
   In their last conversation, after Swindall had received a
$150,000 advance, he told Mullaney, ``If Charles wants to launder
y'all's money, fine. But I can't do that. ... I can borrow the money
from Charles.''
   Later, Swindall told a federal grand jury he was ``never
satisfied ... with respect to (the deal's) criminality'' and knew
almost nothing about LeChasney's mortgage company.
   The deal never was completed. Swindall was to have received
$850,000 in exchange for a $1 million promissory note.
   Swindall's lawyers insisted that he had been duped by a man he
assumed was his friend _ LeChasney, whom they labeled a
``sociopathic liar'' and ``master manipulator'' who assured Swindall
that the deal was OK.
   Hendrix said the former congressman was guilty of ``stupidity''
but not perjury. He said Swindall was fatigued at the time of his
grand jury testimony and tried faithfully to recall details from
months gone by.
   ``He never laundered a dime. He did the best he could when he got
in front of the grand jury,'' Hendrix said.
   But Prosecutor Cragi Gillen scoffed at the ``I don't remember''
and ``I don't recall'' phrases that peppered Swindall's grand jury
testimony.
   ``Do you think you would remember,'' Gillen asked the jury, ``if
you took a walk with a man you believed to be a criminal ... and he
tells you narcotics dollars are involved ... what he does violates
currency laws?
   ``Do you think you could ever forget?''
   The prosecution called a surprise witness, money-laundering
conspirator Kirk Smith, who testified that Swindall had told him
last fall _ before the congressman was indicted _ how he planned to
beat the perjury rap.
   Smith recalled: ``He looked at me and said, `Kirk, I'm a lawyer.
In front of the grand jury, I used phrases like ``I don't remember''
and ``I can't recall.'' They can't convict me for having a bad
memory.'''
   Swindall was a largely unknown lawyer and furniture store owner
when he was elected in an upset in 1984, toppling veteran Democrat
Elliott Levitas.
   Swindall, a Presbyterian, took his campaign to evangelical
churches, distributing a ``Biblical Scorecard'' in his race against
Levitas, who is Jewish.
   In his two terms, Swindall staunchly voted with the Reagan right
and acquired a reputation as somewhat of a gadfly, voting against
such popular programs as school lunch funding and aid to African
famine victims. He filed a brief with the Supreme Court advocating
the teaching of ``creationism'' in schools.
   After his indictment, Swindall hoped to clear his name by
Election Day with an immediate trial, but the effort collapsed after
jurors received Swindall campaign mail proclaiming his innocence.
The judge aborted the trial.
   Two weeks later, Jones won by 20 percentage points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
