<FIRST>u a PM-StolenExams 1stLd-Writethru a0542 06-20 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stolen Exams, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0542,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Statewide Final Exam Canceled After Thefts in New York High Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf with four grafs to ADD Post editor unavailable,
cost of new exam, answers being faxed.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York's education commissioner today
canceled statewide chemistry exams for 80,000 high school students
after the New York Post, citing widespread thefts of the test,
published a stolen answer sheet.
   Commissioner Thomas Sobol described the Post's move as ``beneath
contempt.''
   Attorney General Robert Abrams' office said it was investigating
the theft of two exams in New York City and looking into reports
that copies of them were being sold for as much as $2,000 to groups
of students who split the cost.
   The New York Board of Regents sponsors 17 exams on different
subjects, which it distributed to high schools in padlocked safes
for administering June 15-22.
   The exams are crucial for many students to graduate from high
school without attending summer school and to get a diploma
acceptable to colleges.
   The Post reported that so many stolen tests were circulating it
took the newspaper just 15 minutes and two phone calls to obtain a
copy of the chemistry answer sheet.
   The tabloid printed the 56 answers on its front page, explaining,
``The Post is publishing it only after learning that thousands of
answer sheets have been photocopied by and distributed to high
school students illegally.''
   Post Editor Jerry Nachman did not immediately return a telephone
call today.
   Sobol's spokeswoman, Linda Fisher, said a new chemistry exam will
be offered Aug. 17 and the state also will grant students credit
based on their high school chemistry grades. Other exams went on as
scheduled this morning.
   Fisher estimated the cost of preparing and administering the new
test at $250,000.
   She said Sobol canceled the exam after learning that the answers
in the Post were quickly being ``faxed'' across the state.
</TEXT>
