<FIRST>r p AM-ChildCare-Politics     06-20 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Care-Politics,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strategists See Child Care as Significant Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Child care will be a significant issue in the
1990 congressional campaign and Republican chances could be damaged
if child care and parental-leave legislation is vetoed by President
Bush, GOP and Democratic political strategists said Tuesday.
   Vince Breglio, a Republican consultant who was pollster for the
Bush campaign in 1988 and is a former director of the Republican
Senate campaign committee, said: ``I don't believe serious political
candidates in 1990 can avoid discussing the issue of child care. I
don't believe they can avoid discussing the issue of long-term
health care.''
   Breglio said he did not believe parental leave would be an issue
because ``in terms of an issue you have to have clear-cut
differences. It is very hard for me to imagine two candidates going
at each other over the issue of parental leave.''
   Celinda Lake, a Democratic consultant, argued that ``work and
family issues,'' including child care, parental leave and long-term
health care, ``have emerged as major policy issues in 1990.''
   ``The president has vetoed the minimum wage,'' Ms. Lake said.
``There is some possibility of a veto of parental leave and child
care. If those three vetos come down, that is a definite statement
of the Republicans' position on work and family issues, and it is up
to the Democrats to take those voting records into the district and
make those the issues that decide elections.''
   The two consultants appeared on a panel sponsored by the Child
Care Action Campaign, the Great American Family Tour, and Lifetime
television, which discussed results of a poll published by several
magazines in February in which 74 percent of those responding said
family issues should be a top priority for the president and
Congress.
   Breglio, asked by a member of the audience about the effects of a
series of presidential vetos, said, ``I think any time you are seen
as a naysayer, that you have nothing positive to offer in the
debate, you have a problem with voters of either gender.''
   ``If programs have particular importance to women and you are
vetoing a series of programs ... I think the cumulative effect of
that could have more impact than, say, a single program and
certainly that is one thing we would be watching,'' he said.
   Breglio said the most recent White House poll indicates about 5
to 6 percent more support for Bush's child care program, based on a
tax credit, than for a program being considered in Congress that
would involve direct government funding.
   ``So far, George Bush is doing pretty well with women,'' he said.
``The numbers look very good. Now, if there is a whole series of
vetos on legislation that is of particular importance to women, that
could be a different ball game.''
</TEXT>
