<HEAD>US Urges China to Grant Clemency to Demonstrators</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs, with new material, editing throughout. Grafs 10-13
for release at 2 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has urged China to grant
clemency to demonstrators sentenced to death in Beijing and Shanghai
and to pardon those who were arrested in pro-democracy protests, the
White House said today.
   ``Sentences of death in Shanghai and Beijing could only deepen
the wounds of the past few weeks,'' said White House press secretary
Marlin Fitzwater.
   He declined to say what, if any, steps the United States might
take if China goes ahead with executions.
   The White House announcement came on the heels of demands in
Congress and elsewhere that the United States intensify its
condemnation of Chinese repression and consider further sanctions
against the Beijing government.
   Fitzwater said China's ambassador to the United States, Han Xu,
was called to the State Department Monday night to hear what the
spokesman called ``the strong United States' position.''
   Hinting at worsening relations between Beijing and Washington,
Fitzwater said ``the United States raised this subject in the spirit
of a country that has worked with China over the past two decades to
improve relations.
   ``We believe that human rights are universal, and our duty to
comment on them is great,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``We urge the leaders of the Peoples Republic of China to show
clemency and to use their powers to pardon those who were arrested
in the demonstrations for democracy,'' Fitzwater said.
   Human rights are ``an important principle by which the United
States judges its relations'' with all countries in the world, he
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Following 0 grafs embargoed for release at 2 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said in prepared testimony
for the Senate Foreign Relations Committee that the United States
strongly supports reform in the communist world and accused Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev of dodging the China issue.
   ``To stand in the way of such necessary historic changes _ as we
are seeing to our outrage and sorrow in China _ is to turn one's
back on the future,'' he said.
   Gorbachev's ``temporizing comments on those tragic events are
disappointing,'' Baker said.
   On a visit last week to West Germany, Gorbachev said he did not
have ``sufficient information'' on what was happening in China to
make a ``balanced and responsible'' judgment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Embargoed Material</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   Although the administration is trying to keep Americans from
returning to China, only military transactions with Beijing have
been suspended by Bush.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., and other lawmakers have
called on Bush to consider other punitive measures and also step up
U.S. condemnation of the Chinese government.
   At a news conference almost two weeks ago, Bush rejected the
suggestion of more sanctions against China, saying the halt of
weapons sales went far enough under present circumstances. ``I think
that the position we took, aiming not at the Chinese people but at
the military arrangements, was well-received around the world, and
was followed by many countries right after we did that,'' he said.
   Chinese dissident Fang Lizhi and his wife, Li Shuxian, took
refuge June 4 at the U.S. Embassy in Beijing shortly after the
military crushed pro-democracy protests.
   Fang has led Chinese intellectuals in calling for release of
political prisoners and asserting that economic and scientific
progress is impossible without protections for free thought. He was
also angered the Chinese by saying Marxism is dead.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret D. Tutwiler said Monday
American workers are being advised strongly not to return to jobs in
China. ``We're not going to lift our travel advisory. That remains
in effect,'' she said.
   The advisory _ which is a suggestion and not an order _ was
posted after Chinese Army troops attacked students demonstrating for
a more liberal regime June 3-4 in Tiananmen Square.
   Thousands of Americans subsequently left China, some with U.S.
assistance, thereby stripping U.S. companies of many of their key
personnel.
   About 175 American companies have offices in China. Many of them
have received word from their Chinese partners in joint ventures
reporting that the turmoil has subsided.
   Ms. Tutwiler said that despite ``a pause in anti-U.S. propaganda
over the weekend,'' the situation in China remains ``far from
normal.''
   She said criticism of the Voice of America resumed on Saturday,
and that articles had appeared attacking expelled VOA Bureau Chief
Alan Pessin and Associated Press correspondent John Pomfret.
   On Sunday, the official New China News Agency said Fitzwater's
criticism of death sentences imposed on three Chinese for burning a
train was ``ridiculous.''
