<FIRST>r a AM-StubbornTower     06-20 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stubborn Tower,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leaning Tower of Providence Immortalized on T-Shirts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The building that twice has defied
explosions to fell it, now is being immortalized in three T-shirt
designs and their creators are in a spat over whose brainstorm the
shirt idea was.
   One depicts ``The Leaning Tower of Providence,'' another ``The
Leaning Tower of Bilray,'' for the construction company that pulled
the boo-boo, and ``The Hartford Park Horror Project,'' sponsored by
Republicans who want to make political capital from the snafu.
   Bilray, contracted by the Providence Housing Authority, tried
twice on May 21 to implode the Hartford Park housing project and
succeeded only in knocking out one floor, leaving the L-shaped
building leaning on itself.
   The company has since been working at taking the building down
with a traditional wrecking ball.
   State GOP Chairman Michael Vallante came out with the Republican
T-shirt on Monday, but he says he had the idea all along but just
got sidetracked about getting the shirts made up.
   The housing authority sold out its first 100 shirts Thursday and
says it has 300 more going on sale Tuesday, with a price increase
from $4 to $6.
   When Bilray groused they already had $9 shirts for sale, Stephen
O'Rourke, the authority's director, said he was the one who came up
with the phrase ``Leaning Tower of Bilray'' the day the implosion
failed.
   ``What does he want to do, sue us?'' O'Rourke said. ``I mean this
is not one of those things that is high up on my agenda.''
   Vallante said the GOP would offer to eventually add the total
cost of the project to the back of its $5 shirts.
   ``The people of Providence have a right to know what is the cost
in extra security, the costs for safety, the cost of the lost
business in the area for this tower that is a testament to
incompetence,'' Vallante said.
</TEXT>
