<FIRST>u i AM-SovietShip-Witness     06-20 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Ship-Witness,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Passengers on Soviet Ship, It Was Vodka Among the Rocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Ship, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA JANZON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last thing Rudolf Ludwig expected to
be served for breakfast on his arctic cruise was vodka.
   Ludwig had gone to bed early Monday night, leaving his wife to
enjoy a cabaret evening aboard the Soviet cruise liner Maxim Gorky.
He ended up spending five hours in a lifeboat floating among
icebergs.
   ``I was in bed when suddenly there was a terrible crash that
almost shook me out of bed,'' said Ludwig, one of more than 950
passengers and crew aboard the vessel when it struck an iceberg.
   Obeying instructions from the ship's loudspeakers, the
67-year-old West German pensioner with a walking disability pulled
on his trousers, put on his life vest and went on deck to stand by a
lifeboat.
   The liner, on a cruise out of Bremerhaven, West Germany, struck
the iceberg about 300 miles east of northern Greenland. No injuries
were reported.
   ``We are all safe and sound here,'' Ludwig said in a telephone
interview from a church on the Norwegian island of Svalbard, where
passengers were taken by ship and helicopter after the accident.
   Ludwig said he had just heard that his wife was safe and coming
to join him. They were being taken home to Wiesbaden as soon as the
rescue operation was complete, he said.
   He seemed in good spirits, joking: ``I'm standing here in my
pajamas, and the trousers keep wanting to fall down to my knees.''
   For a while, though, there was nothing to laugh about.
   ``When I got up on deck, I saw enormous ice blocks around. We
were told to get into the lifeboats,'' he said, adding that there
was no panic.
   ``We sat for five hours among the icebergs. The atmosphere was
calm, and the Russian sailors did everything they could. They gave
us vodka and whiskey in the boats, since it was cold,'' said Ludwig.
``And blankets too.''
   Temperatures in the area were about 38 degrees.
   ``From the lifeboats, we could see that a third of the ship was
under water,'' he said. Ludwig said that the ship appeared to be
moving fast through the icy waters before the crash. There was a
slight fog, but not enough to impair vision, he said.
   The Norwegian coast guard vessel Senja reached the stricken ship
early Tuesday and picked up hundreds of passengers who had jumped
into lifeboats or scrambled onto ice floes, said Kjell Larssen of
the north Norway Rescue Center at Bodoe. Others were rescued by
helicopter from the ship or ice floes.
   ``My wife will get here in a while,'' he said. ``They've gotten
blankets and stuff together so that people can spend the night, I
suppose.''
</TEXT>
