<FIRST>r a PM-TVSurgery 2ndLd-Writethru a0552 06-20 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TV Surgery, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0552,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public TV Station Airs Surgery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with rating, telephone calls. PICKS
UP 6ath graf pvs, `Dr. Richard ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman underwent back surgery on live TV and
said she agreed to it in hopes of helping others who may need the
operation.
   ``I don't feel invaded at all,'' said Deborah Arizin, 27, a sales
representative from Haddonfield, N.J., who had suffered from back
pain for more than half her life. The surgery took place on public
television Monday night.
   The 2{-hour operation to help correct a 50-degree curvature of
Mrs. Arizin's spine is expected to make the 5-foot-9-inch patient an
inch and a half taller.
   ``It's really kind of surprising, but the focus is the surgery
and the new technique and how it can help other patients,'' Mrs.
Arizin said. ``I agreed in the hope that it would help other people
who are going through the same thing.''
   WHYY said it broadcast the operation live for its impact and
educational value.
   ``It's more exciting. It's more television, more immediate. It's
just much more real. We did it as an attempt to show people what
it's really like, without editing,'' said station manager David
Othmer.
   WHYY spokeswoman Tina Brock today said the station received at
least 330 calls, its highest ever for one show. She said viewers
called the program ``absolutely breathtaking'' and ``magnificent,''
but several found it gory.
   Ms. Brock said the show received a good 6.9 rating and an 11
percent share against the network lineup, which began at 8 p.m. with
``Kate &amp; Allie'' on CBS, ``ALF'' on NBC and ``MacGyver'' in ABC. The
rating is percentage of all homes with television, the share a
percentage of televisions in use.
   Dr. Richard Rothman, founder of Pennsylvania Hospital's Rothman
Institute for orthopedic surgery, was host during the operation at
the hospital.
   ``It was a tense evening because of the live television, but
everything went extremely well,'' Rothman said. ``This is real life,
that's what makes this operation so interesting. We do it every day,
and even we are impressed.''
   Viewers saw Mrs. Arizin, who was introduced in taped sequences,
lying on her stomach on the operating table, surgical drapes
covering her from the shoulders up and the hips down.
   Three cameras, including an overhead one, covered the 10-member
medical team at work in the two-hour, 20-minute program.
   Dr. Richard Balderston performed the operation, during which
stainless steel rods were attached to the vertebrae to nearly
straighten Mrs. Arizin's spine. Bone was then grafted onto the rods
to hold them in place.
   ``The surgery used to take six to seven hours. It now takes two
to four hours,'' Balderston said. ``Patients used to be in bed for
as long as six months. Now they're out of bed in one or two days.
They used to be in a plaster body cast for as long as a year. Now
it's very unusual to need a cast.''
   Two percent of Americans suffer from curvature of the spine, or
scoliosis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
