<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1414EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Baker     06-20 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Criticizes Gorbachev, Supports Reform in Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III on
Tuesday endorsed the ``potential revolution'' under way in the
Soviet Union but criticized President Mikhail S. Gorbachev for not
taking a strong stand against suppression of reform in China.
   Baker, in a prepared statement to the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, reigstered U.S. support for reform throughout the
communist world. Whether in Asia or in Europe, he said, reform ``is
very much in our interests.''
   At the same time, Baker said no one could predict the outcome of
the changes taking place in Moscow and elsewhere. ``In the end,'' he
said, ``we do know that the success of reform will depend primarily
upon choices made in Moscow, Beijing or East Berlin, not Washington,
Brussels or Bonn.''
   He stressed, however, that political and economic reform were
necessary in order for the East to progress.
   ``To stand in the way of such necessary, historic change _ as we
are seeing to our outrage and sorrow in China _ is to turn one's
back to the future. And that is why General Secretary Gorbachev's
temporizing comments on those tragic events are disappointing,'' he
said.
   Baker apparently referred to a statement by the Soviet leader
last week that he did not have ``sufficient information'' on events
in China to make a ``balanced and responsible judgment'' about
Beijing's actions.
   Baker appeared before the committee mostly to report on his
meeting in Moscow last month with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze and on the summit President Bush held in Brussels at
the end of the month with the leaders of the 15 other North Atlantic
Treaty Organization nations.
   There Bush outlined a proposal for reductions in NATO and Warsaw
Pact conventional troops and armories in Europe and delayed
consideration of deploying more powerful short-range nuclear
missiles in West Germany.
   Baker told the committee the administration was ``exploring and
establishing new vehicles'' to foster cooperation with the Soviet
Union.
   ``We're actively engaging Moscow with our eyes open and fixed on
our longstanding goals and interests,'' he said.
   Baker said these goals were to protect Western security and to
promote democratic values and interests.
   ``The movement we're seeing in Soviet politics presents a
potential revolution _ a revolution we hope will succeed,'' Baker
said.
   In reviewing U.S. relations with the Soviet Union for the Senate
committee, he endorsed reform in Moscow, Eastern Europe and China.
</TEXT>
