<FIRST>r i AM-France-Prison     06-20 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Prison,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marie Antoinette's Prison Restored To Gloomy Grandeur</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Conciergerie, the dank and forbidding stone
prison where victims of the French Revolution spent their final
moments, opened to the public Tuesday in all its former gloom and
grandeur.
   Queen Marie Antoinette occupied a cell on the ground floor for 10
weeks in 1793, hoping her supporters would come up with enough money
to buy her freedom.
   She waited in vain, and went to her death at the guillotine on
Oct. 16, 1793.
   The cell she shared with her jailer later was turned into a
chapel as a shrine to her memory, but a replica of the cell has been
recreated nearby and is decorated with wallpaper embossed with the
royal blue and gold lily emblems that covered the walls 200 years
ago.
   Maximilien Robespierre, who sent thousands of heads rolling
during his 12-month Reign of Terror against counterrevolutionaries,
spent his final hours a few cells away on July 28, 1794.
   ``His death warrant arrived about 10 a.m., and he was carted away
to the guillotine in mid-afternoon,'' Michel Colardelle of the
Culture Ministry said during a tour of the restored landmark
overlooking the Seine. The spot is marked by a simple black marble
plaque.
   Admirers of Robespierre, known as the Incorruptible, say history
has not done him justice.
   ``He has been made to bear all the guilt of the Terror,'' said
former Health Minister Leon Schwartzenberg, one of several public
figures eager to rehabilitate Robespierre's memory.
   ``All revolutions are characterized by excess of some sort,
otherwise they would not be revolutions,'' he said.
   No one, however, can accuse the French of not paying tribute to
Robespierre's victims and others who died during the turbulent
events.
   A small room on the second floor is devoted entirely to their
memory. Its four walls are covered with framed lists, in
alphabetical order, of the 2,780 aristocrats, gardeners, shoemakers,
doctors and clergymen found guilty by the Revolutionary Tribunal and
beheaded within three days. The verdict was either guilty or
acquittal. There were no appeals.
   Some names are familiar, like Charlotte Corday, who stabbed
Jean-Paul Marat in his bath. Others, like F. Perrin, gardener, are
not.
   A short film with English subtitles helps visitors follow the
events and depicts daily life at the prison.
   Ordinary prisoners shared the squalor of cold cells littered with
filthy straw. The wealthy bought their way into cells furnished with
beds and sometimes even desks, where many an aristocrat penned his
memoirs.
   Also recreated are the quarters where the condemned were taken to
have their shirts ripped wide and the napes of their necks shaved so
the guillotine's blade would cut cleanly.
   Prisoners were allowed to circulate freely during the day in the
women's courtyard. Despite their predicament, many privileged ladies
managed to keep up with fashion trends, and even groomed themselves
without the help of maids.
   ``Marie Antoinette, in her final days, even learned to put up her
own hair,'' said Jean Chalon, author of a recent biography.
   The $375,000 renovation of the Conciergerie is one of several
refurbishing projects linked to bicentennial celebrations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e AM-APArts:Rivkin 1stLd-Writethru   06-20 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Rivkin, 1st Ld - Writethru,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Producer Has Singular Priority</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS name of group in 1st graf to Fine Young Cannibals,
sted Five</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Rivkin has produced hit albums for Prince,
Fine Young Cannibals and Jody Watley, but the Minneapolis native has
``higher'' priorities.
   ``In the back of my mind, I always go for the single,'' said the
producer of Prince's ``Kiss,'' Watley's ``Looking for a New Love''
and Fine Young Cannibals' ``She Drives Me Crazy,'' all No. 1 smashes.
   ``I go for the throat, really. I really am a singles-oriented
person. It's really the way I want to go after it.''
   Like a baseball manager who must cope with the personalities of
different players, Rivkin _ known in the business as David Z _
adjusts his style to fit the artist. With Prince, a gifted
songwriter and arranger, the producer sees himself as a collaborator
and occasional mind reader.
   ``He's a different personality every day, so you just have to
capture whatever personality he is that day. I just think about how
to frame whatever mindset he's in.''
   With Tyka Nelson, Prince's introverted sister, Rivkin took a more
delicate approach.
   He remembered the Jets' first album as his most difficult.
   ``It was the first real time we discovered a new artrist and we
had to come through with all the songs and vocals. We were shooting
in the dark, we were taking kids from a bar band and trying to make
a national product,'' Rivkin said.
   ``We had to establish a direction. That was a bit difficult. We
had to do every vocal; there was no sampling. Somes things you take
for granted now.''
   Rivkin was once a musician himself, playing guitar for Billy
Preston and writing with country-rock artist Gram Parsons. He had
lived in Los Angeles in the early 1970s, but returned to his
hometown in 1974.
   He was soon behind the control board.
   ``I didn't want to do it at the time, but I realized I had much
more control over material sitting behind that seat. I gave up the
idea of being a rock star.''
   In 1980, he engineered Lipps, Inc.'s No. 1 dance hit,
``Funkytown,'' and played guitar on their album. He has since
produced a remarkable range of acts, from the Minnesota funk of
Prince and Jesse Johnson, to the blue-eyed soul of Hall &amp; Oates and
Boy George, to the dance music of Watley and Jermaine Jackson.
   ``I try to fill the holes the artists can't fill,'' he said.
``That comes from doing the right sound, a special snare drum sound,
a special vocal echo, and from making the artists feel good enough
to bring out their personality.''
   His sheer diversity has had drawbacks. In an industry that loves
labels and openly categorizes music according to race, it's hard to
define a white kid from the Midwest who produces best-selling dance
records by black artists.
   ``I used to be classified as an R&amp;B producer. It was a hard notch
to get out of. Because I was white, I would get a lot of flack. I've
had a lot of No. 1 black records. In the face of all that, my own
inclination was to combine rock and R&amp;B.''
   Rivkin compared himself to in a way to Alfred Hitchcock, speaking
of the cameo appearances that were the great film director's
trademark. A guitar riff is Rivkin's subtle way of popping up in his
work.
   ``I think if you look real hard, there's a thread running through
all those records,'' he said. ``Rhythmically, there's a certain
sound. ``In `Kiss,' it's a major part of the record. Sometimes, it
appears as a little wink.''
   His presence is unmistakeable in the studio. Hit singles don't
come easy and Rivkin pushes hard for the best sound.
   ``I make singers breath and emote a lot more than they would
normally. I always look for that sexy breath. There's a fine line
between getting it perfect and not losing the artist when you're
doing it. I don't care if there's some rough edges,'' he said.
   ``Finding a producer is like finding a wife. It's tough. It's a
chemistry thing. I like to get involved from the ground up. Usually,
what I do is start programming drum parts at home on my machine. If
you get a good drum and bass part, that's 90 percent of the pop
record.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0100 </DOCNO>
