<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     06-20 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Willing to Resume Peace Talks With South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea said Tuesday it was ready
to resume talks with South Korea on easing tension, but it also
denounced Seoul for arresting a top dissident and called for his
release.
   The communist nation delivered a letter at the Panmunjom border
truce site proposing the talks resume June 28. South Korea made a
similar proposal May 26.
   South Korean officials, who released the letter, had no immediate
response. The two nations have held talks at various levels since
August 1988 on improving relations, but there has been no major
progress.
   The latest talks are meant to set terms for the nations'
legislatures to meet for formal negotiations on easing tension and
reunification.
   North Korea suspended the talks in February after Seoul refused
to cancel annual military exercises held in March with the United
States. North Korea has been seeking the withdrawal of U.S. forces
from South Korea.
   The letter, from North Korean delegation head Chon Gum Chol,
charged South Korea delayed talks further by arresting a South
Korean dissident clergyman, the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan, when he returned
in April from a visit to Pyongyang. Moon was charged with acting as
a North Korean agent.
   ``We consider that your side should set free Rev. Moon Ik-hwan,
who was arrested unreasonably ... and show sincerity to take a step
to create an atmosphere of dialogue,'' the letter said.
   Neither nation allows its citizens to visit the other side
without permission. Seoul said Moon's visit was part of efforts to
cause political chaos.
   Separate government talks and negotiations between sports
officials on forming a joint team for the 1990 Asian Games in
Beijing have been suspended until July. The two sides have not said
if they will resume.

</TEXT>
