<FIRST>r a PM-GalloTademark     06-20 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gallo Tademark,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winery Brothers Win Right to Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winemakers Ernest and Julio Gallo today won
exclusive rights to the family name, thwarting a younger brother who
had put his name on a brand of cheese.
   U.S. District Judge Robert E. Coyle ruled that Joseph Gallo's use
of his full name on cheese was calculated to mislead consumers into
thinking the brand is connected with the E &amp; J Gallo Winery.
   The judge ordered Joseph Gallo to quit using his name on cheese.
   Joseph Gallo has no direct connection with the Modesto,
Calif.-based Gallo Winery, the world's largest, but sells grapes to
his older brothers
   Joseph Gallo's attorney, Denis Rice, said he will recommend an
appeal. Rice said at trial in December that he knew of no case in
which a person was prohibited from using his full name on a
non-competing product.
   Ernest and Julio Gallo claimed in a 1986 lawsuit that they had
contracted with a company to market cheese under the Gallo name.
   Patrick Lynch, attorney for the winery, contended that Joseph
Gallo was ``riding on the recognition and riding on the power that
the Gallo mark conferred.''
   Previously, a federal judge threw out a countersuit in which
Joseph Gallo, 69, claimed he is entitled to one-third of the winery
holdings on grounds that it developed from the estate of the Gallo
brothers' parents.
   Ernest, now 80, and Julio, now 78, began making wine in 1933,
shortly after their father killed their mother, then committed
suicide, their attorney said.
</TEXT>
