<FIRST>r w AM-Glenn-B-2     06-20 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Glenn-B-2,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glenn Urges Cheney to Suspend B-2, Reinstate Osprey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Democratic member of the Senate Armed
Services Committee on Tuesday urged Defense Secretary Dick Cheney to
suspend production of the B-2 stealth bomber because the aircraft
has yet to undergo flight testing.
   Cheney in response reaffirmed his support for the B-2, which at
$500 million a copy is the most expensive plane in history. The
bomber is a necessary component of the triad of air-, land- and
sea-based nuclear weapons, said Pete Williams, Cheney's spokesman.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, a former astronaut and test pilot,
argued that pursuing production of the radar-evading plane violates
the rule of ``fly before buy.''
   The bomber program has been ``buy it, and then we'll see how it
flies,'' Glenn said in a letter to Cheney.
   ``The B-2 is a total departure from our usual new aircraft,''
Glenn said. said. ``It is a flying wing. There are new control
concepts, different center of gravity considerations, and new
aerodynamics just to name a few. Going ahead with additional
production before flight tests have even started just doesn't make
sense.''
   Cheney has proposed pushing back production of the stealth bomber
a year to 1993 and cutting almost $4.1 billion from fiscal 1990 and
1991 budgets for the plane.
   Glenn said $22.4 billion has already been invested in the stealth
program, and concluded that it would be ``totally irresponsible'' to
continue production without flight test results.
   Glenn argued that the money earmarked for the stealth bomber
could be used for ``high-priority conventional programs that have
been terminated or deferred.''
   Glenn, a former Marine, said he favors the Marine Corps' V-22
Osprey, a battlefield aircraft designed to take off like a
helicopter and fly like an airplane. The Pentagon had hoped to spend
$25.9 billion on 663 Ospreys, including $1.3 billion in 1990, but
Cheney decided to terminate the program.
   Cheney is ``a big believer in the triad, and he thinks the B-2's
long-range capabilities and its stealth capacities make it an
important strategic asset to the United States,'' said Williams.
``So, he plans to continue right on with that and he reaffirmed his
strong support for the B-2 program.''
</TEXT>
