<FIRST>r a PM-People-Hurt 1stLd-Writethru a0488 06-20 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Hurt, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0488,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>William Hurt Gets Hot Under the Collar</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with today's testimony. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hot-under-the-collar William Hurt today gave a
lawyer the big chill and refused to answer his questions after the
attorney made a wisecrack about the conception of the actor's
6-year-old son.
   ``I'm blocked. I can't hear you,'' the star of ``Body Heat'' and
``The Big Chill'' said as A. Richard Golub pressed him about his
feelings for former lover Sandra Jennings after the birth of their
son, Alexander.
   Jennings, a 32-year-old former ballerina, is pursuing a
multimillion-dollar divorce claim against Hurt, contending they had
``a spiritual marriage'' more sacrosanct than a legal union.
   Golub today became frustrated during cross-examination of Hurt by
constant objections from the defense. He complained to the judge
that the objections were ``interrupting my rhythm, and rhythm is
everything.''
   As Golub sought to resume questioning, Hurt _ who had been
snappish, combative and evasive in a day and a half of testimony _
said to Golub, ``Get your rhythm right.''
   Golub replied: ``You got your rhythm right when you made Alex,
didn't you?''
   Hurt turned to Justice Jacqueline Silbermann and said, ``You can
permit that?'' She told Golub to confine himself to the issues.
   When Golub resumed questioning, Hurt said he was couldn't hear
the questions. He leveled his finger at Golub and accused him of
making ``a perverse and insulting remark about my son.'' The judge
declared a recess.
   Jennings is seeking half the money Hurt has made since Dec. 9,
1982, when he learned his divorce from his first wife, actress Mary
Beth Hurt, was final. Golub put Hurt's worth at about $10 million.
   Jennings claims a common-law marriage exists because she and Hurt
lived together from 1981 to 1984. ``He told me we were married in
the eyes of God,'' she said during a courtroom break Monday.
   Hurt, 39, said he told Jennings after they started living
together that he was put off marriage by ``the pain of it not
working out with Mary Beth.''
   In March, Hurt married Heidi Henderson, daughter of bandleader
Skitch Henderson.
   Hurt, who won a best-actor Oscar for ``Kiss of the Spider
Woman,'' also has starred in ``Broadcast News,'' ``Gorky Park,''
``The Accidental Tourist'' and ``Children of a Lesser God.''
</TEXT>
