<DOCNO> AP890620-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1444EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SkinDonor     06-20 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skin Donor,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dieter Sheds 173 Pounds, Donates Excess 4 Square Feet of Skin to
Burn Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dieters who lose 10 or 20 pounds may give away
their baggy old clothes. But Dennis Genz's 173-pound loss left him
with too much skin, so he donated about 4 square feet to help save
burn victims.
   ``This is a first for us. ... Occasionally, rarely, if a child is
a patient a parent may donate skin,'' Betty Perls, director of
education for the Regional Organ Bank of Illinois, said Tuesday.
   The 5-foot-11 Genz, 43, weighed 430 pounds last August when he
began a high-protein weight-loss regimen.
   Last week, he weighed in at 260 and prepared for surgery to
remove excess skin from his abdomen to ease back pains and other
problems.
   ``I was sitting at lunch with some nurses and we were joking that
it was too bad I couldn't donate the skin,'' said Genz, equipment
coordinator for the emergency department at Sherman Hospital in
Elgin, just northwest of Chicago.
   ``Then one of the nurses said, `Why not?''' he recalled Tuesday
from his hospital bed, where he was recovering from Monday's surgery.
   The decision ``left me with a good feeling,'' Genz said, adding
that he felt fine but had ``kind of a big scar.''
   ``I've worked in emergency rooms for 25 years. ... I'm a strong
supporter of transplants,'' he said.
   What if he gains back the lost weight?
   ``The skin would just stretch out again _ but I don't intend to
gain the weight back,'' Genz said.
   The operation removed 19{ pounds of skin and adjoining tissue,
Genz said.
   His donated skin _ about four square feet _ will be used to care
for burn patients at the University of Chicago Medical Center.
   ``More lives are saved by skin transplants than any other donated
organ,'' said Dr. Lawrence Gottlieb, professor of surgery and
director of the university's burn unit.
   ``What kills burn patients is loss of fluid and infection,'' Ms.
Perls said.
   Donated skin ``is used as a kind of living bandage'' while the
patient regenerates his own skin, she said. Then the borrowed tissue
sloughs off.
   Because its use is temporary, skin used for burn patients need
not be a perfect tissue type match like that used for skin grafts or
other organ transplants, Ms. Perls said.
   She noted that noting most such tissue is removed from cadavers.
   But while Getz's contribution is unusual, ``this kind of weight
loss is unusual, too,'' she said.
   ``Anything that will make people think about organ or tissue
donation is good,'' she said.
   University hospital spokesman John Easton agreed.
   ``There's a shortage of any sort of donated organ. ... It is
beneficial and it comes at a good time _ I think they're planning to
use some of it today,'' Easton said of Genz's contribution.
   ``I think any sort of organ donation ... is a valuable,
life-saving procedure.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
