<FIRST>u w AM-TalkingMachine     06-20 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Talking Machine,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>For the Blind, a Device That Obeys Spoken Commands and Speaks Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Argyropoulos talked to a machine Tuesday
and the machine talked back, telling the 22-year-old engineering
student the time, reading newspaper articles aloud and dialing a
phone number.
   Its developers say the machine, though still primitive, is the
most promising aid for the blind since the introduction of Braille
160 years ago..
   The Personal Companion, unveiled at a news conference, was
created for the 6.5 million Americans who cannot see well enough to
read or are so handicapped they can't turn a page or punch a
keyboard.
   The machine has the appearance of a computer, but without a
keyboard. It is programmed to respond to the voice of its user.
   Transceptor Technologies Inc., an Ann Arbor, Mich., company
founded in 1986 by people with backgrounds in medicine, visual
rehabilitation, telecommunications, computer design and education,
developed the Personal Companion.
   Argyropoulos, a 22-year-old computer buff, designed the softwear,
working 20 hours to 80 hours a week while a student at the
University of Michigan.
   He said he wanted to build a machine ``not for the superstar
blind person but one that your grandmother could use without knowing
anything about computers.''
   Argyropoulos said 20 minutes of training by the machine, which
gives instructions by voice, are all that's needed to get started.
   Company president Bernard F. McCrory said the machine costs
$6,500 to $6,800. The higher priced model comes with a screen for
the visually impaired on which the type can be made several inches
high.
   McCrory said the machine could be leased by those who can't
afford to buy one.
   Carroll Jackson, director of the Greater Detroit Society for the
Blind and a consultant to the company, called the development
``analogous to the introduction of Braille'' by blind Frenchman
Louis Braille in 1829.
   Jackson, who is legally blind, compared its potential impact to
the introduction of curb cuts that enable people in wheelchairs to
use sidewalks.
   In the voice demonstration, Argyropoulos had the machine do
mathematical computations, record a checkbook transaction _ but not
actually write the check _ tell what was in his appointment ledger
and turn on the radio and the lights.
   At his command, the device called information to get and record a
phone number and then dialed the number.
   By arrangement with the Gannett Co., a condensed version of USA
Today is made available each day over a telephone line. The
machine's synthetic, mechanical sounding voice lists the sections of
the newspaper, recites the headlines and reads abbreviated versions
of stories selected by the user.
   Ultimately, McCrory said, far more information will be available
from computer data banks and the machine will play compact discs,
each capable of reading aloud up to 50 books.
   Company founder Mark Blumenkranz, an ophthalmologist and surgeon
at the Kresge Eye Institute in Detroit, said an engineer who lost
his sight in a hunting accident five years ago consequently lost his
business.
   The engineer has been testing the machine and ``feels he will be
able to go back into business for himself,'' Blumenkranz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1505EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Visas     06-20 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Visas,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Visa Applications Drop as New Exit Control Takes Effect</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New controls on Chinese travel abroad took effect
Tuesday, causing the number of applicants for U.S. visas to plummet.
   Dozens of Chinese had camped outside the U.S. and Canadian
embassies in hopes of getting their visa applications in before the
new rules took effect.
   Among them were doctors, computer scientists and economists, some
of China's best-educated and brightest citizens, all hoping to study
or do research abroad.
   ``We didn't dare leave to eat or sleep for fear of losing our
place in line,'' said an economist who succeeded in applying at the
Canadian Embassy and was waiting outside for a response.
   The revised visa requirements appeared designed to screen
depatures more carefully and prevent fugitive dissidents from
getting out. They came two weeks after the army rolled into Beijing
and opened fired on students and supporters demanding a freer
society.
   There was much confusion about the new regulations.
   Under existing procedure, Chinese are required to obtain exit
permits from their local police stations before Chinese guards
outside foreign embassies allow them to enter to apply for visas.
   According to reports in the official media over the weekend, the
new rules invalidate all permits issued before Tuesday. Through
Monday, Chinese could still use the old permits to enter embassy
grounds, but as of Tuesday the old permits were not good for even
that.
   One radio report and a Chinese source said visa applicants now
must also get a second permit after obtaining the visa. Many Chinese
applicants and several Western consular officials said they did not
know about this requirement and it could not immediately be
confirmed.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Sheridan Bell said only three Chinese
showed up at the consulate Tuesday with the new permit and were
allowed by Chinese guards to apply for visas. By comparison, 350
people applied on Monday, about average for summertime, he said.
   The United States and Canada are two of the most popular
destinations for Chinese traveling abroad for business or study. A
third popular country, Australia, has not reopened its consular
section since closing it after the military crackdown began on June
3.
   Most of those waiting outside the U.S. and Canadian embassies on
Tuesday made plans to go abroad before the crackdown and were not
involved in the protests.
   But they said they feared police would be stingy about issuing
exit permits in the new conservative political climate.
   ``I haven't been in trouble but (Chinese officials) may be
worried about `spiritual pollution,''' said a doctor waiting for a
response to his wife's application to study in Canada.
   Chinese officials refer to unwanted Western cultural influences
and values as spiritual pollution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1509EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Soviet Bjt   06-20 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Soviet, Bjt,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Moving on Soviet Policy After Four Months of Study</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is seeking to take advantage of
new openness in the Kremlin as he forges a Soviet policy designed to
meld Moscow into the international community.
   Bush is on the move now, unveiling new arms negotiating tactics
as well as plans to relax financial strictures on Poland as that
Soviet-bloc nation moves toward democracy.
   But four months of silence at the beginning of the
administration, while the president and his aides conducted a
``strategic review,'' left the impression that the new team was
uncertain how to deal with a volcano of Soviet reform.
   Robert Blackwill, National Security Council staff member for
Soviet and European affairs, and other Bush aides are seeking to
counter that impression.
   ``We know where we want to go,'' Blackwill said. ``We know of the
enormous opportunities that are out there. And we also understand
that if one makes a mistake in an era of transition, that there is
no inevitability for stability in international order, and it could
have a very high price.''
   ``We are trying to create the structure of a relationship that
makes it less likely it can be reversed, less likely that we can
have a return to the sort of conflict we saw in the 1970s and 80s.
And finally, to integrate the Soviet Union into the international
system so that it uses its enormous power to solve international
problems rather than to exploit them,'' Blackwill said in a speech
Tuesday at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce in Washington.
   Bush, during a summit of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
three weeks ago, outlined a plan to rapidly reduce superpower
conventional forces in Europe, surpassing even the proposals of
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Some of the fine print of Bush's Soviet-bloc plans, outlined in
broad terms over the past two months, has been disclosed recently
concerning arms negotiating tactics and help for the Polish economy.
   Within a few days, said Blackwill, the administration will
divulge specifics of new proposals in the Strategic Arms Reduction
Talks to test _ with the Soviets _ means of verifying the reduction
or elimination of long-range nuclear weapons.
   The ideas take advantage of apparent new Soviet openness to
verification and are designed to avoid the Senate misgivings that
helped block ratification of the Strategic Arms Limitation Treaty in
1979 and held up the Intermediate-range Nuclear Force Treaty last
year, said Blackwill.
   ``The purpose of the confidence-building and verification
measures which ... are being conveyed to the Soviets are to
accelerate, not delay, a historic agreement,'' said Blackwill,
declining to specify whether the proposals envision on-site
inspections or satellite surveillance.
   More details of Bush's policy toward Eastern Europe are expected
early next month when Bush travels to Poland and Hungary, two Soviet
bloc nations that Blackwill said are pushing away ``the dead hand of
communism'' with their political and economic reforms.
   ``Some believe that in trying to conceptualize a Soviet-American
relationship through the end of the century, taking four months to
do that, is a long time. I don't how long they take to buy a
house,'' Blackwill said.
   ``We have to keep remembering that dealing with an autocratic
system as exists in the Soviet Union, that reversibility is
possible. We have just seen tragic evidence of that fact in China,''
said Blackwill, referring to the suppression of the pro-democracy
movement in Beijing, in which thousands reportedly died.
   Bush and his top aides have lived most of their adult lives
during the Cold War. Blackwill and his boss, National Security
Adviser Brent Scowcroft, also served in the White House during
detente, under Presidents Nixon and Ford, when many proclaimed the
end to the Cold War.
   And so they dilute their hope with caution.
   ``I wrote myself the toast that President Nixon gave in Moscow
indicating that detente was irreversible'' in the early 1970's, said
Blackwill. ``It turned out that that wasn't so.''
   ``The danger still exists. ... The Cold War began in Eastern
Europe and it must end there,'' he said, adding that Soviet military
intervention in Poland or Hungary now ``would set back normalization
of East-West relations through the end of the century.''
   ``It is somewhat difficult for me to imagine that the Cold War is
over when today, there are 580,000 members of the Red Army in
Eastern Europe,'' he said. ``After Mr. Gorbachev's unilateral
reductions, which we welcome, which were announced at the United
Nations last December, there will still be 550,000 men of the Red
Army in Eastern Europe. We have a ways to go before the Cold War is
over in Eastern Europe.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
