<FIRST>r a PM-WVaTreasurer     06-20 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WVa Treasurer,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embattled W.Va. Treasurer Retires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Virginia's treasurer announced his
retirement today, averting an impeachment trial on charges he
bungled an investment fund.
   The move preserves A. James Manchin's $2,000-a-month pension,
which he would have lost if convicted by the state Senate next month.
   Manchin announced an end to 41 years of public service at a party
in his office. His retirement is effective July 9, one day before
the trial was to begin.
   ``I cannot in good conscience ask the people of this state to
endure the financial and emotional expenses that would accompany a
lengthy political trial _ and that's what it would be, a political
trial,'' Manchin said.
   The flamboyant Democrat turned 62, making him eligible for an
immediate pension, after he was impeached by the House in March on
17 counts blaming him for an estimated $279 million loss from an
investment fund.
   Lawmakers charged that Manchin didn't know about the losses and
should have, or knew of the losses for more than a year and hid them
from the public.
</TEXT>
