<DOCNO> AP890620-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1515EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-20 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They were in hog heaven over at the
World Pork Expo. There was everything a porker could produce: pork
rinds, pork chops and just plain pork. There was even stuff to help
farmers produce plumper profits.
   ``It's so hot it's going to smoke your hair,'' Martin Yan said as
he stirred spicy fried pork and promoted his cookbook. ``God bless
you and all the pigs in the world. Let's all have one pork dish a
day for the next 365 days.''
   About 75,000 people went hog wild at the second annual Expo, a
three-day pork fest that ended Tuesday. Browsers sampled the latest
pork products and hog farmers examined equipment and research aimed
at improving profits.
   ``I enjoyed the Chinese cooking demonstration,'' said Bobbie
Angstrom of Des Moines, Iowa, who accompanied her husband to the
show. ``I'm glad I didn't go to the shopping mall.''
   At a booth operated by Evans Food Products Co., of Chicago, Bill
Connor popped pork rinds into hot oil and cooked them into the snack
President Bush is said to enjoy. Visitors sampled the rinds _ pieces
of hogs' skin _ plain and with barbecue sauce and cheese.
   ``The acceptance of this product since George Bush became
president has been incredible,'' said Connor, whose company's sales
are up 12 percent over 1988.
   Elanco Products, which manufactures medications for livestock,
set up supermarket meat cases to display pork products, and
demonstrated how the meat is cut and trimmed.
   ``The trend now is convenience food,'' said Randy Buller of
Elanco, holding a flat plastic pack with four strips of bacon.
``Here is a big one _ microwave bacon. The pad in there soaks up the
grease.''
   Lloyd Etzler of the Pork Industry Group offered information on
how hogs can be bred to contain less fat, as well as ideas for
cooking pork.
   ``Our main message is that we have a leaner product, and that
pork will work in a well-balanced diet,'' Etzler said. ``I think
we're changing people's attitudes, but not as fast as we'd like.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Gasparro's artwork is worth a fortune,
but people drop it on the ground every day one cent at a time and
few bother to pick it up.
   For sentimental reasons, Gasparro usually fetches pennies from
the sidewalk.
   Gasparro designed the tails side of the penny that replaced the
wheat-back penny 30 years ago. His initials can be found just to the
right of the Lincoln Memorial's base.
   Occassionally when he gets a penny in change, he'll point out his
work to the cashier.
   ``They think I'm goofy,'' the former chief engraver of the United
States said. ``I'll say, `I designed it, you can see my initials if
you've got good eyesight.'''
   As the man who designed the Susan B. Anthony dollar, he is the
only living person to have sculpted the front and back of a
general-circulation U.S. coin. He also designed the back of the John
F. Kennedy half dollar.
   Gasparro, who asked a reporter not to write his age, said he is
dissappointed the Susan B. Anthony dollar wasn't more popular. He
figures people just couldn't get used to a dollar that doesn't fold.
   But the back of the penny, which he designed in 1958 and was
first issued in 1959 to mark the 150th anniversary of Lincoln's
birth, is the most circulated of his work.
   When he presented his design to his superiors, they told him to
remove the words ``Lincoln Memorial'' from below the relief of the
building and 13 stars that ran around the outer edge of the coin.
   Gasparro agreed, but refused to take out his initials and the
tiny statue of Lincoln between the sixth and seventh columns, two
features his boss said would look like smudges of dirt.
   ``If you do that, it would look like a library,'' he recalled
saying at the time.
   After 38 years at the mint, Gasparro retired in 1981 and has been
sculpting about 15 to 20 commemorative coins a year for private
groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
