<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Shamir     06-20 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Shamir,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Says He Lied To Immigrate to Palestine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, in a rare moment
of candor about his personal life, said Tuesday he was so determined
to come to Jerusalem from Poland in 1935 that he lied to get around
British restrictions.
   Shamir applied and was accepted at the Hebrew University of
Jerusalem that year even though he had no plans to study. The
acceptance paved the way for an entry permit from the British.
   ``I decided that this was the only way,'' he said.
   The Polish-born Shamir, who was leader of a militant Jewish
underground and later a senior officer in Israel's Mossad
intelligence service, usually is tight-lipped about his personal
life.
   He was speaking to about 600 Israelis who were among 2,000 Jews
saved from the Nazi Holocaust with the help of acceptance
certificates from the university between 1932 and 1941.
   Many applicants used the certificates to get around immigration
restrictions, said university spokesman Jerry Barrach. The
university was trying to save as many people as possible, but had to
limit the number of certificates because it was being closely
watched by the British, Barrach said.
   In his 1935 application, the 20-year-old Shamir wrote he had
studied law for a year at Warsaw University to please his parents,
but that Hebrew literature was his true love.
   ``After some months of study, it became clear to me that the only
place where I could fully realize my desires and exercise my
abilities would be the Institute for Jewish Studies at the Hebrew
University,'' wrote Shamir, then known as Icko Yezernicki.
   He also wrote that his family was well-off and would support him.
   The letter ``wasn't too accurate a description of my feelings,''
Shamir conceded Tuesday. ``I had to put my family into debt to be
able to immigrate.''
   He said he spent some of his first days in Jerusalem wandering
around campus and sitting in the library.
   ``I wanted to study, also Hebrew literature, but I couldn't
because I had nothing to live on,'' Shamir told reporters, adding
with a smile: ``In the meantime, I got involved in other things.''
   They included joining Irgun Zvi Leumi, a militant Jewish
underground group that fought British mandatory rule in Palestine.
In 1940, he became a founder and leader of the ``Stern Gang'' which
carried out a campaign of political assassinations and bombings of
British installations. In 1948, the United Nations ended the British
mandate and established the state of Israel.
   Asked whether he was sorry he didn't complete his studies, Shamir
said: ``Not at all. I don't regret anything I did.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
