<FIRST>r w AM-FloridaPanthers     06-20 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Florida Panthers,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Department Acquires Florida Land as Panther Refuge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Department has acquired 25,000
acres of land in southern Florida for a refuge to protect the
state's threatened panthers, the department said Tuesday.
   The land east of Naples and adjacent to the Big Cypress National
Preserve will be the location of the Florida Panther National
Wildlife Refuge to be managed by Interior's Fish and Wildlife
Service.
   The land was purchased for $10 million. An additional 5,000 acres
will be part of the refuge as a result of land exchange.
   ``The Florida panther is one of our country's most endangered
species. It is a symbol of the wilderness amidst the booming
development of South Florida,'' said Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan.
   The Florida panther is among the most critically endangered
mammals in the country, with only an estimated 30 to 50 animals
remaining.
   The new refuge also will provide habitat for a half dozen other
endangered or threatened species including the wood stork, snail
kite, bald eagle, red-cockaded woodpecker, peregrine falcon and
Eastern indigo snake, officials said.
</TEXT>
