<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1520EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MysteryDeaths     06-20 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mystery Deaths,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Confirm Suspect, But No Charges Filed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police confirmed that a convicted rapist now in
custody in two attacks is a suspect in at least some the slayings of
19 young women, most of them crack addicts who exchanged sex for
drug money.
   But no new charges have been filed against Charles Henry Williams
and investigators may never have enough evidence, said Metro-Dade
Homicide Cmdr. Wayne McCarthy.
   ``We've exhausted all leads,'' McCarthy said Monday. ``It's not
like anyone has left a calling card or footprint or anything like
that.''
   All but one of the women were found dead in a low-income area of
Miami and neighboring Dade County starting in September 1986. Most
showed signs of recently having had sex, and initially appeared to
have little or no evidence of trauma on their bodies.
   Almost all had traces of cocaine in their blood and were known
for prostitution, police reports said.
   Police are investigating a second suspect in one of the killings,
which occurred while Williams was in jail, and are looking at a
third man as well, but not as seriously, McCarthy said.
   Williams, who served time for rape in the past and is in jail
facing two additional charges, has denied any involvement in the
killings.
   But McCarthy, noting he could only speak for the 11 Dade County
cases, said Williams ``is a main suspect in some of them.''
   Eleven of the killings occurred in Metro-Dade's juristiction,
seven in Miami and one in Hialeah.
   Williams has been linked with four of the dead women, McCarthy
said. ``He knew them, or he dated them or he did drugs with them,''
he said.
   In addition, relatives and friends of one of the Miami victims
have said she knew Williams.
   Since Williams was arrested in early April on the rape charges,
no women have been found dead in the same manner.
   Miami police spokesman Ray Lang said his department's detectives
have little to say about the case.
   ``Our investigators are cooperating with the county in
investigating Charles Williams' alleged connections with any of the
deaths,'' Lang said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
