<FIRST>r a AM-Manchin     06-20 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manchin,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasurer Announces Retirement at W.Va. Day Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tearful state Treasurer A. James
Manchin on Tuesday announced his retirement, effective the day
before the state Senate was to consider removing him from office.
   Manchin's decision saves his $2,000-a-month pension, which he
could have lost had he been ousted from office for his role in the
loss of $279 million from an investment fund his office supervised.
   ``I cannot in good conscience ask the people of this state to
endure the financial and emotional expenses that would accompany a
lengthy political trial _ and that's what it would be, a political
trial,'' Manchin, 62, said during a West Virginia Day celebration
marking the state's 126th birthday.
   State Del. Rod Berry, one of the five House of Delegates members
who would have helped present the case against Manchin, said he had
mixed feelings.
   ``I think it may have done the state some good to kind of have a
trial in the case because it would have shown the citizens just
exactly what went on in the treasurer's office and hopefully prevent
it from ever happening again,'' Berry said.
   ``On the other hand, I'm certainly glad we don't have to expend
the state's money to put on this trial.''
   He said the trial would have lasted a month and cost $750,000.
   Another member of the House team, Del. Jim Rowe, said a trial
would have given the state bad publicity.
   ``I'm certainly relieved for his benefit as well as the
state's,'' Rowe said. ``I think as things stood this morning, it was
the honorable thing to do. He should have done it a while back.''
   Manchin said he will concentrate on supporting the Special
Olympics, the Spinal Cord Injury Foundation and Ronald McDonald
houses.
   ``The time for my departure is at hand,'' Manchin said, reading
from his letter to Gov. Gaston Caperton announcing his retirement,
effective July 9. ``I have fought a good fight. I have finished my
course. I have kept the faith.''
   Caperton will appoint a temporary successor to Manchin, and
voters in the 1990 general election will select someone to fill the
remaining two years of Manchin's term, Secretary of State Ken
Hechler said.
   Manchin served in the House of Delegates, as secretary of state
and was elected state treasurer twice.
</TEXT>
