<FIRST>r i AM-Palme     06-20 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palme's Son Says He Saw Man Glaring at Parents Before Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Palme-Press, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA JANZON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of Prime Minister Olof Palme
testw the slaying suspect, defendant Carl Gustaf Christer
Pettersson, in a police lineup ``I was shocked ... because the man I
saw was so similar to the picture I had in my mind.''
   Palme, the dominant figure in Swedish politics for more than a
decade, was killed Feb. 28, 1986, as he and his wife, Lisbeth,
walked home from a late movie.
   Pettersson has denied shooting the prime minister.
   The prosecution has accused Pettersson, 42, of waiting for Palme
to emerge from the theater, following the couple for several hundred
yards, then shooting the Swedish leader.
   Marten Palme, a 28-year-old sociologist, said he noticed a man
who looked like Pettersson as he and his girlfriend left his parents
after discussing the film they had just seen together.
   ``I saw him looking at my parents intently. It's possible that he
followed them, but I'm not sure,'' he told the court.
   But under questioning from defense attorney Arne Liljeros, the
younger Palme said he had compared memories of the man's appearance
with his mother's recollections several times since the shooting.
   Also Tuesday, witness Lars-Erik Eriksson told the court that he
had seen a man who looked like Pettersson as Eriksson waited in a
car for his parents to come out of the theater.
   ``I got a little frightened,'' said Eriksson, 29. ``I even locked
the car doors, and I thought it's better not to look too much at
him. This person can explode soon.''
   Asked if he was certain Pettersson was the man he saw, Eriksson
replied, ``Can you ever be 100 percent sure? But I am very sure.''
   Birgitta Wennerling, a 47-year-old painter, said she noticed a
suspicious man as she left an earlier showing of the film.
   He was straining to see over people's heads into the lobby, she
said and ``had a sick, horrid look.'' She and Eriksson independently
picked out Pettersson in police lineups.
   The trial adjourned until Wednesday.
   In a dramatic courtroom confrontation on Monday, Mrs. Palme
pointed to Pettersson and said she was ``absolutely certain'' he was
the man she saw nearby as her husband collapsed with a fatal bullet
wound.
   Mrs. Palme's testimony was crucial for the prosecution, which has
suffered setbacks in trying to establish a motive and breaking the
defendant's alibi.
   Prosecutors have no murder weapon and no witness who saw
Pettersson with a gun in his hand.
   Mrs. Palme said she looked at Pettersson three times after the
shooting, at first for help. The prosecution has claimed no one else
was on the scene who could have shot Palme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
