<HEAD>Sentence in Arson Case Includes Work Fighting Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state forestry director says he's
excited by a judge's decision to require a man convicted of setting
a forest fire to spend 10 days fighting fires.
   ``We're going to be trying to do this every time we turn around
now. Absolutely,'' said William Gillespie, director of the state
forestry division.
   Ralph Brewster Jr., 49, of Delbarton was sentenced after pleading
guilty to setting a fire that destroyed 12,000 acres in the
Delbarton area in November 1987, state forester Coy Mullins said.
   In addition to a 10-day jail sentence, a $500 fine and the 10-day
fire-fighting detail, Brewster also was placed on two years'
probation, Mullins said Monday.
   Brewster initially was charged with setting fire to property
owned by someone else, a felony, and pleaded guilty to destruction
of property, a misdemeanor, the Mingo County circuit clerk's office
said.
   Brewster was sentenced May 22, but Mullins said his office just
learned of the plea and the sentence last week. There was no answer
at Brewster's home.
