<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearCosts     06-20 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Costs,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Proposed New-Style Reactors Won't Help Global Warming
Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nuclear industry's proposed new-generation
reactors, designed to operate more reliably and safely, will not be
available soon enough to help the global warming problem, an
anti-nuclear group said in a report Tuesday.
   The Safe Energy Communication Council said the nuclear industry
was misleading the public by billing the advanced-design reactors as
a partial solution to global atmospheric warming caused by emissions
from fossil fuel plants.
   ``Nuclear power offers a `fools gold' solution to global
warming,'' said Scott Denman, the group's director.
   Alex Antypas, a researcher at the council, said it's too early to
tell whether new reactor designs will prove better and more economic
than the current generation.
   ``It will take at least 10 years to develop and build a single
demonstration plant, and another two or more decades to bring many
of those plants on line,'' Antypas said.
   The proposed new reactors would rely heavily on ``passive''
design features to guard against a melting of the reactor core. A
gas-cooled reactor, for example, uses helium as a coolant instead of
water and its core is encased in graphite. This gives its operators
more time to respond to problems because the gas cannot boil away
and the graphite takes hours to reach a dangerous temperature.
   Antypas said that even if the advanced-design reactors prove more
safe and reliable than the current light-water reactors, the
industry still will not have solved the problem of long-term
disposal of wastes generated by the plants.
   The group said more emphasis should be placed on improving energy
efficiency in transportation, buildings, appliances and utilities
instead of spending billions on new nuclear plants.
   Many in the nuclear industry believe that widespread adoption of
the new reactor technologies is vital to restoring public confidence
in the safety and efficiency of nuclear power.
</TEXT>
