<FIRST>u w PM-TradeConcessions 1stLd-Writethru a0577 06-20 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade Concessions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0577,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Trade Benefits for Poland and Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>EdSUBS grafs 2-3, beginning `s `With no ..with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with House passage of Polish concessions. Picks up 4th graf pvs `That 1974
...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee today
approved trade concessions for Poland and Hungary, two Soviet-bloc
nations that President Bush will visit next month.
   With no debate or dissent, the committee agreed to a bill that
makes exports from Poland eligible for duty-free treatment under the
Generalized System of Preferences.
   The House quickly gave the measure approval by voice vote and
sent it to the Senate.
   A second bill approved by the Ways and Means Committee by voice
vote would allow a five-year extension of most-favored-nation trade
status to Hungary. That has the effect of suspending a law that bars
trade concessions to certain communist nations until the United
States is satisfied they have liberalized emigration policies.
   That 1974 law, known as the Jackson-Vanik Amendment, usually
requires that any exemption be reviewed every year. Rep. Richard
Schulze, R-Pa., complained because the suspension for Hungary's
benefit would be subject to a review only after five years.
   ``We take a very important step when we change Jackson-Vanik,''
Schulze said. ``It's symbolic around the world.''
   Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., who chairs the committee's trade
subcommittee, said the five-year suspension is justified because no
emigration complaints against Hungary are pending. ``Hungary, of all
nations, has demonstrated its continued interest in freedom,'' he
said.
   Few American investors are willing to put their money into
Hungary and take the risk of having the United States withdraw trade
concessions after only a year, Gibbons added.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the committee, said it
is expected that Congress will complete action on the concessions
this week.
</TEXT>
