<FIRST>u a AM-AmericanDreamKids Bjt   06-20 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American Dream Kids, Bjt,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thirteen of 17 Boston High School Valedictorians Born Outside US</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bich Nguyen spoke almost no English and was too
afraid to talk when she entered South Boston High School two years
ago. Now she's at the head of her class and among a remarkable array
of this year's valedictorians at Boston high schools.
   The list includes students born in Vietnam, China, El Salvador,
Cape Verde, Jamaica, Italy and Czechoslovakia. One of the four
U.S.-born graduates among the 17 scholars is a ward of the state.
   The explanation for the unusual mix lies in a lot of new faces in
the city and a lot of old values, educators say.
   ``When you've been running for your life in the jungles just to
get your freedom, you're not looking for the good life; you're
looking for survival. They come in and they're willing to do
anything and work anywhere. It's the same with all immigrants,''
Jerome Winegar, principal of the 900-student South Boston High
School, said Tuesday.
   Duc Hoang Vo, valedictorian at the 1,000-student Boston Technical
High School, was beaten by Thai pirates when his family fled Vietnam
by boat. His sister was kidnapped during the voyage.
   He said he had to do well; he owed his family.
   ``When my (parents) left their country they left everything
behind,'' said Vo, 18, who emigrated seven years ago. ``They dropped
everything at once, including my grandmother, just to give us a
better future.''
   ``Being a minority, I work harder for a better future, success
and to make my parents proud,'' said Vo, who will study medical
engineering on a full scholarship at Boston University this fall.
   Nguyen's family also made some wrenching decisions to get her
into an American school.
   Nguyen, who has a full scholarship to Emmanuel College, came here
with her father. Her mother, two brothers and a sister were left
behind in Vietnam because there wasn't enough money for all of them
to emigrate.
   She and her father floated seven days and nights without food or
water before they were picked up by an American ship.
   She said she wants from an education what she and her father, who
was imprisoned for several years after the fall of Saigon, could not
get in Vietnam.
   ``Money is important but I want to have the power of knowledge,''
said Nguyen. ``The knowledge can do something the money can't do. It
can get respect from other people.''
   She earned it in South Boston, site of many bitter racial clashes
during forced busing of the 1970s.
   Rolando Cabrera, 17, said he and his family felt they could not
make enough money in El Salvador, and his parents did not want their
three sons serving in the army.
   He said he learned good work habits in his home country, where
teachers and education are widely respected. He is headed for the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
   Massima Chiocca, 17, of East Boston High School, said he'd
noticed the high number of foreign-born students who were
valedictorians this year.
   Chiocca, whose family came to the United States from Italy about
three years ago, said Americans might be taking their education for
granted.
   ``Seems like people from other countries are taking over this
place. I'm one of them, but there's enough space for a lot of
people,'' he said.
   ``Since I started school in first grade my mother always pushed
me to do my best,'' said Chiocca, who will attend Harvard University
in the fall.
   Clarice Pereira, 22, a deaf immigrant from Cape Verde, a former
Portuguese colony off the coast of Africa, spoke only Portuguese
when she arrived in 1982, said Carol Donohoe, an adviser at the
Horace Mann School for the Deaf.
   ``They come here and see the possibilities and they know it means
work if they want to succeed,'' Donohoe said.
</TEXT>
