<FIRST>r a AM-BoatBuilderKilled     06-20 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boat Builder Killed,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Designer of Reconstructed `Half Moon' Dies in Port Mishap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENSSELAER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicholas Benton, the designer and builder
of the ``Half Moon,'' a full-size replica of Henry Hudson's
17th-century exploration ship, died when the mast of a boat he was
working on collapsed. He was 35.
   Benton, of Middletown, R.I., was working Monday morning in the
Port of Rensselaer along the Hudson River when a mast snapped on the
schooner ``Domino Effect'' and Benton fell 75 feet to the deck.
   He later died of ``shock and hemorrhage due to multiple trauma''
at Albany Medical Center, according to Barbara Cavanaugh,
confidential secretary to the Albany County coroner. Benton died on
his birthday.
   A master ship-rigger and founding member of the Colonial Maritime
Association, Benton is survived by a wife, Debbie, and three
preschool-aged sons, Carol McLeod of McLeod Public Relations of
Albany said.
   McLeod is publicist for the $1 million Half Moon project which is
aiming to teach Americans about the accomplishments of Hudson and of
people of Dutch heritage in America. She said the project would
continue.
   The 85-foot, 120-ton Half Moon took about a year to build. It was
christened June 10 at the Port of Albany and is to begin a goodwill
voyage to several Northeastern ports on July 5.
   At the christening ceremonies, Benton told a crowd of about 500
people that ``what the sea separates, the shipbuilder unites.''
   Ernest Cowan, who has been responsible for the woodworking on the
``Half Moon'' replica, arrived Monday in Albany to take over the
project, McLeod said.
   The ship Benton was working on at the time of his death was a
175-foot schooner owned by Domino's Pizza Inc.
</TEXT>
