<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Sculptor     06-20 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Sculptor,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emigre Artist Returns for Lecture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sculptor and philosopher Ernst Neizvestny, who
emigrated from the Soviet Union in 1976, said Tuesday that Karl Marx
was a good critic of 19th century capitalism but a bad prophet.
   Neizvestny, who gained fame for his differences over art with
former Soviet leader Nikita S. Khrushchev, spoke to about 500 people
as part of a Moscow Summer School series of lectures on democracy,
freedom and free-market economics.
   The artist did not elaborate on Marx, whose prediction that
capitalism will inevitably self-destruct into communism is taught to
every schoolchild in the Soviet Union. The audience responded to the
comment with quiet laughter and grunts of acknowledgement.
   Neizvestny had a rocky relationship with Khrushchev. They met
when the Soviet leader came to a rare exhibition of modern art and
termed Neizvestny's work ``garbage.'' The sculptor strode up and
started arguing.
   Khrushchev later asked Neizvestny to create his grave monument,
which marks the final resting place of the former Soviet leader in
Novodevichy Cemetery in Moscow.
   The 64-year-old sculptor told his audience the flood of famous
Soviet artists and performers who have left their homeland will stop
when they are certain they can leave the Soviet Union and know they
can return _ and then leave again.
   ``I always had a fear of being parochial,'' for lack of the
ability to travel, he said. Emigration clearly solved that, he said.
   But he also found that his life in the Soviet Union left him
afraid only of prison and death, so less-serious difficulties such
as poverty or the opinions of others have had little effect.
   The lecture was arranged by the American Foreign Policy Council
and a group seeking to establish an American university in Moscow.
</TEXT>
