<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChildHealth     06-20 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Health,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Oppose Measures to Make Them Expand Eligibility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Physicians and children's advocates told
Congress on Tuesday that making more women eligible for Medicaid
prenatal care would help reduce the nation's high rate of infant
deaths.
   However, the states, which share the cost of the health insurance
program for the poor with the federal government, opposed measures
backed by the administration and members of Congress requiring
states to expand eligibility in their Medicaid programs.
   The administration is proposing to require states to admit to
their Medicaid programs women and infants with incomes up to 130
percent of poverty. Sens. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, and John Chafee,
R-R.I., introduced a bill Monday to require coverage for women and
children up to 185 percent of poverty.
   The need for prenatal care to reduce infant mortality ``has to be
one of the nation's most pressing problems,'' Bentsen said at
Tuesday's hearing of the Senate Finance Committee, which he chairs.
   ``White American babies now die at a greater rate than babies
born in Singapore,'' he said. ``Minority babies born in Washington
today have a greater chance of dying before their first birthday
than babies in Cuba.''
   The U.S. infant mortality rate ranks 20th among industrialized
nations, according to the Public Health Service.
   A third of all pregnant women are not receiving prenatal care,
Bentsen said, and one in five children have no health insurance.
   ``The best way to ensure that a child will begin life as healthy
as possible is to ensure the health of the mother during pregnancy
through prenatal care,'' said Kay Johnson of the Children's Defense
Fund.
   Richard H. Schwarz of the American College of Obstetricians and
Gynecologists said the evidence is overwhelming that prenatal care
reduces low birthweight. This condition, he said, is associated with
two-thirds of neonatal deaths and 20 percent of postnatal deaths.
   Yet, Medicaid falls far short of meeting the health-care needs of
poor women and children, witnesses said.
   Current law gives states until July 1, 1990, to cover all
pregnant women and infants with incomes below the poverty line.
   Forty-four states now provide coverage to pregnant women and
infants with family income below the poverty line, and 15 states
provide such coverage for women and infants with incomes up to 185
percent of poverty, according to the National Governors' Association.
   Bentsen's measure would require coverage for pregnant women and
children up to age 6 with incomes below 185 percent of poverty, or
$22,385 for a family of four, by Jan. 1, 1991. It would add 300,000
women and 1.6 million children.
   The change would cost about $1 billion annually, a cost that
would have to be matched by the states.
   The administration's proposal would add a total of 374,000 women
and children to the program and would pay for the change by reducing
state matching funds for administrative costs.
   The states, however, oppose ``any further mandated eligibility
requirements in the Medicaid program,'' said Raymond C. Scheppach,
executive director of the National Governors' Association.
   In the last year and a half, states have had to absorb the costs
of sweeping changes in nursing home care and expanded benefits for
the elderly, he said.
   Yet, states voluntarily have been moving to expand their Medicaid
programs to make more women, infants and children eligible for
benefits and will continue to make improvements as their budgets
allow, he said.
   ``Individual states are in the best position to decide how
Medicaid funds should be spent to assist citizens who are in need,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
