<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-US     06-20 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-US,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Secret Police Interrogating U.S. Photographer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan secret police Tuesday
interrogated an American photographer captured while traveling with
Moslem guerrillas, diplomatic sources said.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani confirmed an
American was being interrogated for his ``ill intentions.''
   ``He is being interrogated in Kabul, but we would like to assure
that there will be no violent actions against him.'' Amani said the
American entered Afghanistan illegally.
   Free-lance photographer Tony O'Brien of Santa Fe, N.M., was
caught Wednesday in Kabul, guerrilla sources in Pakistan said.
O'Brien, 43, is with Picture Group photo agency and was on
assignment for Life magazine.
   ``We were told he probably was arrested for illegally entering
the country,'' said the agency's president, Don Abood. ``He had no
visa. He probably went in through Pakistan and got caught. We're not
sure what the circumstances were.''
   He said O'Brien had been covering the Afghan war from the
Pakistani frontier city of Peshawar.
   Diplomatic sources speaking on condition of anonymity said
O'Brien was being questioned by the Afghan secret police, called
Khad, in one of their offices in the capital.
   Amani said the American entered Afghanistan without valid travel
documents. ``It is our right to arrest him,'' he said. ``We are
allowing journalists to come to Afghanistan and stay here. Why did
he choose to come in company of terrorists? This gives us a right to
assume that he is a saboteur, he may even be a spy.''
   Amani said the prisoner was in good health and his family had
approached the Afghan Embassy in Washington.
   ``But we have no other contacts with the United States
government,'' he said.
   Washington closed its embassy in Kabul last winter, citing fears
of a bloodbath after the Soviet army ended nine years of involvement
in the war and left Afghanistan in February.
   In the past five years, seven foreigners have been arrested in
Afghanistan, according to Amani. He said five were journalists and
two were West German physicians. All were released after their
countries intervened, Amani said.
   The guerrillas have been fighting the Soviet-backed Kabul
government for 11 years with help mainly from the United States and
Pakistan.
   O'Brien had made several trips into Afghanistan with the
guerrillas and his photographs have appeared in major U.S.
publications.
</TEXT>
