<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Procurement     06-20 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Procurement,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Subcommittee Accepts Cheney Procurement Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House Armed Services subcommittee voted
Tuesday to accept Defense Secretary Dick Cheney's $69 billion
procurement budget with no add-ons, endorsing a proposal from the
panel's Democratic chairman by a slim margin.
   The procurement and military nuclear systems subcommittee, by a
vote of 10-9, approved the amendment of Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., who
had urged members to give Cheney a vote of confidence and prevent
add-ons totaling $7.2 billion.
   The full House Armed Services Committee will vote on the
amendment next week.
   ``While the budget may not be perfect, it's a darn good product _
especially given the 39 days Dick Cheney had to put it together,''
Aspin told the panel.
   Aspin and two other Democrats _ Ike Skelton of Missouri and
Richard Ray of Georgia _ joined seven of the panel's eight
Republicans in approving the measure.
   Rep. Robert W. Davis of Ohio was the lone GOP member to vote
against the plan, which basically removes the right of members to
rewrite the $300 billion fiscal 1990 budget to restore local
projects canceled by Cheney.
   Pentagon spokesman Fred Hoffman said he was pleased to hear about
the vote.
   Aspin refused to give odds on the measure's chance of winning
approval in the full committee, but called the subcommittee's
acceptance of a budget that terminates programs ``staggering.''
   Some Democratic members complained that approval of the measure
could signal the end of the subcommittee's authority.
   ``A yes vote ... would be abrogating ourselves out of business,''
said Rep. Frank McCloskey, D-Ind., who voted against the amendment.
   Rep. Norman Sisisky, D-Va., who also opposed the amendment, said
approval was not a vote of confidence for Cheney because there was
no guarantee that the defense budget wouldn't be changed on the
House floor.
   ``I think I'm giving up my rights if I have to vote for something
that I can only change on the floor,'' Sisisky said. ``I think we're
making a big mistake and it has nothing to do with a vote of
confidence.''
   Some members have pressed for restoring the Navy F-14D Tomcat
fighter and Marine V-22 Osprey, which Cheney canceled, at the
expense of other projects. If restored, the F-14D would add $366
million and the V-22 $700 million.
   Other possible add-ons include $55 million in new equipment for
the Navy P-3 anti-submarine aircraft, $436 million for Air Force
C-130s and $240 million for heavy trucks made in Oshkosh, Wis.
   McCloskey argued that although Aspin didn't strong-arm his
Democratic colleagues on the amendment, ``there are people on that
side who are very much for the Osprey that ... have been
strong-armed by the secretary of defense.''
   Rep. John G. Rowland, R-Conn., said ``no one on this side of the
aisle was strong-armed.''
   Cheney, former House Republican whip who served as representative
from Wyoming, has the ``mildest, softest touches on the Hill,''
Rowland said.
   Aspin said after the vote that lobbying was fierce on both sides,
with President Bush and the Northrop Corp. pushing for adoption of
the amendment.
   Northrop, which manufactures the B-2 stealth bomber, fears losing
funds for its program to support other defense projects.
   Lobbying against the plan were Grumman Corp., builder of the
F-14, and the alumni association of the Marine Corps, backers of the
V-22 Osprey.
   Shortly after the vote, Rep. Thomas J. Downey, D-N.Y., said he
would fight to save the F-14, which is manufactured in Bethpage,
Long Island.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
