<FIRST>r a AM-MockInvasion 1stLd-Writethru a0630 06-20 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mock Invasion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Invites Navy To Reschedule Mock Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Navy accepting invitation.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `The exercise...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has accepted the city's invitation
to reschedule a mock beach assault that was canceled after religious
and peace groups opposed it.
   The City Council, after hearing emotional testimony during a
meeting Monday night, voted 6-3 to extend the invitation.
   Lt. Commander Luanne Smith, executive officer of the Navy
Recruiting District in Minneapolis, said Tuesday the Navy will
contact city officials soon about reviving the Park Point mock
assault.
   The exercise involving 200 Marines was to be part of a recruiting
and goodwill visit July 21-23 by the Boulder, a tank landing ship.
   City Council President Joyce Benson and members of several
religious and peace groups earlier had persuaded the Navy to cancel
the show. Many had complained that it would glorify war and damage
the Lake Superior beach.
   The council's action followed emotional testimony by veterans and
peace activists.
   Those in favor of the mock assault argued that the military needs
such exercises to train. Some said such shows instill valuable pride
in the military, enhance recruiting and demonstrate strength.
   ``If you're strong, nobody will muck around with you,'' said
veteran Harvey Solon.
   Those against the assault said it would glorify violence, falsely
advertise military jobs as glamorous and advocate wasting money that
could be spent on social needs.
   ``The real issue is political,'' said veteran Mark Skinner.
``This is a demonstration on the part of the Pentagon to get support
for military spending.''
</TEXT>
