<FIRST>u a AM-NeighborhoodBattle Bjt   06-20 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Neighborhood Battle, Bjt,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighborhood Fights Crime-Linked Apartment Building</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Francisco Street residents are tired of
living in fear because of rampant drug dealing and prostitution in
their neighborhood. So they're fighting back _ in small claims court.
   Fifteen homeowners and renters have filed mental anguish claims
for $2,000 each against the owner of the five-unit apartment
building residents contend is the wellspring of neighborhood crime,
illicit sex and drugs, all linked to sales of cheap, potent crack
cocaine.
   Instead of soda cans and drifting newspapers, the neighborhood of
modest Victorians and new condominiums has been littered with used
syringes and condoms.
   ``I can't walk down the street anytime,'' said Elisa Flores, 18.
``People think I'm a prostitute.''
   Her 15-year-old brother was robbed at gunpoint. One neighbor
found a bloody syringe next to his child's swing. A second
encountered a prostitute having sex on a picnic bench outside his
back door at noon.
   Kenneth Martin, who has lived in the area for four years, said
the neighborhood was being ruined by drug dealing on the sidewalks
and prostitution in the schoolyard, constant traffic and the sounds
of fighting inside two apartments linked to narcotics sales.
   ``Our purpose is not to gouge anyone for lots of money, but to
get the criminality removed,'' Martin said.
   Bonnie Perocier, who has lived on Francisco Street for 29 years,
said her car has been broken into twice and items have been stolen
from her garage. She said a man across the street was burglarized
twice by thieves who ripped his deadbolt locks off with crowbars.
   ``He came back Sunday morning and even his underwear was gone,
and he was wondering what he was going to wear to work,'' Perocier
said.
   Residents say the drug and crime problems have grown worse in the
past year and a half.
   The small claims filed in Berkeley-Albany Municipal Court blame
the apartment building owner for negligence, creating a nuisance and
endangering the neighborhood. Judge Jennie Rhine will receive final
evidence in the case Wednesday and will rule later.
   Martin said the small claims idea stemmed from news about a
successful lawsuit by South San Francisco homeowners against airport
officials who promised to abate noise but failed to follow through.
   Police spokesman Capt. Bobby Miller said the two-story apartment
building in the middle of the block is well-known to police, who
have served search warrants and made arrests there.
   Molly Wetzel, who lives across the street, said she contacted
owner Percy Davis about the problems there several times since last
October.
   Davis' attorney, Michael Sims, contends Davis filed a notice on
April 18 to evict the alleged trouble-makers. Sims said Davis
complained that Berkeley's strict rent control law makes eviction
difficult.
   About the troublesome tenants, Sims said Davis isn't ``accepting
any responsibility for their criminal behavior.''
   Repeated calls to Davis were not returned.
   Martin said the apartment tenants have been evicted or have
agreed to move soon. ``All we know is that the problem is at last
being solved,'' he said.
   ``I know Mr. Davis now has promised to clean this situation up,
but the time it has taken has ruined our lives,'' said the resident
who found the bloody syringe. He did not want to be identified.
   The neighborhood, in Berkeley's flatlands about a mile west of
the University of California campus, has long had crime problems
because of a busy thoroughfare nearby. Residents acknowledge that
getting new neighbors in the apartment building won't eliminate all
of their problems, but it will help.
   ``We will not do away with the petty kind of burglary that you
have everywhere in West Berkeley, but the problems of prostitution
and fear on the street definitely will go away,'' Martin said. ``If
it can stay clean a year, I believe it will be solved.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
