<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Boeing     06-20 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Boeing,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airlines Say Boeing Groundings Haven't Disrupted Schedules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British airlines, whose Boeing 737-400s were
grounded for engine tests, said Tuesday they have managed to keep to
schedule.
   British Midland Airways and DanAir, the largest airlines
operating the plane, said they were using spare aircraft or
borrowing replacements from other airlines. Each has two 737-400s.
   Eight more 737-400s are operated by Novair, Air Europe and Air
UK-Leisure, which also reported no difficulties meeting schedules.
   DanAir spokesman Peter Clegg said the airlines were hoping for
word Wednesday on the outcome of inspections by SNECMA of France,
the company that manufactures the CFM56-3C engines jointly with
General Electric of the United States.
   The 12 planes were grounded by Britain's Civil Aviation Authority
eight days ago after two incidents in which Boeing 737-400s were
forced to make emergency landings because engine fan blades broke.
   One was a British Midland plane and the other a DanAir plane.
Their engines were shipped to SNECMA's plant for inspection. The
other aircraft are being checked by their companies in Britain.
   Boeing and CFM International, the SNECMA-General Electric
partnership, recommended a week ago that airlines operating planes
with such engines ground the aircraft until the engines can be
replaced or adjusted to operate at lower thrust levels.
   The Federal Aviation Administration issued a similar order the
next day for U.S. airlines. The only U.S. planes affected were five
operated by USAir, and these have received new engines.
</TEXT>
