<FIRST>u w AM-US-Nicaragua     06-20 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Rejects Nicaraguan Offer for Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Tuesday rejected a
Nicaraguan offer to hold talks on improving relations, saying that
there can be no accommodation unless certain conditions are met
including free and fair elections.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega said Monday he had asked
Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo to go to Washington with the
government's proposal for opening talks on normalizing relations.
   There have been no substantive talks between officials of the two
countries in more than four years.
   State Department press officer Rudi Boone said an improvement in
relations depends on holding free and fair elections under
international supervision, the beginning of a genuine dialogue with
the Nicaraguan opposition and ``an end to Nicaraguan support for
subversion in the region.''
   The Bush administration has accused the Sandinista government of
increasing its support for leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   The administration also has been exerting heavy diplomatic and
economic pressure on Nicaragua to ensure that opposition parties are
able to compete fairly in national elections set for next February.
   Boone said Nicaragua's professed intention of improving relations
contrasts sharply with several recent actions by the Sandinista
government, including the expulsion of two U.S. diplomats.
   The envoys were accused of fomenting labor unrest but the State
Department has insisted they engaged in no wrongdoing.
   After his meeting Monday with Obando y Bravo, Ortega told
reporters, he had asked the prelate to ``mediate with President Bush
so that a fluid dialogue can develop. We are willing to develop a
dialogue with the North American government so foundations can be
laid for normalizing relations between Nicaragua and the United
States.''
   Although the United States no longer provides military aid to the
Nicaraguan resistance, a U.S. trade embargo imposed five years ago
remains in effect and has contributed to the country's steep
economic decline.
</TEXT>
