<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1814EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GalloTrademark     06-20 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gallo Trademark,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Younger Brother Can't Use Name as Trademark on Cheese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ernest and Julio Gallo, owners of the
world's largest winery, won the right Tuesday to keep the younger
brother they raised from using his own name as a trademark for his
own cheese.
   A federal judge concluded that use of the name Joseph Gallo on
retail cheese is misleading because many consumers assume the brand
is connected with E &amp; J Gallo winery. Joseph Gallo sells about
10,000 tons of grapes a year from his vineyards to his brothers but
has no other connection with their winery, based at Modesto, 90
miles southeast of San Francisco.
   ``There is substantial evidence of actual confusion,'' U.S.
District Judge Robert E. Coyle wrote, citing retailers who asked if
the cheese and wine were connected.
   However, the judge's permanent injunction permits Joseph Gallo to
use his name as a signature or in block letters below the words
designating the variety of cheese if the label also includes a
prominent trademark above that does not include the word Gallo.
   Joseph Gallo's attorney, Denis Rice of San Francisco, said he
expects to win on appeal. He criticized Coyle for appearing to use
arguments by winery attorneys verbatim in his brief and failing to
submit a decision separate from the findings and injunction.
   Rice said the findings failed to deal adequately with the
question of whether ``a person is entitled to use his own full name
on his own product.''
   However, Coyle's findings addressed the dilemma of using a common
name that also is a well-known brand.
   ``If every person named Gallo were entitled to use Gallo as a
consumer trademark, Gallo might be adopted as a trademark on any
imaginable product,'' Coyle wrote. ``Such proliferation of uses
would destroy the unique nature of the Gallo brand, its
distinctiveness and its commercial value.''
   A month-long trial last fall offered rare glimpses of the
family-owned winery's development from a provider of bulk wines
without a brand during the Depression to fame and fortune for its
cheap wines _ first Thunderbird in the 1950s, later the Gallo brand
itself. Gallo Winery's sales now total $1 billion a year.
   A Gallo attorney said during an opening statement that in 1933 _
six weeks after their father killed ther mother, then committed
suicide _ Ernest and Julio Gallo began making wine with knowledge
gained from a book they got at the public library. Julio, now 79,
has handled the winemaking ever since while Ernest, 80, became a
widely recognized marketing expert.
   Even though they raised younger brother Joseph, now 67, after the
deaths of their parents, the winery Gallos sued him after he began
using his name on cheese in the mid 1980s.
   Winery attorney Oliver Wanger said Tuesday that Ernest and Julio
had to protect their trademark and a licensing agreement that let
Gallo Salami Co. use the Gallo name on cheese under an agreement by
which winery inspectors checked that brand's quality. Gallo Salami
Co. has no other connection to the three Gallo brothers.
   Wanger said Ernest and Julio were reluctant to sue their brother
but were rebuffed when they offered to license him to use the Gallo
trademark if the winery were allowed reasonable quality control over
his cheese.
   Coyle also commented on the issue of quality control, saying the
winery and Gallo Salami ``have reasonable grounds to be concerned
that sale of cheeses by defendants under the Joseph Gallo brand
creates an undue and unnecessary risk of a serious health problem
resulting from the sale of Joseph Gallo-brand cheese that may injure
the Gallo brand.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
