<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Scholars     06-20 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Scholars,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Presidential Scholars Should Serve Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By Christopher Connell</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday told the 141
teenagers who are this year's Presidential Scholars they are doubly
bound to answer his call to community service.
   Calling them ``some of the best and brightest students in
American education,'' Bush said, ``While already you've done much, I
know you will do more _ and not for yourselves alone, but for nation
and neighbor.''
   Bush was joined by his wife Barbara and Secretary of Education
Lauro Cavazos for the ceremony held under threatening skies on the
South Lawn of the White House.
   Bush, who is staging another White House event on Wednesday to
launch his youth service initiative and will follow up with a speech
in New York on Thursday, said, ``An educated person also has duties
and responsibilities.''
   ``The definition of a successful life must include serving
others. That goes double for America's best,'' he told the
Presidential Scholars, who hail from all 50 states, the District of
Columbia, U.S. territories and even from American families living
abroad.
   They were chosen by a commission _ 121 for academic achievements,
leadership, character and ideals, and 20 for artistic
accomplishments.
   Each Presidential Scholar got to bring his or her most
influential teacher to Washington to share in the accolades, a
five-day whirlwind of seminars, speeches, dinners and festivities
that concludes Wednesday.
   ``Many have labored to share their knowledge with you and you can
give them no greater gift than to share your knowledge with
others,'' Bush said.
   Bush noted that one of the scholars, Clarity Haynes of Duke
Ellington School of the Arts in Washington, D.C., speaks both
Portuguese and Spanish.
   ``I'm a little jealous. Some say I'm not even fluent in
English,'' Bush joked.
   He quoted the poet James Lowell's words, ``If youth be a defect,
it is one we outgrow only too soon.''
   ``I hope you'll accept some counsel from one who's a little long
in the tooth, maybe. But if youth is a defect, treasure it as many
years as you can,'' said Bush.
</TEXT>
