<HEAD>Five Win Frankel Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Americans were selected as the first
winners of the Charles Frankel Prize for their efforts to bring a
broad range of knowledge to the public, the National Endowment for
the Humanities announced Tuesday.
   The $5,000 prizes were named for the late Columbia University
professor who served as the first head of the National Humanities
Center.
   The prizes were established to honor people who strive to help
the public understand great themes and ideas, reported Endowment
Chairman Lynne V. Cheney.
   The winners are:
   _Daniel J. Boorstin, librarian of Congress emeritus and the
author of several books on American history and culture.
   _Willard L. ``Sandy'' Boyd, president of the Field Museum of
History in Chicago.
   _Americo Paredes, professor emeritus at the University of Texas
at Austin and developer of numerous programs on folklore and
Mexican-American culture.
   _Patricia L. Bates, developer of a program for reading and
discussion groups in use in libraries across the country.
   _Clay S. Jenkinson, a leader in the revival of the Chautauqua
effort to educate the public on the lives of outstanding people in
history, philosophy, arts and politics.
