<FIRST>r w AM-Backhauling     06-20 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Backhauling,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smith Bill Would Prohibit Hauling Waste, Food in Same Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trucks hauling food could not carry garbage
under a bill introduced in the House by Rep. Chris Smith, R-N.J., to
head off what he said was a growing health hazard.
   ``Drivers who are bringing meat, produce and grain products from
the Midwest to the East Coast are often returning with bales of
solid waste to be disposed of in landfills,'' Smith said.
   Smith's bill would require the Department of Transportation to
adopt regulations prohibiting any vehicle that carries solid waste
or hazardous waste from being used to transport food.
   Violators would be punished with criminal penalties of up to
$350,000 and five years in jail.
   In a one-minute address to the House on Monday, Smith said that
the practice of carrying both food and garbage appears to be
increasing as landfills in eastern states reach capacity.
   New Jersey produces about 15,000 tons, or 750 truckloads, of
solid waste daily to be sent to landfills in western Pennsylvania
and Ohio, Smith said.
   ``Although these trucks must be licensed by New Jersey to haul
garbage within or out of state, there are no requirements which
prevent these same trucks from returning with a cargo of food,''
Smith said.
</TEXT>
