<FIRST>r w AM-Aerodyne-Pentagon     06-20 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aerodyne-Pentagon,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Says No Harm Done by Substitutions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Aerodyne Indictments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Armed Services have yet to detect any
safety problems because of the alleged illegal substitution of scrap
metal for designated alloys in engines for 5,000 military aircraft,
the Pentagon said Tuesday.
   According to a fraud indictment Monday in Tampa, Fla., of three
former executives of Aerodyne Investment Casings Inc., the company
used scrap in making turbine blades of the type used in 22,000 jet
aircraft, helicopters and tanks.
   ``Now, it's estimated that 5,000 aircraft have been equipped with
these parts since 1982,'' said Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams.
``Two million hours have been accrued on the aircraft without any
known related incidents.
   ``There has been no noticeable degradation in performance using
that 50-percent mixture.''
   The blades were used in T-53 engine that's used on the Huey,
Cobra and Mohawk helicopters for the Army, he said.
   The Army suspended the contractor last Aug. 16 ``because of the
evidence of Aerodyne's use of nonspecified alloys in making parts''
said Brown.
   The grand jury indicted three former Aerodyne executives, Russell
K. Baker Sr. and Russell K. Baker Jr., and Carman Eugene Alexander.
   Williams said the alleged fraud was discovered by the Defense
Department's inspector general, who notified the military services
and the Defense Logistics Agency.
   Since then ``a new source has been since required to produce the
parts,'' said Williams.
   It was not immediately clear what steps the services had taken to
cope with the alleged substitution.
</TEXT>
