<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Spill     06-20 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Spill,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Approves Measure to Deal with Oil Spills</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Oil Spill Plan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate committee approved a bill Tuesday
designed to deal with oil spills and try to prevent them through
such steps as random alcohol testing of crews and improved radar
systems for tracking tankers.
   The Oil Tanker Navigation Safety Act of 1989 deals directly with
Alaska's Prince William Sound, where Exxon continues cleaning up a
massive spill, and would also affect tanker operations elsewhere.
   Meanwhile, Transporation Secretary Samuel Skinner announced a
comprehensive inspection of the 800-mile Alaska pipeline. He
indicated that the March 24 rupture of the Exxon Valdez oil tanker
prompted the inspection, originally set for 1991.
   ``The Exxon Valdez oil spill has taught us a valuable lesson: the
need to avoid complacency when it comes to protecting our
environment,'' Skinner said.
   He said the inspection will review operating pressures, repair
procedures, protective coating requirements, routine inspection
schedules and the electric current used to retard corrosion, along
with oil spill contingency plans for the pipeline.
   Skinner also sent Congress a proposed bill to give the Coast
Guard broader authority over mariners, including revocation of their
certification if they have a record of drunken driving.
   That and several other provisions already were in the bill
approved without opposition by the Senate Commerce, Science and
Transportation Committee.
   The bill, backed by Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, would open
highway driving records of merchant mariners to the Coast Guard,
provide for random and other alcohol testing of people in
safety-senstive jobs on tankers and improve radar systems to aid the
tracking of ships through potentially hazardous areas.
   It also requires the secretary of transportation to examine
several other safety steps and sets guidelines for oil spill
contingency plans, including requiring some oil spill cleanup
equipment to be prepositioned at strategic locations and other
equipment to be carried aboard tankers.
   The legislation, consolidating six proposed bills arising from
three Senate hearings on the Alaska spill, was sent to the full
Senate as the oil industry unveiled its own plan for responding to
major spills.
   The industry announced it would spend $250 million to set up a
network of response teams capable of handling an accident as large
as the March 24 disaster involving the Exxon Valdez.
   The Senate bill would require at least three persons to be on the
bridge of a tanker in certain waters, including the sound. The Exxon
Valdez's captain had gone below deck and turned the helm over to his
third mate, who was not licensed to navigate the sound. The captain,
Joseph Hazelwood, faces several charges in connection with the
incident.
   The Senate measure would allow suspension of a merchant marine's
license, following a hearing, for being drunk on the job or if there
is a record of a highway driver's license being suspended or revoked
within the previous five years for alcohol or drug use.
   The legislation instructs the transportation secretary to examine
whether newly constructed tankers should be built with double hulls
or double bottoms and also to conduct a study of whether the size of
tankers being built is a factor in oil spills. The Exxon Valdez
carried over 50 million gallons.
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., said he would propose on the Senate
floor an amendment that would impose financial punishment on
companies responsible for oil spills, including a possible giving up
of all profits for one year if in a case of ``gross or willful
negligence.'' The money would go into an environmental fund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
