<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle-Trade 1stLd-Writethru a0656 06-20 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0656,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Promises to Shore Up U.S. Trade Interests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs `I share ...' with 1 graf to CORRECT that
National Foreign Trade Council is separate from National Association of
Manufacturers and ADD third group. Picks up 4th graf pvs `The Council ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's committee to enhance U.S.
trade competitiveness began work Tuesday as Vice President Dan
Quayle promised to shore up U.S. interests against the consolidation
of European markets.
   Quayle, chairman of the Council on Competitiveness, said the
European Community's plan to restructure its economies into a single
European market by 1992 has caused concern among U.S. businesses.
   ``I share some of those concerns, but fundamentally EC-92 is both
a challenge and an opportunity for the United States,'' he said in a
speech to the National Foreign Trade Council, the National
Association of Manufacturers and the Coalition For Employment
Through Exports.
   The Council on Competitiveness, Quayle said, will review federal
laws to ensure they don't unfairly restrict U.S. companies against
European competitors.
   The vice president said the council also would ensure United
States access to and fair competition in the single European market,
and would re-evaluate policies on deregulation of financial
institutions and anti-trust restrictions.
   American companies complain that antitrust measures prevent them
from competing fairly because European countries are not restrained
by the same standards.
   Many of the antitrust policies are ``anachronistic in this age of
global competition,'' Quayle said, adding that merger law reform is
needed.
   ``We need to consider reducing present incentives for price
antitrust litigation,'' he said.
   The vice president said the area of biotechnology, in which the
United States has been a leader, will be reviewed.
   ``The key to our success in marketing new biotechnology products
has been a sensible regulatory regime that applies basic
competitiveness principles,'' he said, but cautioned against
unnecessary regulatory burdens on product development.
   ``We need to consider ways to improve incentives for private
sector investment,'' Quayle said, citing Bush's proposal to reduce
the capital gains tax, make permanent tax credit payments for
research and development and ease the patent applications process.
   The Council on Competitiveness, whose members include cabinet
members involved with trade issues, was set up by Bush to continue
the work of President Reagan's task force. Reagan's task force dealt
with eliminating excessive government regulation.
</TEXT>
