<DOCNO> AP890620-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1916EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Procurement     06-20 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Procurement,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government to Pay for Development Stage of Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, in a policy shift from
the Reagan era, has decided that the government will pay the full
cost of readying new weapons for production, Pentagon officials said
Tuesday.
   For the past eight years, government and defense contractors have
split the development cost of most weapons systems. That policy will
change, the new No. 2 Pentagon official, Deputy Defense Secretary
Donald J. Atwood, revealed in a published interview.
   Atwood's proposal was embodied in a Pentagon management review
that Defense Secretary Dick Cheney approved and sent to the White
House on Tuesday, acording to other Pentagon officials. The policy
change does not require congressional review.
   ``We're just going to implement it,'' said Atwood.
   The old system does not encourage defense contractors to develop
the most efficient weapons and means of producing them, Atwood said.
``It encourages them to skimp,'' he said in an interview with The
Washington Post.
   Pentagon officials distributed the text on Tuesday.
   ``The consequence is, lo and behold, we end up in production with
something that's difficult to build. We didn't put the time and
effort into it,'' said Atwood, a former executive at General Motors
Corp.
   He did not offer any specific examples, but the Pentagon has had
trouble in recent years in the performance of several costly weapons.
   The development contract, said Atwood, ``is when you should put
your effort into designing it for simplicity and producibility, of
designing it for reliability and performance and quality. And it is
not the time you skimp. That is the whole purpose.''
   The shift, which is likely to be hailed by the defense industry,
will not affect existing contracts on major weapons systems, such as
the B-2 ``stealth'' bomber or a new class of attack submarines.
   But Pentagon officials said in a statement that future contracts
for full-scale development of the Air Force's new Advanced
Technology Fighter ``may reflect the change in contract policy.''
   In outlining the new policy, Atwood distinguished between
research that contractors pursue on various weapons-related
technologies and the money they spend developing actual weapons for
the government.
   ``I think the government should pay the bill for the development
phase,'' he said. ``By the development, I mean the early-on
demonstration, validation phase, and for the full-scale
development.''
   ``Now, I don't want to hold out any bonanza to any industry that
thinks, `Well, we'll get all the money we want. Quite the
contrary,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
