<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Appointments     06-20 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Appointments,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Makes Appointments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush announced Tuesday he will retain
Frank G. Wisner as ambassador to Egypt and will name Susan M.
Coughlin to the National Transportation Safety Board.
   In addition, the White House said two top Pentagon officials will
retain their posts, and Bush will name Wade F. Horn as chief of the
children's bureau in the Health and Human Services Department and S.
Anthony McCann to a new post in Veteran's Affairs.
   In the Pentagon appointments, Bush announced his intention to
retain Robert W. Page Sr. as assistant secretary of Army in charge
of civil works, and Stephen M. Duncan as assistant secretary of
Defense in charge of reserve affairs.
   In other appointments, Bush announced he will name McCann as
assistant Veteran's Affairs secretary for finance and planning.
McCann since 1986 has been assistant secretary of management and
budget at HHS.
   Wisner has been ambassador to Egypt since 1986, and was
previously senior deputy assistant secretary of state for African
affairs and ambassador to Zambia. He served in a variety of State
Department posts prior to his posting in Zambia in 1979.
   Ms. Coughlin has been deputy administrator of the Federal
Railroad Administation at the Transportation Department since 1987,
and previously was acting vice president and deputy vice president
of the Export-Import Bank. Earlier, she was an officer for
intergovernmental relations at the Transportation Department from
1981 to 1983.
   Horn since 1986 has been director of outpatient psychological
services at Children's Hospital Medical Center in Washington, and
previously was a professor and administrator at George Washington
University School of Medicine and Michigan State University.
   Bush also said he will retain Henry E. Hockeimer as associate
director of the U.S. Information Agency. Hockeimer has served in
that job since 1988 and before that was assistant director of the
U.S. Information Agency.
</TEXT>
