<FIRST>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     06-20 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Afghanistan,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Envoy to Afghan Rebels Pledges Continued U.S. Support</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new U.S. envoy to Afghan rebels said
Tuesday he plans to meet with their leaders to stress continued U.S.
support as they ``conclude successfully the final phase of their
struggle'' against the Kabul regime.
   Peter Thomsen, a career diplomat, commented after taking the oath
of office for the newly created position.
   He acknowledged it was unusual for a U.S. diplomat to be
accredited to a rebel movement, and said creation of the post was an
``unusually strong way'' to convey continuing support for the rebels.
   Thomsen said he plans to leave shortly for the rebel headquarters
in Pakistan to meet with the leaders and to establish a dialogue
with the interim government the insurgents have set up.
   ``In these and many other future meetings with the resistance, my
objective will be to deepen further our relations with them and to
ensure continued American support for their cause as they conclude
successfully the final phase of their struggle,'' he said.
   Thomsen, who has concentrated on Asian affairs during most of his
career, said U.S. objectives in Afghanistan remain unchanged,
providing for ``a political settlement that will include genuine
self-determination for the Afghan people, the return of the refugees
in safety and dignity, and the restoration of Afghanistan's
sovereignty and independence.''
   He said the Marxist government in Kabul ``has been thoroughly
discredited'' by its role over the past decade.
