<FIRST>r w AM-PlutoniumPlant 1stLd-Writethru a0644 06-20 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plutonium Plant, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0644,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Watkins Decided to Delay Plutonium Project</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS lead to show Energy Department confirmation; SUBS 4th
graf pvs, Department spokesmen ..., with 2 grafs to update with Energy
Department comment; picks up 5th graf pvs, Spratt said ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department confirmed Tuesday it will
make a closer study of environmental risks posed by a prototype
plutonium refinery, a move that a House panel chairman says will
delay start of plant construction at least two years.
   The department has called the plant a key to modernization of the
nation's nuclear weapons production complex. It would use a new
laser technology to convert existing military stockpiles of
fuel-grade plutonium to weapon-grade material.
   Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C., chairman of a special Armed Services
Committee panel, said Energy Secretary James D. Watkins had made the
decision in response to an environmental group's threat last April
to sue to force such a study.
   Will Callicott, a department spokesman, said Watkins had notified
selected members of Congress of his decison on Monday and Tuesday,
although no general announcement was made.
   The move was made, Callicott said, because of ``our own wish to
put any public doubt to rest ... as to the environmental safeguards
for the project.'' He declined to say how long the environmental
study would delay the refinery project.
   Spratt said Watkins had committed the department to conducting a
formal Environmental Impact Statement on the prototype, which is
being built at the department's Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory near San Francisco.
   The Livermore project is a prototype for a permanent plutonium
refinery, called the Special Isotope Separation plant, that the
department wants to build at the Idaho National Engineering
Laboratory, near Idaho Falls.
   An environmental study of the Idaho site already has been
completed.
   Spratt's panel, which is reviewing Energy Department plans for
modernizing the nuclear weapons complex and cleaning up its
hazardous wastes, last week voted to recommend withholding funds for
beginning construction at Idaho Falls in 1990.
   In a statement announcing Watkins' decision, Spratt said he was
pleased by the move.
   ``It signifies to the people of Livermore and vicinity that their
concerns for health and safety are shared by the Department of
Energy, and more broadly, it is a tangible sign of what Secretary
Watkins calls a `change of culture' at DOE,'' he said.
   The Natural Resources Defense Council, which notified the
department last April that it would sue if an environmental
assessment were not performed, said it was pleased by the decision.
   ``We scored a victory,'' said Dan Reicher of the council. ``It's
a combination of the strong position we believe we have, plus
congressional pressure.''
   Spratt said it would take at least 12 months to finish the
environmental study, and that the start of construction at Idaho
Falls is likely to be delayed at least two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
