<DOCNO> AP890620-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1924EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-StarWars     06-20 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Star Wars,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Star Wars Research Less Costly Than Bush Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States can conduct Star Wars
research and development far more cheaply than the Bush
administration is proposing, acording to a congressional report
released Tuesday.
   The three types of budget options described in the Congressional
Budget Office report would cost $11.3 billion to $18.4 billion from
1990 to 1994, rather than the $31.1 billion proposed by President
Bush for the same period.
   ``If we spend billions on strategic defense that does not really
defend us _ and siphon these billions from the budgets of fighter
planes, ships, tanks and personnel _ we may not make the country
more secure,'' said Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C., a member of the House
Armed Services Committee who requested the report. ``For this
reason, the CBO report bears careful study.''
   Bush cut spending on the Strategic Defense Initiative to $4.6
billion for fiscal 1990, down from the $5.9 billion proposed by
former President Reagan.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has also said Bush will shift the
focus of Star Wars from deployment sometime in the 1990s to research
on a more advanced system known as ``Brilliant Pebbles,'' consisting
of thousands of orbiting satellites.
   Under the report's first option, the United States would be
protected against a Soviet breakthrough in technology or the
Kremlin's deployment of a strategic defense system.
   Total spending would range from $11.3 billion to $14.5 billion
and the option would be in compliance with the Anti-ballistic
Missile Treaty, the report said.
   The second option, estimated at a cost of about $17 billion,
would enable the United States to defend parts of the country
against a limited nuclear attack caused by an accident. That option
may comply with the ABM Treaty, the report said.
   The third option, costing about $18.4 billion, would provide a
larger strategic defense system that would protect land-based
missiles housed in silos such as the MX and Midgetman.
   The report estimates did not include the cost of procuring the
system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
