<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1932EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PollutedCounty     06-20 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polluted County,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pollution News Shocking But Not Surprising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOOELE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this arid county in western
Utah, home to military installations, industrial plants and waste
disposal facilities, are no strangers to pollution hazards.
   And now, state officials have been told that AMAX Magnesium
Corp., which extracts metal from evaporation ponds on the western
shore of the Great Salt Lake, is the nation's single greatest source
of toxic air pollutants, specifically chlorine, according to the
Natural Resources Defense Council.
   ``Certainly we're not proud of the designation,'' AMAX spokesman
Lee Brown said Tuesday. ``But the fact is, we've been cognizant of
the emissions and have done environmental studies that show
absolutely no discernable effects.''
   Brown said the plant, about 65 miles from Salt Lake City and 40
miles from the nearest community, employs about 600 workers who
extract magnesium chloride salt from the briny water and process
magnesium and liquid chloride for a variety of industrial uses.
   Even now, the company is installing devices to reduce the
emission of chlorine gas from the stacks by 50 percent at year's end
and a total of 75 percent by 1991, state environmental health
officials say.
   What concerns some officials more than AMAX's emissions is that
Tooele County, with its immense deserts and desolate mountains, has
become a favorite destination for low-level hazardous wastes from
producers in and out of the state.
   Radioactive tailings from an old uranium mill in Salt Lake County
are buried there. Hazardous waste disposal sites are in operation or
on the drawing boards, one waste incinerator is under construction
and another has been proposed.
   At Dugway Proving Ground, the Army has conducted germ warfare
defense testing for decades, and Tooele Army Depot stores much of
the nation's arsenal of obsolete chemical weapons. The Air Force
uses hundreds of square miles of the county for bombing runs and jet
fighter training.
   ``People drive out there, and they think of all this wasted
land,'' said state Rep. Beverly White, a 10-term Democrat. ``But we
have mountains, streams and deserts. It isn't just nothing. I've
been saying for years that I hope we don't turn into the dumping
ground of the world.''
   Alan Miller of the Utah Environmental Center in Salt Lake City
shares her concerns.
   He praised the strict criteria county officials have established
for siting, mitigation and emergency response capabilities when
approving new hazardous waste and other developments with a
potential for pollution.
   ``But along with expertise in knowing how to handle, manage and
work with a hazardous management zone, comes a feeling of growing
confidence,'' he said. ``Just like with TAD, there's an attitude of,
`We can live with these things.' Is Tooele going to be the
hazardous-waste frontier?''
   However, Tooele County Commissioner Bill Pitt says the potential
perils of hazardous waste and pollution or accidents at Dugway or
Tooele Army Depot must be weighed with the economic benefits to its
30,000 residents.
   Besides, he said, all are strictly regulated by a variety of
local, state and federal agencies.
   ``I'm not trying to downplay the health factors,'' he said. ``But
we are trying to balance the two _ health factors and economics.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
