<FIRST>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0658 06-20 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settler Shoots at Palestinians; Wounds Two</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Rabin, intelligence
chief. Pickup 3rd pvs, `Police said...' Subs 10th pvs, `The shooting...'
to UPDATE with report gunman came from funeral. Subs 19th pvs, `Two stone-throwing...'
to UPDATE with three attacks. ^By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARIEL, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish settler pumped
submachine gunfire into a crowd of Palestinians waiting for a ride
near Tel Aviv on Tuesday, wounding two people, police said.
   The shooting occurred shortly after angry settlers booed and
shouted down Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, chanting ``Traitor!
Traitor!'' as the Israeli leader tried to eulogize a U.S.-born
settler slain Saturday in the occupied West Bank.
   ``Revenge! Revenge!'' some screamed.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said some ``extremist reactions''
aim at jeopardizing government plans for elections in the occupied
territories.
   ``I think some right-wing extremists in Israel are horrified by
the peace plan,'' Rabin said on Israel Television. ``They still
believe we can restore the status quo through the use of military
force only.''
   Israel's military intelligence chief, Maj. Gen. Amnon Shahak,
said the Palestine Liberation Organization may accept the election
proposal because its ranks are split and there is more open
criticism of chairman Yasser Arafat. He also said international
support for the uprising has declined.
   Police said they arrested three Palestinians in the stabbing
death of settler Frederick Steven Rosenfeld, 48. Israel radio
reported the army blew up the suspects' homes Tuesday.
   After Rosenfeld's funeral, a 23-year-old settler approached
Palestinians at a highway intersection and opened fire with an Uzi
submachine gun, said police spokeswoman Dalia Gilad.
   He wounded two Palestinians, one seriously, she said.
   The gunman fled on foot, but was captured by police, Ms. Gilad
said, refusing to name the settler.
   One witness told Israel army radio the man wore a checkered Arab
headdress when he approached the intersection and fired, then pulled
off the headdress and shouted ``I'm a Jew!'' before running away.
   Israel radio quoted police officials as saying the gunman wore a
Jewish skullcap.
   Tel Aviv police refused to comment, saying there was ``a news
blackout.''
   Itim national news agency said the attacker was returning from
Rosenfeld's funeral, which took place 18 miles east of the shooting
site where Palestinians from the occupied territories wait for
transport home.
   The funeral began with a procession from Ariel settlement, where
Rosenfeld lived. It drew 500 settlers, most armed.
   Shamir told the crowd, ``The people of Israel are standing with
you today.''
   But most of his eulogy was drowned by shouts of ``Liar!'' and
``Shamir go home!''
   Settlers are demanding harsher measures to quell the 18-month
Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip and
blame Shamir for Arab attacks on settlers.
   At least 526 Palestinians and 23 Israelis have been killed since
the revolt against Israeli occupation began in December 1987.
   Shamir's hard-line rival in the right-wing Likud bloc, Industry
Minister Ariel Sharon, was not interrupted when he recited the
Kaddish, or prayer for the dead, for Rosenfeld.
   Sharon opposes Shamir's initiative to hold elections in the
occupied lands. Fistfights erupted after the funeral, when furious
settlers attacked a left-wing activist who attended the service.
Soldiers who pulled the activist to safety also were struck.
   Three stone-throwing attacks on Arabs were reported, Israel radio
and Arab reports said. Two Arabs were slightly injured and a third
was in moderate condition in the hospital with injuries from rocks
and flying glass.
   Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, the West Bank army commander, told Israel
radio the Palestinian suspects encountered Rosenfeld hiking alone
near Arab villages outside Ariel.
   He said the Palestinians told interrogators that Rosenfeld
chatted with them, took their pictures with his camera and asked
them to photograph him. One of the Palestinians then grabbed
Rosenfeld's knife and stabbed him in the back, Mitzna said. There
was no motive, he said.
   The army identified those arrested as Fahim Ramadan Sirhan
Ibrahim, 21, Bilan Ibrahim Mustafa Samrah, 22, and Mustafa Otman
Amar Elhaj, 21, all from Burkin village near Ariel.
</TEXT>
