<DOCNO> AP890620-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1935EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TaxPenalties     06-20 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Penalties,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Tax Penalty Revisions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee approved
legislation Tuesday revising and simplifying most of the nearly 150
federal tax penalties.
   The measure generally would require the Internal Revenue Service
to be less harsh on a taxpayer who tries to comply with the law but
fails than on one who makes no effort to comply.
   It also aims to reduce chances that a taxpayer will be hit with
two or more civil penalties for the same shortcoming.
   The committee, meeting behind closed doors, added the provision
to a package that eventually is expected to include spending cuts
and revenue increases required to reduce the budget deficit.
   Rep. J.J. Pickle, D-Texas, said that his oversight subcommittee
heard testimony that ``the current penalty structure is a confusing
morass of complex, overlapping penalties that are often unduly harsh
or just plain irrational.''
   The IRS, 35 years ago, had only 13 penalties to enforce. The
increase, authorities say, is due in part to Congress' use of
penalties to raise revenue. The rewriting is based on the notion
that penalties should be used only to encourage compliance, not to
raise money.
   In 1988, the IRS assessed 26 million penalties totaling nearly $6
billion. The IRS supports overhauling the penalty structure.
   Present law imposes a 5 percent penalty for underpayment of tax;
the bill would raise that generally to 20 percent.
   Most of the changes involve penalties on banks and others that
fail to file reports on interest and dividends, and on employers who
miss the deadline for turning over withheld taxes to the IRS.
   In most cases, the revised penalties would be graduated so that
the longer the delay in paying or filing, the higher the penalty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
