<FIRST>r i AM-Libya-Terrorists     06-20 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-Terrorists,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Says Terrorists Met in Libya to Plan Attack at Frankfurt Airport</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian terrorists met with
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi to plan an attack at the Frankfurt
Airport, but an Israeli agent warned West German authorities, Stern
magazine said Tuesday.
   The Hamburg-based magazine said an agent from Mossad, the Israeli
intelligence service, infiltrated the meeting, and his information
prompted last week's security alert at the airport.
   The security measures are still in force at the airport, West
Germany's busiest.
   Police are conducting a nationwide search for suspects, Stern
said.
   It reported the terrorists were planning the attack in an attempt
to gain the release of convicted TWA hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi
and two imprisoned members of the Syrian-backed Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command.
   Stern said the terrorists met with Col. Gadhafi June 10 in
Tripoli, the Libyan capital.
   It made no further mention of Gadhafi. The story will be carried
in Stern's Thursday edition, but the magazine sent a summary of the
article to other news media Tuesday.
   Stern said the Israeli agent quoted terrorists at the meeting as
saying: ``The time is right to free the fighters from prison.
   ``It is time to carry out the great attack. The means are in our
hands. We possess a weapon that will drown many in West Germany in
blood and tears.''
   West German security sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed that the warning of a possible attack came from Mossad.
   Christian Jaletzke, a spokesman for the Hesse state Interior
Ministry that is responsible for security at the Frankfurt Airport,
said he could neither confirm nor deny that Mossad provided the tip.
   But he said the information that had been received was considered
reliable. ``The information ... was of such quality that we had to
step up security,'' he said.
   When security was strengthened last week authorities said the
measures were linked to Hamadi's case.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, was convicted by a Frankfurt
court last month of murder and air piracy in the 1985 TWA hijacking
and was sentenced to life imprisonment. A U.S. Navy diver was killed
by the hijackers.
   Stern said that in addition to freeing Hamadi the terrorists
wanted to gain the release of two Popular Front members jailed in
West Germany after a raid in October on suspected terrorist cells in
the Frankfurt and Duesseldorf areas.
   One of the men, Hafez Kassem Dalkamoni, is believed to be a
ranking Popular Front official.
   Police found in his car a bomb concealed in a radio cassette
player that was similar to the device that blew up Pan Am Flight 103
over Scotland in December, killing 270 people.
   Stern said a search of Dalkamoni's apartment in Frankfurt turned
up evidence of an underground arms cache, but it was empty.
   It added that police using dogs are searching for explosives in
wooded areas around the airport.
   The Reagan administration accused Gadhafi's regime of supporting
international terrorism, and on April 14, 1986, U.S. warplanes
bombed the Libyan cities of Tripoli and Benghazi. Gadhafi repeatedly
has denied he supports terrorist actions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
