<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-RuralDevelopment     06-20 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rural Development,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>House, Senate Panels Differ on Pace of Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House member whose subcommittee is crafting
rural development legislation says he wants to move slowly but
surely, despite the desire in the Senate to push such a measure
through quickly.
   ``We're taking a different approach,'' said Rep. Glenn English,
D-Okla., whose subcommittee is holding a lengthy series of hearings
before crafting legislation early this fall.
   ``We're reaching outside Washington,'' said English. ``We will
have heard from over 40 witnesses by the time we finish hearings
this month.''
   He also has scheduled hearings in five regions of the country in
August.
   English said the House Agriculture subcommittee on conservation,
credit and rural development is moving as quickly as it can, but he
doesn't understand the ``push it through approach'' being taken by
the Senate.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt. and chairman of the Senate Agriculture
Committee, was joined by several other Democratic senators, the
National Association of Development Organizations and the National
Association of Counties at a news conference Tuesday promoting his
bill.
   ``One of the reasons we worked so hard to get this out is so that
it won't be perceived as a farm bill,'' said Leahy. ``Ninety percent
of rural America is not involved in farming.''
   English said that timing will determine whether the legislation
is incorporated into the 1990 omnibus bill that sets farm policy for
several years.
   ``There are some good points about that legislation (Leahy's
bill), and I think it is fine as far as it goes,'' English said. ``I
don't think legislation drawn up by any one house is going to be the
best approach to all the problems in rural America.''
   English said the House might pass a rural development bill by
this December, but his timetable is geared for passage of a law
before the session's end in December 1990.
   He said he expects a conference committee comprising members of
both the House and Senate to bring the measures together.
   Legislation to aid rural communities is considered necessary
because steady loss of job opportunities, deteriorating roads,
bridges and other infrastructure, and declining education are
driving people away.
   But such legislation is more difficult to pass in the House than
in the Senate, because urban districts hold the majority in the
House.
   English has warned that unless something is done to reverse the
trend, cities will be greatly overburdened.
   Leahy calls his bill ``landmark legislation'' that he has waited
15 years to see passed.
   ``This bill has three basic purposes,'' he said.
   It will provide capital for new businesses in the form of
revolving loans, set up satellite educational and health
communication systems and provide funds for improving drinking water.
   Leahy claimed he has strong support in the Senate now that the
interests of those seeking drought legislation have been met.
   A snag developed last week when Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., threatened
to block the bill if the agriculture committee didn't pass his
relief legislation for winter wheat farmers whose crops were
destroyed by drought.
   Leahy has scheduled hearings on the drought measure next month
with both it and his rural development bill to receive floor action
the same day, soon after the July 4 break.
   Economic development officials from the rural South complained,
however, that Leahy's bill will help rural areas with the worst
economic problems.
   The officials questioned whether the most economically depressed
rural areas will be able to use the centerpiece of the legislation _
$300 million to start or expand revolving loan funds _ because of
its requirement that the federal aid be matched by local sources.
   Most poor areas can't afford those matching funds, they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
