<FIRST>r w AM-SuperCollider     06-20 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super Collider,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appropriations Committee Votes $200 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Appropriations Committee on Tuesday
approved $200 million to begin construction next year of the
supercollider atom-smasher, a gigantic machine for probing the
secrets of matter.
   Under the supercollider provisions of an appropriations bill for
the Energy Department and the Army Corps of Engineers, $110 million
could be used to initiate construction of the $4.4 billion,
53-miles-around accelerator at a site south of Dallas, with the
balance for research and development on what would be the largest
scientific instrument ever built.
   The Bush administration had sought $250 million.
   The collider project faces significant opposition, not least from
members who believe it will starve other worthy projects of funds.
The bill is expected to come to the House floor next week.
   One backer of the project, Rep. Jim Chapman, D-Texas, said,
``People who oppose the super collider do so with some jeopardy,''
because of the scores of energy and water projects in the spending
package that affect many members' districts.
   The Committee approved the super collider appropriation without
dissent.
</TEXT>
