<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Poll     06-20 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Poll,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Says Public Happy with Bush, Not with Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is even more popular than his
predecessor, but Congress is increasingly unpopular, according to an
ABC-Washington Post poll released Tuesday.
   Bush's approval rating after nearly six months in office is 73
percent positive, according to the random telephone survey.
   That ties with President Reagan's all-time high of 73 percent
positive recorded just after he was wounded in an assassination
attempt in 1981.
   Bush has averaged a 72 percent positive rating since he took
office in January, compared with Reagan's 66 percent approval rating
during roughly the same period of his presidency, according to
ABC-Washington Post polls.
   A total of 54 percent of those polled said Bush had been as tough
as needed in response to the political upheaval in China, while 38
percent said his response had been too weak.
   The poll found that those interviewed were disenchanted with
Congress in the wake of the resignation of House Speaker Jim Wright
over allegations of ethics violations.
   Congress' approval rating fell from 54 percent in May to 37
percent in June, the poll found. That is the lowest rating recorded
for Congress in any ABC-Washington Post poll since the question
began being asked in 1985, the news agencies said in a release.
   Pollsters interviewed 1,546 people 18 and older from June 15-19.
The margin of error is plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</TEXT>
