<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 2003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NYCSchools     06-20 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYC Schools,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigator Says He Cast 33 Votes in Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An undercover agent for a state commission
pretended to be 33 men and cast 33 ballots at 33 voting sites in the
citywide local school board elections on May 2, the agent testified
Tuesday.
   Leslie Smith, an undercover operative for the Commission on
Integrity of the Public Schools, detailed for the commission Tuesday
how easy it was to register under dozens of fake names and hop from
polling place to polling place.
   Commission chairman James F. Gill emphasized that there was no
evidence that fraud, outside of Smith's, had occurred in the
election.
   He also stressed that Smith filled out each of his ballots
improperly, so that all his votes were invalidated and did not
affect any outcome.
   ``We were getting a lot of information from a lot of sources
indicating that these elections were open to fraud,'' Gill said.
``We decided to find out if there was that kind of systemic weakness
and I think we've demonstrated there is.''
   ``In the old days if you wanted to engage in this kind of voter
fraud, you had to go to the cemetery and take the names of the most
recently deceased off of the gravestones and try to vote those
folks. In this situation, all that had to be done was sit down and
draw up a list of fictitious parents and children,'' Gill said.
   Voting for school boards is open to all registered voters and to
all parents of children in the schools, regardless of whether they
are registered voters.
   Smith and a commission lawyer made up 84 men's names and gave
each a fictitious child. A parent registration card was filled out
and mailed to the Board of Election for each fake name.
Seventy-three of the 84 names made the voter list of the Board of
Election; 11 registration cards evidently were lost, Smith said.
   On Election Day he went to all 35 polling sites within the two
districts, but voted only 33 times because his registration cards
could not be found at two schools.
   Under state law, the Board of Education is supposed to weed the
rolls of ineligible parents and certify legitimate voters to the
Board of Election. But Aaron Maslow, the Board of Elections counsel,
said the Board of Education did little more than give blanket
certification.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
