<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Sakharov     06-20 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Sakharov,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov Says Gorbachev Could Be Ousted in a Coup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei Sakharov said Tuesday the Soviet Union is at
a turning point, and if the worst happened President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev could be the victim of a military coup by conservative
elements.
   The Soviet human rights activist, in a lecture at the Royal
Institute of International Affairs, said: ``The country is at the
crossroads and faces major reforms. From this position the country
can go either way. If it goes too far there could be a fascist
military coup, especially from the right, which is the conservative
element.''
   He told the audience, which included representatives of the
Soviet Embassy, that the West should be cautious about overtures to
the Soviet Union.
   Western aid could be like pouring water into the sand and might
prevent necessary reforms, he said.
   ``The important thing is not to undertake new initiatives,''
Sakharov added. ``Wait for real change in the political system.''
   He noted Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher is considered a
supporter of the reform-minded Soviet president.
   ``The caution she is observing now (toward Gobachev) is
justified,'' he said. ``It does not contradict her earlier policy.
It is a revision of that policy taking account of existing
circumstances.''
   Commenting on the Soviet Union, he said: ``I suppose our country
is now one of the last, if not the last, world colonial power. If
this problem is not going to be solved in a constitutional, rational
way the destruction or downfall of our country is inevitable.''
   Sakharov, accompanied by his wife Yelena Bonner, is on his first
trip to Britain. The 1975 Nobel Peace Prize winner received an
honorary degree at Sussex University on Monday and is to receive
another honorary degree from Oxford University on Wednesday. He will
meet Mrs. Thatcher on Friday.
   The 68-year-old physicist was elected to the newly formed
Congress of the People's Deputies by the Soviet Academy of Sciences
in April, three years after he was freed from internal exile in the
city of Gorky. He had been sent there as punishment for his
dissident activites, including criticism of the Soviet military
intervention in Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
