<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     06-20 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Official Says Namibian Police Threaten Fair Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African-led police in Namibia have
created an atmosphere of fear and intimidation that threatens fair
independence elections in the territory, a top U.N. official said
Tuesday.
   Police in armored cars mounted with heavy machine guns apparently
have driven through villages destroying crops and terrorizing local
inhabitants, according to Martti Ahtisaari, the U.N.'s special
representative in Namibia.
   A feared counter-insurgency unit called ``Koevoet,'' Afrikaans
for crowbar, disbanded months ago is behind the terror campaign,
Ahtissari said.
   ``Their activities appear to have created an atmosphere of fear
and intimidation among much of the population in the northern
region,'' Ahtisaari reportedly wrote to Namibia's South African
administrator-general.
   On July 1, campaigning begins for seats in a Namibian constituent
assembly that will draft a constitution and organize the territory's
first black majority-ruled government.
   The South-West Africa People's Organization is expected to win
the November elections, part of a U.N.-mediated peace plan. Most of
SWAPO's popular support comes from the Ovambo tribe in northern
Namibia.
   SWAPO, which fought a 23-year bush war against South African rule
of Namibia, may not capture the two-thirds of the assembly seats
needed to impose one-party rule.
   Many observers believe South Africa is funding political parties
and using the Koevoet police to intimidate SWAPO supporters and stop
the guerrillas from gaining their majority.
   Ahtisaari heads a U.N. commission monitoring Pretoria's
cooperation with a U.N. plan to free Namibia from 74 years of South
African rule.
   He wrote to the South African official, Louis Pienaar, on June 9,
Nadia Younes, a U.N. spokeswoman, said Tuesday. He has received no
reply, she said.
   ``The activities in which (the Koevoet) have been engaged render
its members ... unfit for continued service in the police ... in
view of the need to ensure the necessary conditions for free and
fair elections,'' Ahtissari reportedly wrote.
</TEXT>
