<FIRST>r w AM-AccusedNazi     06-20 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Accused Nazi,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deportation Proceedings to Begin Against N.J. Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department moved Tuesday to begin
deportation proceedings against an elderly New Jersey man accused of
being a Nazi propagandist during World War II.
   The Justice Department charged Ferenc Koreh, 79, of Englewood,
N.J., of advocating the persecution of Jews and the defeat of the
Allies during World War II when he edited a newspaper in Hungary,
which was an ally of Nazi Germany.
   Besides editing the newspaper Szkelely Nep from 1941 through
1944, the department said Koreh was a press officer for the
Hungarian Minister of Propaganda and later edited a government-run
publication.
   Reached at his home by telephone, Koreh would say only, ``I will
certainly fight it.''
   In 1947, the People's Court of Budapest convicted Koreh of war
crimes in connection with his editorship of the government
publication, which supported the German war effort, according to the
government's lawsuit.
   The department's Office of Special Investigations charged in the
lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court in Newark that Koreh concealed
his wartime activities and his war-crimes conviction from U.S.
immigration officials.
   Koreh was admitted to the United States as a displaced person in
1950 and began as a naturalized citizen in 1956.
   The complaint noted that when he edited the newspaper, Koreh
wrote and published anti-Semitic propaganda, including pieces
entitled ``Disloyal, Unscrupulous, Cheating Jews in the Pages of
Hungarian History.''
   The newspaper also advocated the defeat of the United States
during the war, the department charged.
   OSI Director Neal M. Sher said 30 individuals have been
denaturalized and 27 have been deported. He said 600 people are
under investigation by the deparment's Nazi-hunting unit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
