<FIRST>u w AM-ChildCare 2ndLd-Writethru a0722 06-20 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Care, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0722,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hatch Admonishes GOP Colleagues on Child Care Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Ledes with 11 grafs to add Hatch attack on conservative groups,
Mitchell intent to delay recess if necessary; debate ended for the day.
Picks up graf 10 1st Ld: ``Hatch did,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Republican senator accused fellow GOP
lawmakers and conservatives Tuesday of ``downright deliberate
deceit'' in attacks on a major child care package and said the
Republican alternative paled in comparison.
   ``It's really irritating to see the misinformation and downright
false information that has been spread around this body,'' said Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
   ``I get a little tired of seeing partisanship and seeing people
playing with this issue,'' said Hatch, the ranking Republican on the
Senate Labor Committee. Hatch crossed party lines to co-sponsor the
bill, which is backed mostly by Democrats.
   Hatch twice took the floor to denounce the tactics of Republicans
and conservative groups, singling out the Eagle Forum for
distributing ``shameful'' information he said misrepresented the
child care package he supports.
   Hatch's criticism of fellow conservatives highlighted a day that
was to be spent debating an alternative child care package to be
offered by Senate Republican leader Bob Dole.
   Dole had promised to present the alternative Tuesday but did not
do so. GOP aides said the Republican leadership was lobbying
Southern Democratic senators in hopes of gaining enough support for
its proposal to present it on Wednesday.
   Democratic leaders predicted the GOP effort would fail.
   The majority leader, George Mitchell, D-Maine, warned senators he
would delay a Senate recess scheduled to begin next week if a final
vote on child care is delayed past Friday. ``We're going to stay
here as long as it takes,'' Mitchell said.
   The only amendment considered before debate ended for the day was
approved unanimously on a voice vote. It rolled back from 16 to 13
the maximum age for a child to be eligible for grant money under the
program.
   Floor debate resumed after both parties held caucuses. During the
Republican meeting, Hatch said GOP senators were given a memo
attacking the Act for Better Child Care sponsored by him and Sen.
Christopher Dodd., D-Conn.
   Hatch said the memo was full of ``downright deliberate deceit, as
though that's the way it should be.'' Later, Hatch said the memo was
not on the letterhead of any senator or group. ``I do not know who
prepared this piece of junk,'' he said.
   Hatch did not refer to any of his GOP colleagues by name, but
many Republicans, including Dole, have sharply criticized the ABC
bill. Hatch, Dodd and other Democrats have said many of the
criticisms are not valid because the current bill has been revised
substantially from Dodd's original proposal.
   ``I regret that I have to spend time answering charges that don't
relate to this legislation,'' Dodd said. ``We've spent the last two
days arguing about myths.''
   As revised, the ABC bill would authorize $1.75 billion for child
care programs in fiscal 1990, with 70 percent of the money going to
low-income parents to help them pay for child care. The remaining
funds would go to the states for programs to improve the quality and
quantity of available child care.
   The amended bill leaves regulatory decisions to the states; the
original included federal regulations that faced staunch GOP
opposition.
   Tacked on to the Dodd-Hatch bill were two proposals approved by
the Senate Finance Committee, a new, up-to-$500, tax credit to help
families pay for health insurance for children and a provision
making refundable the existing dependent care tax credit.
   The Republican alternative Dole planned to offer _ with the
blessing of the White House _ would rely almost entirely on tax
credits to help parents pay for child care. It too would make the
dependent-care credit refundable and create a new child care tax
credit for low-income families with children up to 4 years old. The
Dole proposal also would create a $400 million block grant program
to help states expand child care opportunities.
</TEXT>
