<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe 1stLd-Writethru   06-20 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0686,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manafort Concedes He Peddled Influence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf: ``About a,'' to give exact amount of rehabilitation
grant.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Republican political consultant
acknowledged Tuesday he used ``influence peddling'' to steer
millions of dollars in government renovation funds to a housing
project that he owned in part.
   Paul Manafort, a one-time adviser to the campaigns of Presidents
Bush and Reagan and a former business partner of GOP National
Committee Chairman Lee Atwater, also told a House subcommittee that
the $326,000 fee his lobbying firm charged for helping to obtain the
government money was the going rate for such services.
   The housing project in southern New Jersey, approved by the
Department of Housing and Urban Development late in the Reagan
administration, was denounced as wasteful by Democratic and
Republican members of Congress and by local officials from the
7,000-person township where it is located, Upper Deerfiel.
   Manafort said his firm was to provide public relations and
lobbying services for the project. When pressed on what those
services entailed, he conceded, ``I would stipulate that for the
purposes of today, you could characterize this as influence
peddling.''
   ``I think it is a horrible waste of taxpayers' money,'' said
Bruce T. Peterson, the mayor, after learning that with tax credits,
rent subsidies and repair grants the project was costing the federal
government about $43 million.
   Peterson said local officials were told nothing about the project
until well after the developers and their paid consultants started
going after the federal money.
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., later said he believed that the
project was not worthy of federal funds in the first place.
   The housing project is a complex of 326 apartments built in the
1940s that had become dilapidated over the years.
   In April 1987, CFM Development Corp., of which Manafort is one of
three principal owners, bought the project for $4.4 million _ at
least $1 million more than township officials said the land and
buildings were worth.
   About a month later the state housing authority ran an
advertisement announcing the availability of government funds to fix
up such projects. About two weeks later, Manafort's group, the only
one to apply, was awarded $5.5 million to fix up the buildings.
   In his testimony Tuesday before the housing and employment
subcommittee of the Government Operations Committee, Manafort
repeatedly said the development company was taking risks because
there was no guarantee that it would get the money from the
Department of Housing and Urban Development. As proof, he cited an
advertisement, which ran just once and in just one newspaper,
soliciting applications from developers.
   ``Nobody in this world believes that you had any doubt'' the
money would come through, said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass.
   Holding up a copy of the advertisement, Rep. Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y., said, ``You could have cut out all this language and written
one sentence: The fix is in.''
   Subcommittee Chairman Tom Lantos, D-Calif., just read the
advertisement out loud: It invited developers to apply for HUD funds
but said the money was only for projects with more than 100
apartments and ``must be located in the city of Seabrook.''
   There is no such city in New Jersey. Seabrook is the name of the
housing project.
   ``This was about as phony an advertisement as you have ever
seen,'' Lantos said. ``This was a sham and an illusion that it was
publicly advertised.''
   Manafort testified that before the developers bought the property
his lobbying firm, Black, Manafort, Stone &amp; Kelly, had already spent
months contacting state and federal officials, including Deborah
Gore Dean, an assistant to then-Housing and Urban Development
Secretary Samuel Pierce.
   Ms. Dean is a key figure in investigations of allegations that
HUD money to rehabilitate run-down housing for the poor and elderly
was handed out to developers who hired high-priced political
consultants with ties to the Republican Party or the Reagan
administration.
   Earlier this month Ms. Dean appeared before the same subcommittee
but refused to answer any questions on the grounds that to do so
would violate her constitutional rights against self-incrimination.
   Manafort is not the only Republican who is said to have benefited
by access to HUD during the eight years of the Reagan presidency.
Former Interior Secretary James Watt, former Sen. Edward Brooke of
Massachusetts and the late John Mitchell, attorney general during
the Nixon administration, all made thousands of dollars by helping
others get money from the department.
   On Tuesday, The New York Times reported that Robert Weinberger, a
nephew of Reagan's defense secretary, was a consultant who helped a
St. Paul, Minn. housing project get funds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
