<HEAD>More Arrested; Chinese Add New Requirement to Obtain Visas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. sanctions and ADD
details on condemned. Pickup 14th pvs, ``Sentences of...' ^By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested more students involved in the
pro-democracy movement, the government said Tuesday, and it
stiffened visa requirements in what appeared to be an move to keep
others from fleeing.
   President Bush ordered new sanctions on China to retaliate for
the military's crackdown on the movement this month, and the United
States urged China to spare the lives of the 11 demonstrators
sentenced to death and to pardon all those arrested.
   China maintained its surveillance of foreign journalists, and the
Canadian government said it would lodge a formal protest after a
Canadian reporter said authorities tried to abduct her.
   A Beijing University student who was one of the leaders of the
democracy movement was caught and returned to the capital, the
official media reported.
   Liu Gang, 28, was apprehended Monday in Hebei province south of
Beijing, radio and televison news reports said.
   Liu was one of 21 students on a wanted list the government issued
last week. They are accused of masterminding the seven weeks of
demonstrations for greater freedom and an end to official corruption.
   Six of those students have been arrested or have turned
themselves in. Authorities say they have arrested more than 1,360
people for participating in the democracy movement.
   A student who was not on the wanted list was arrested and accused
of ``spreading rumors'' to the U.S. government radio Voice of
America, the People's Daily said Tuesday.
   Tens of millions of Chinese listen to the VOA, a main target of
criticism by the Chinese government, whicates might do if
China carried out the executions.
   In a move apparently designed to tighten the dragnet around
pro-democracy activists, the Chinese government invalidated all exit
permits issued before Tuesday. Chinese must obtain the permits when
seeking visas to travel abroad.
   Chinese police guarding foreign consular offices turned away visa
applicants who did not have the permits. Only three applicants who
approached the U.S. Consulate had obtained the permit, officials aid.
   Chinese who had camped outside some Western embassies for almost
a week said they feared the new regulation would cause delays that
might make them miss the beginning of school terms this summer and
fall.
   Chinese authorities detained a CBS News TV crew for 2{ hours
Tuesday for filming near Tiananmen Square. A CBS reporter said
police confiscated the identity papers of the three crew members but
later returned them and ordered the crew to obey martial law
regulations that ban coverage of the democracy movement.
   The three left for Hong Kong later in the day, although they had
not been ordered to leave, the reporter said.
   The government has ordered six foreign journalists to leave China
for violating martial law regulations imposed in Beijing on May 20.
   A senior Canadian Embassy diplomat said he will meet with Chinese
Foreign Ministry officials Wednesday to protest what he called the
``attempted abduction'' of a Canadian newspaper correspondent.
   Jan Wong, a Canadian-Chinese working for the Toronto Globe and
Mail, said two men tried to force her into a car Monday evening,
saying they wanted to talk to her, but they released her when she
screamed and attracted a crowd. She said the men were in plain
clothes and she believed they were policemen.
   ``We are quite disturbed about the incident and would like to
have some clarification about what it means,'' said Daniel
Dhavernas, minister-counselor at the Canadian Embassy.
   State-run media continued to focus on the families of soldiers
killed on the crackdown, showing the relatives meeting with senior
leaders.
   The families of three soldiers who were beaten to death, thrown
off bridges or set on fire by enraged mobs June 4 met with Beijing
Mayor Chen Xitong and former President Li Xiannen.
   In previous days, the families met with Premier Li Peng and
President Yang Shangkun.
   The news also showed busy factories and students back at school.
   Workers at a major hotel and a restaurant said they were being
ordered back to work on Tuesday and Wednesday, but that they were
required to write reports about their activities since June 3.
   They said they also were ordered to devote half a day Tuesday to
studying a June 9 speech by senior leader Deng Xiaoping calling on
Chinese to unite behind the Communist Party.
