<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     06-20 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attention Turns to Presidency After Polish Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Official results Tuesday confirmed that
Solidarity clinched 260 of the 261 seats it was allowed to contest
in the new National Assembly, guaranteeing the union a veto over
Communist Party legislation.
   But two days after Sunday's voting, politicians from both sides
already were turning attention to the election of Poland's first
president in 37 years.
   Results issued by the National Electoral Commission showed
Solidarity holding 99 of 100 seats in the Senate, the East bloc's
first democratically elected parliament chamber.
   The independent union also gained 161 seats in the lower house,
the Sejm, compared to 299 seats held by the Communist-led coalition.
That gave the Communist coalition 65 percent of Sejm seats and
Solidarity 35 percent, the ratio permitted under a pre-election
bargain.
   But the Communist Party had only 173 of the coalition seats,
making it technically a minority. Minor pro-government Catholic
groups made up the remainder of coalition places.
   And among the Communist coalition's seats, at least 46 were
progressives endorsed by Solidarity. Several prominent hard-line
Communists were defeated.
   ``There is hope that in the new Sejm we will find partners who
understand our causes and who, like us, favor the process of
reform,'' Solidarity spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said Tuesday.
   The two sides in the Assembly will be roughly balanced so that
``either there will be cooperation between the coalition and the
opposition or we will face a chain of conflicts that will block the
legislative process,'' said government spokesman Zbyslaw Rykowski.
   In a next step, the National Assembly convenes within 30 days to
choose a president. The Communist coalition enters the meeting with
about 40 more votes than the opposition, although there could be
defections.
   Choosing the president is the last stage of the political bargain
struck April 5 between the Solidarity-led opposition and Communist
authorities after two months of talks.
   The accord led to the restoration of Solidarity's legal status
after a seven-year ban and the holding of Eastern Europe's freest
parliamentary elections since World War II.
   The new president will sign legislation and be commander-in-chief
of the armed forces. The president will serve one six-year term.
   Poland had five presidents between 1918, when the modern Polish
state was established, and 1952, when the office was abolished by
the Communist Party.
   The president in turn will nominate the next prime minister, who
will form a government.
   Although Communist Party leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, who now
leads the country, is assumed to be the party's candidate, his
spokesman last week said he still has not decided to run.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
