<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Africa-Pollution     06-20 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Africa-Pollution,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Discover Air Pollution Over Much of Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have discovered air
pollution over much of Africa, and it is chemically similar to the
smog that plagues southern California, a research leader said
Tuesday.
   Meinrat Andreae, a chemist with West Germany's Max Planck
Institute, said the deliberate burning of huge savanna areas
produces acid rain and ozone pollution that settles over Africa's
rain forests.
   ``These levels we've seen over the rain forests are dramatically
higher than anything anybody has seen over rain forests before,''
Andreae said in a telephone interview.
   Andreae headed the West German group in a 20-member project that
included scientists from France and the Congo.
   He said his team spent two weeks in the field in the Congo in
February and March of 1988.
   Africa's air pollution is ``a combination of atmospheric
pollutants which is very similar to the sort of smog-type chemistry
that you get in southern California,'' Andreae said.
   ``When the smoke plume spends some time in the atmosphere and has
the sunshine burning on top of it, you start photochemical reactions
just like in any old smog situation in southern California.''
   He said the acidity and ozone levels are similar to those in some
industrialized areas of North America and Europe, and he noted such
levels damage plants, lakes and forests.
   ``There is no reason ... to assume that the equatorial forests
should be more resistant to these sort of pollutant impacts than
those in temperate regions,'' Andreae added.
   He said that while the team's field work was done in the Congo
that country is not a source of the pollutants.
   The area affected by the pollution runs from the ``southern edge
of the Sahara down to South Africa,'' he said. ``It's a phenomenon
that essentially covers all of tropical Africa.
   ``Any country where there are savannas there will be large-scale
burning, typically once a year, sometimes every two years. All the
savannas are burned periodically for agricultural purposes. The
farmers like to burn the shrub and grass in order to remove the old
dry grass and get the fresh grass to sprout.
   ``The amount of burning is increasing rather dramatically, and
also the area covered by burns,'' he said. ``There are more people _
the population of all those regions is growing dramatically.''
   Andreae is a director of the Max Planck Institute for Chemistry
in Mainz.
</TEXT>
