<FIRST>r i AM-Dominican-Strike     06-20 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dominican-Strike,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Forces Wound 4 Strikers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces shot and
wounded four protesters and looters Tuesday on the second day of a
general strike over rising prices and poor services, an independent
radio report said.
   At least three civilians were reported killed and a dozen wounded
in street battles Monday when this impoverished Caribbean nation
began a 48-hour nationwide stoppage.
   Francisco Antonio Santos, leader of the General Workers' Union,
told reporters they may call a new strike if the government fails to
meet demands.
   President Joaquin Balaguer met for a second day with Roman
Catholic archbishops trying to mediate with the strikers. The
clergymen were to meet strike leaders later Tuesday.
   Radio Popular said security forces wounded two youths, one
seriously, when they opened fire to stop a mob trying to plunder a
grocery store in La Vega, 85 miles north of Santo Domingo.
   In Barahona, 125 miles southwest of the capital, soldiers fired
at youths burning tires in the street and wounded two, the report
said.
   Normally jammed streets of Santo Domingo, a city of 1.6 million,
were virtually deserted for a second day.
   Armed soldiers and police patrolled the capital, where stores,
restaurants and office buildings remained closed. Banks shut down
after opening Monday under police and military guard.
   Strikers want better public services, price freezes and a
doubling of salaries for government workers, who earn a monthly
average of $65.
   Power cuts and water shortages plague this island nation of 6.5
million people, and inflation has hit 60 percent a year.
   Balaguer's economic adviser, Juan Jose Artega, said the strike
will cost the country $35 million.
</TEXT>
