<FIRST>r w AM-Shoreham-Ritter     06-20 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shoreham-Ritter,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania Congressman Trying To Block Shoreham Shutdown Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Don Ritter, R-Pa., has introduced
legislation to block any federal tax deductions from the plan to
shut the controversial Shoreham nuclear power plant in New York.
   Ritter, who quietly introduced the bill last Thursday, took to
the House floor Tuesday to rally support and seek co-sponsors.
   Ritter objects to the fact that the Long Island Lighting Co.
would be able to write off some $2.8 billion in expenditures if it
sells the plant to New York state for $1 as planned.
   ``Misery loves company but the state of New York doesn't have the
right to share its misery with the American taxpayer,'' Ritter said.
   His measure would alter the tax code to deny any deduction for
unrecovered expenditures on the abandonment of a fully licensed
nuclear plant.
   The bill was referred to the House Ways and Means Committee,
where senior New York Democrats such as Reps. Charles Rangel and
Thomas Downey could be expected to block it.
   Ritter said he was uncertain how the bill would fare in
committee, but ``we're going to leave some big legislative history
behind.''
   Under a plan negotiated by Gov. Mario Cuomo and teh company,
Shoreham would be sold to the state for a symbolic dollar in
exchange for a series of rate increases. Shoreham's license would be
transferred to the Long Island Power Authority, which would contract
with the New York Power Authority to decommission the $5.5 billion
plant.
   The Energy Department has said it will do everything in its power
to keep the plant from being decommission. Deputy Secretary Henson
Moore last week wrote the New York Power Authority that it would
exceed its legal authority if it undertook the decommissioning.
   Cuomo's plan has been approved by everybody involved in New York
except the company shareholders, who vote June 28.
</TEXT>
