<SECOND>AM-Cuba-US,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuba Accuses Guantanamo Personnel of Violating Sovereignty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban military newspaper said Tuesday that
servicemen at the U.S. Naval Base at Guantanamo are violating Cuba's
territorial sovereignty.
   In a dispatch monitored here, the Cuban news agency Prensa Latina
quoted the newspaper Bastion as saying three incidents occurred this
month.
   It reported Bastion said the latest incident happened June 15
when an American serviceman ducked under the base's northwest fence
and ``illegally occupied'' Cuban territory for four minutes.
   Bastion claimed there were two incidents on June 10 involving
U.S. aircraft. It said a helicopter flew 200 yards over Cuba near
the northwest corner of the base and a small plane violated Cuban
air space from the west.
   The newspaper reported that Defense Minister Raul Castro,
President Fidel Castro's brother, said last week there is an
``escalation of provocations by the United States against Cuba.''
   It said Castro also spoke of ``certain U.S. notes of protests in
April denouncing alleged exploratory penetrations by Cuban
soldiers'' of the base perimeter, and he called those assertions
``absolutely unfounded.''
   The United States has held the base on Cuba's eastern tip for 87
years.
