<DOCNO> AP890620-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 2141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FreedomCaravan 1stLd-Writethru a0705 06-20 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Freedom Caravan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0705,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northern Civil Rights Workers Commemorate 1964 Murders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with caravan arriving for night
in Meridian. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `An FBI...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MERIDIAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of northern civil rights workers
arrived in Mississippi on Tuesday to relive _ for one day _ the
long, hot summer of 1964.
   The riders, predominantly blacks, traveled 30 hours from New York
City and Philadelphia, Pa. They came to take part in memorial
services commemorating the murders of James Chaney, Andrew Goodman
and Michael Schwerner on June 21, 1964.
   ``This state has a dark history and I wanted to see what
Mississippi is like,'' said Viola Sulton, 76, of Philadelphia, Pa.
   An FBI investigation revealed Goodman, Schwerner and Chaney were
killed by members of the Ku Klux Klan and their bodies were buried
in an earthen dam near Philadelphia, 40 miles north of here. The
murders occurred while the three volunteers were trying to keep
alive a voter registration drive in neighboring Neshoba County,
where Philadelphia is located.
   The crime was one of the most sensational events during the civil
rights movement of the 1960s. The killings, and subsequent coverup
by Neshoba County officials, ignited indignation around the country
and marked a dramatic and tragic beginning to the so-called
``Mississippi Freedom Summer Project,'' which brought young people
from the North pouring into Mississippi.
   Tuesday's caravan was modeled after those earlier caravans. It
was scheduled to spend the night in Meridian and go on to
Philadelphia Wednesday for a day of ceremonies marking the 25th
anniversary of the murders.
   Philadelphia Mayor Charles McClain said his town was ready for
the visitors, which were to include relatives of the victims and the
governors of Mississippi and Pennsylvania.
   ``I have to admit our people have mixed emotions about this
event,'' McClain said Tuesday while attending a Meridian luncheon
for relatives of Chaney, a native son of Mississippi and former
resident of Meridian.
   McClain added he didn't expect any trouble on Wednesday but
acknowledged that not everybody in Philadelphia, a farming community
of 7,000 residents, is happy about the memorial service.
   However, Mississippi Secretary of State Dick Molpus said state
officials hope to use the event to show the world that many positive
changes have taken place in Mississippi since the bloody summer of
1964.
   ``We intend to send a message to the nation that the only thing
burning in Mississippi today is a desire for a better life for all
our people,'' Molpus said, in an oblique reference to ``Mississippi
Burning,'' a recent, controversial movie about the murders.
   McClain, meanwhile, said he had doubts about Mississippi Attorney
General Mike Moore's statement last weekend that he might reopen a
state investigation of the 1964 murders.
   ``It could be a pretty rocky thing for our community,'' McClain
said. ``We've come 25 years and made a lot of progress and a
reopening of the murder investigation could set us back to ground
zero.''
   Ben Chaney, brother of the slain James Chaney, differed with
McClain.
   ``I think it would be good to reopen the case,'' he said Tuesday.
``An investigation might help bring out some of the terrible things
that happened in Neshoba County back then, such as the beatings at
the Mt. Zion Methodist Church shortly before the Ku Klux Klan burned
the church.''
   Wednesday's commemoration ceremonies are set to begin at the
small, predominantly black church on the outskirts of Philadelphia.
The church was rebuilt the year after it was burned by the klan.
   On the day they were killed, Schwerner and Goodman _ white
volunteers from the New York City area _ went with Chaney to Neshoba
County to visit church members and keep alive a fledgling voters
registration drive in that county. They were jailed on a traffic
charge and later turned over to a KKK mob which killed them and
buried the bodies.
   The state never did bring murder charges in the case but 19
Mississipians, most from the Meridian and Philadelphia areas, were
prosecuted under federal laws for violating the civil rights of the
three victims.
   Seven men eventually were convicted and an eighth pleaded guilty.
Their prison sentences ranged from three to 10 years prison but the
most any ever served was six years.
   The U.S. House of Representitives on Tuesday declared Wednesday
to be ``Chaney, Goodman and Schwerner Day'' in honor of the three
victims. The Senate passed an identical resolution on June 9.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 2150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AncientForests     06-20 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ancient Forests,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subcommittee Chairmen Say Old-Growth Logging A National Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three House subcommittee chairmen warned
Tuesday the fight over logging in the ancient forests of the Pacific
Northwest was more than just a regional conflict and they would keep
a close watch to ensure national interests were protected.
   The chairman of the interior subcommittee of the House
Appropriations Committee, Rep. Sidney Yates, D-Ill., offered an
amendment to the interior appropriations bill which would have
forced the Forest Service to provide for cutting methods in all
timber sales that would result in ``minimal fragmentation'' of
remaining old-growth stands.
   The two Northwest members of the subcommittee, Rep. Norm Dicks,
D-Wash., and Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore., were caught off guard by
Yates' amendment and quickly objected.
   Yates agreed to withdraw the amendment, but said he might offer
it again when the full committee considers the bill.
   ``My intent was to protect old growth to the greatest extent
possible,'' Yates said. ``This is a national issue.''
   Meanwhile, the chairmen of two other subcommittees said during a
joint hearing that they too were concerned.
   ``Although these forests are found primarily in the Pacific
Northwest, all Americans have a stake in them,'' said Rep. Bruce
Vento, chairman of the national parks and public lands subcommittee
of the House Interior Committee.
   Rep. Harold Volkmer, D-Mo., chairman of the forests, family farms
and energy subcommittee of the House Agriculture Committee, said the
future of the old-growth forests presented tough policy questions
for lawmakers.
   ``It's of tremendous national concern and we need to make
decisions in the best interests of all our citizens,'' said Volkmer.
   Both Vento's and Volkmer's subcommittee write legislation for the
Forest Service, an arm of the Agriculture Department, while Yates'
panel provides money for the service.
   The cathedral-like forests, with trees up to 1,000 years old,
several hundred feet high and up to eight feet thick, have been the
focal point of an increasingly bitter fight between
environmentalists and the timber industry.
   Environmentalists have sought to have the spotted owl protected
as an endangered or threatened species as part of their campaign to
halt logging in the old-growth forests of the Northwest. The
industry has claimed such protection would close vast areas of the
Northwest to logging, creating an economic catastrophe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
