<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Bulgaria     06-20 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Bulgaria,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 50,000 Ethnic Turks Leave Bulgaria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50,000 ethnic Turks have poured
across the border from Bulgaria since May to escape government
persecution, officials said Tuesday.
   Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz on Monday took 53 ambassadors to
the frontier and called for world condemnation of the Bulgaria's
``primitive'' policies. He urged the United Nations Security Council
to take up the issue.
   Yilmaz also said Turkey expected a clearer stand from Eastern
bloc countries, particularly the Soviet Union, on the problem.
   In 1983, Bulgaria implemented a forced assimilation campaign,
under which ethnic Turks were to change their Moslem names to
Christian Slavic ones. The campaign also barred the public use of
the Turkish language and the practice of Islamic rites.
   In May, ethnic Turks demonstrated against the campaign and police
attacked them with dogs and clubs, killing about 40 people. On May
26, Bulgaria began mass deportations of ethnic Turks they said were
leading the protests.
   Premier Turgut Ozal on Tuesday reiterated his call to Bulgaria to
open negotiations on the immigration of ethnic Turks. Bulgaria says
the Moslem minority numbers 780,000, while Turkish officials put it
at 2.5 million in the total population of 9 million.
   Ozal has proposed talks on an immigration agreement that would
allow ethnic Turks to dispose of their property and bring out liquid
assets. Deportees have said they were not allowed to take with them
more than a suitcase.
   Through defections and immigration agreements, 380,00 ethnic
Turks have come to Turkey since 1925.
</TEXT>
