<FIRST>r a AM-CoelhoBlamed     06-20 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coelho Blamed,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arkansas Congressman Won't Run Again; Blames Coelho for Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former House Majority Whip Tony Coelho
was ``throwing money away like crazy to get elected whip,'' leaving
the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee heavily in debt, its
chairman said Tuesday.
   U.S. Rep. Beryl Anthony of Arkansas told the Arkansas Democrat
newspaper that he inherited a $1.4 million debt from Coelho, a
former representative from California. Anthony said he then had to
borrow more money to fulfill promises Coelho had made, raising the
debt to $1.8 million.
   Anthony said that was part of the reason he was not going to seek
a third term as chairman of the committee, which he said Coelho had
turned into a political machine to which countless House Democrats
were indebted.
   ``Everybody thought Tony was the greatest thing since sliced
bread,'' said Anthony, also a Democrat. ``Yet I took over a
committee burdened with a huge debt purely and simply because Tony
Coelho was throwing money away like crazy to get elected whip. He
would give members anything they wanted in return for a commitment.''
   Telephone calls made by The Associated Press to Coelho's Virginia
office were not answered Tuesday.
   Coelho became House majority whip in 1987. He resigned recently
in the face of a likely ethics inquiry into his financial dealings.
   The committee's debt is nearly three times its reported 1987
debt. Anthony, named committee chairman in December 1986 and
re-elected without opposition in January to a second, two-year term,
said he worked until September 1987 to reduce the inherited debt.
   ``I wasn't able to start raising funds for my tenure as chairman
for nine months,'' he said. ``Still, I attempted to put things in as
positive a light as possible.''
   The debt shot back up last fall, Anthony said, because he had to
borrow more money late in the election cycle to fulfill promises to
candidates. The committee generates money for distribution to party
members seeking House seats.
   ``This committee certainly is not in worse shape than it was when
I took over,'' he said.
   Anthony also said knowledge of the debt did not hurt him in the
race to succeed Coelho as House majority whip. Anthony finished
third with 30 of 261 votes cast.
   Anthony said he has not talked about the debt in the past because
there was ``nothing to be gained at the time by pointing fingers.''
But now that Coelho is gone, ``there is no reason to keep it a big,
dark secret.''
</TEXT>
