<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 2240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     06-20 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>`The Loman Family Picnic,' A Play by Donald Margulies, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mix Arthur Miller with Neil Simon and a bit of
Jule Styne, and you'll get ``The Loman Family Picnic'' by Donald
Margulies.
   This odd yet imaginative domestic free-for-all, which opened
Tuesday at Manhattan Theater Club's Stage II, keeps the audience
off-balance for most of the evening as the story switches from low
comedy to high drama to hard-sell musical comedy. The changes of
gear could be unsettling, but the playwright and director Barnet
Kellman manage to keep everything spinning for much of the time.
   ``On the day I was married, the world showed every sign of coming
to an end,'' says the play's 38-year-old heroine, Doris. It didn't _
and neither did her marriage to a drab lighting fixture salesman
named Herbie.
   Instead, their lives in a middle-class Coney Island apartment
building just went on and on. The years were highlighted by the
arrival of two sons, Stewie and Mitchell. The play, set in 1965,
turns on Stewie's bar mitzvah, and all the problems and pressures it
produces.
   Like Willy Loman in Miller's ``Death of a Salesman,'' Doris
dreams of a better life and actually believes she has found one with
Herbie. And like Willy, who idolized his successful and adventurous
Uncle Charlie, Doris adores her late and lamented Aunt Marsha who
died at age 23. The ghost of Uncle Charlie hovers over Miller's
classic. Aunt Marsha, a tough-talking, sexy young woman, does the
same in ``The Loman Family Picnic.''
   Doris and Herbie don't really talk. Margulies' dialogue between
husband and wife is a model of non-communication. They don't say
what's on their minds until it is too late.
   The wife focuses her attention on her sons _ the older Stewie,
played with authentic obnoxiousness by Judd Trichter, and the more
artistic and sensitive Mitchell, portrayed with charm and grace by
Michael Miceli.
   Instead of a writing a book report on ``Death of a Salesman,''
Mitchell creates a mini-musical comedy. He calls it ``Willy!'' and
it bursts upon the stage late in Act 2 after the family has had a
major blow-up over the bar mitzvah.
   Mitchell's music for ``Willy!'' is by David Shire, composer of
``Baby'' and ``Starting Here, Starting Now.'' It has the brassy,
uptempo sound of a Styne show, a style totally at odds with the
humdrum happenings on stage. But that's the point of Margulies'
family tale.
   The playwright even adds several alternate endings to the play,
imagining what the characters would like to happen and what really
does. It's funny and a bit sad at the same time.
   Marcia Jean Kurtz gives a marvelously funny and touching
performance as the mother. Doris refuses to give up or grow old.
Dressed as the Bride of Frankenstein, she goes trick or treating
with her sons on Halloween and cuts up her wedding dress for a
costume. She keeps repeating, ``I love my life, I love my life, I
love my life,'' and you believe her.
   Larry Block, one of New York's most underrated character actors,
excels as Herbie. He's a superb physical comedian and a master of
timing. Watch him as he forces himself to eat the diet tuna plate
Doris prepares each evening for him.
   Kellman has a difficult job separating the fantasies from real
life but with the help of the imaginative lighting by Debra J.
Kletter and his hardy troupe of actors, he does just that.
   Out the living room window looms a non-descript apartment
building, much like the high-rises that hem in the Loman home in
Miller's play. Designer G.W. Mercier has an eye for detail, down to
the family's hideous Mediterranean furniture and shag carpeting that
covers the tiny stage.
   ``The Loman Family Picnic'' is an unusual play. It echoes Miller,
Simon and Styne, but it can stand on its own as an original piece of
theater.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 2301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AerodyneIndictments     06-20 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aerodyne Indictments,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Executives Surrender On Charges of Defrauding Defense Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father and son surrendered Tuesday on
charges of defrauding the Defense Department by using lower-quality
scrap metal in engine parts built into thousands of military
aircraft and tanks.
   Russell K. Baker Sr., 63, and Russell K. Baker Jr., 40, of the
Tampa area, both former presidents and general managers of Aerodyne
Investment Castings Inc., were indicted Monday. Also indicted was
Carman Eugene Alexander, 55, a former chief engineer from Converse,
Ind.
   The Bakers surrendered in Tampa and were released on $100,000
bail. Alexander was to surrender in Indianapolis, said Assistant
U.S. Attorney Andrew Grosso. No court date was set.
   The federal indictment charges them with plotting to defraud the
government by using less expensive scrap instead of pure metal for
military aircraft and M-1 Abrams tank parts, then certifying that
tests showed the parts met specifications for pure alloys.
   Alexander and Baker Jr. were charged with lying to the Army about
test results for turbine blade parts and trying to hide the fact
that the blades didn't meet contract specifications.
   The government said the two falsely identified failing results on
lab reports as non-valid and omitted failed test results on
certifications to the Army.
   Baker Jr. also was charged with obstructing justice for allegedly
approving a report for the Department of Defense that contained
false and misleading information.
   The blades manufactured during a 7-year period are used on more
than 22,000 aircraft, including F-16 jets, as well as helicopters
and tanks.
   ``There also appears to be danger to personnel which is not being
adequately addressed by the Department of Defense,'' Rep. John
Dingell, D-Mich., told ABC News. ``I describe the military response
to this problem as being seriously inadequate, callous and probably
seriously indifferent.''
   If convicted, Alexander faces up to 40 years in prison and $1.5
million in fines; the elder Baker faces 20 years and $520,000, and
his son 45 years and $1.7 million.
   The Bakers, along with another of the elder Baker's sons, Roger,
35, were also indicted in April on 11 counts of fraud, conspiracy,
money laundering and theft against Aerodyne.
   They have pleaded innocent to the charges against the company. No
trial date has been set in that case but is expected sometime in
July.
</TEXT>
