<FIRST>r a AM-BrushFire     06-20 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brush Fire,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wildfires Threaten Southern California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wildfire apparently started by target
shooters raged through Southern California brush Tuesday, roaring to
within 1,000 feet of a desert neighborhood where 85 homes were
abandoned by fleeing residents.
   The 600-acre blaze, one of several brush fires in Ventura and San
Bernardino counties, was driven by 45 mph winds and fed on dense,
brittle vegetation as temperatures soared into the 100s.
   Firefighters were managing to keep the flames away from the Yucca
Valley homes late Tuesday. No injuries were reported and no houses
were damaged, said Deborah McClellan of the California Department of
Forestry.
   ``The fire was running in really close. The wind is causing the
firefighters problems. The evacuation was voluntary but about 85
homes were evacuated,'' McClellan said.
   The fire doubled in size in just a half hour and apparently was
started by people target shooting at utility poles, McClellan said.
   Other than the neighborhood threatened, the area 110 miles east
of Los Angeles was a sparsely populated stretch of desert skirting
the Joshua Tree National Monument. The monument was not threatened,
said McClellan.
   In Ventura County, a 300-acre brush fire was being fought by more
than 200 firefighters, and a 115-acre blaze in San Bernardino County
kept about 60 firefighters busy. No damages or injuries were
reported in those fires.
</TEXT>
