<FIRST>r a AM-BabySellers     06-20 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Sellers,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Arrested in Baby-Selling Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four people, including a father-and-daughter
attorney team, were arrested Tuesday for allegedly bilking desperate
couples of $500,000 in a baby-selling scheme that spanned 21 states
and Canada.
   The group ``preyed upon the emotions of these couples'' and ``in
effect, engaged in a black market baby-selling operation,'' said
state Attorney General Robert Abrams.
   The four were named in 144-count indictment alleging they
arranged illegal adoptions for about 100 couples from around the
country. Fifty couples wound up with the infants between 1983 and
1988, Abrams said.
   An investigation disclosed that the defendants enticed
prospective parents into paying extra fees and supposed expenses of
the birth mothers, Abrams said.
   Some prospective parents paid up to $16,000 and did not receive a
child or receive their money back, Abrams said. The couples were
told the birth mothers had miscarried or changed their minds.
   The babies were found primarily through advertisements placed in
a supermarket checkout counter tabloid, and the couples who wanted
babies were found through word of mouth, officials said.
   Abrams said neither the mothers who gave up their children nor
the parents who adopted the infants face any charges.
   The four were charged with grand larceny, conspiracy, fraud,
perjury, filing false documents and making false statements. The
charges stem from the illegal operation of Child Haven of
Northeastern Pennsylvania, a private adoption agency.
   They pleaded innocent before Manhattan Criminal Court Judge Carol
Berkman.
   The most serious charge carries a maximum of seven years in
prison and a $5,000 fine or double the amount illegally gained.
Abrams said he also would seek restitution.
   Arrested were attorney Seymour Fenichel, 65; his daughter,
attorney Deborah Fenichel Greenspan, 35; Harriet Lauer, 46; and her
husband, Lawrence, 53; all of New York City.
   The elder Fenichel was released on $100,000 personal security
bond. His daughter was released on $2,500 bail. The Lauers were
released when they promised to pay $10,000 bail within two weeks.
</TEXT>
