<DOCNO> AP890620-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:AnneFrank Adv22   06-20 1147</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Anne Frank, Adv 22,1182</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Thursday June 22 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Anne Frank Anniversary Commemorated in New Book</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Am I only fourteen? Am I really still a silly little
schoolgirl? Am I really so inexperienced about everything? I have
more experience than most; I have been through things that hardly
anyone of age has undergone.'' _ Anne Frank, April 28, 1944.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anne Frank turned 13 on June 12, 1942. She
received a blue blouse, roses, a bottle of slightly fermented grape
juice, a party game, a plant, a dish of sticky molasses, a bowl of
truffles and a homemade strawberry tart.
   She was also given a squarish book, commonly used to collect
autographs, with a red and white checked cover. Anne began keeping a
diary.
   What began as an adolescent's longing for self-knowledge evolved
into a lasting document about the destruction of human life, the
tragic loss of innocence and unfathomable hatred of the Holocaust.
   Forced into hiding by the Nazis, Anne chronicled her days with
uncommon humor, perceptiveness and faith in the goodness of people.
``The Diary of Anne Frank'' stands as a moving, tangible document,
and has sold millions of copies around the world.
   Anne died at the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp in 1945, and
would have been 60 this year. A critical edition of her diary has
been released in the United States by Doubleday.
   A popular student at a Jewish school in Amsterdam, Anne Frank was
a pretty, dark-haired girl, outspoken in class and admired by many
boys. Yet the diary would prove to be her most cherished friend.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I have darling parents and a sister (Margot) of 16. I know
about 30 people whom one might call friends _ I have strings of boy
friends, anxious to catch a glimpse of me and who, failing that,
peep at me through mirrors in class. I have relations, aunts and
uncles, who are darlings too, a good home, no _ I don't seem to lack
anything.
   ``But it's the same with all my friends, just fun and joking,
nothing more. ... We don't seem to be able to get any closer. .. .
Perhaps I lack confidence, but anyway, there it is, a stubborn fact
and I don't seem to be able to do anything about it.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   While hiding from the Nazis, Anne was transformed from a playful
girl of 13 to an insightful, compassionate, even spiritual
15-year-old. On Jan. 6, 1944, she recalled a dream about a boy from
school:
   ``I awoke at this point, while I could still feel his cheek
against mine and felt his brown eyes looking deep into my heart, so
deep, that here he read how much I loved him and how much I still
love him. Tears sprang into my eyes once more, and I was very sad
that I had lost him again. ...''
   In another dream, she saw her late grandmother and a friend from
school.
   ``... Granny appeared as a guardian angel; then followed Hanneli,
who seems to be a symbol to me of all the sufferings of all my
girlfriends and all Jews. When I pray for her, I pray for all Jews
and all those in need. ...''
   Prepared by the Netherlands State Institute for War
Documentation, the book includes essays on the Franks before and
after they went into hiding, the events surrounding their capture,
and how the diary reached publication.
   The new edition contains three versions of the diary: Anne's
first and second drafts, and the original published work, which
combines the two.
   But commemorating her birth was not the only reason for the
reissue. The book also offers a strong rebuttal to accusations made
over the years that the diary was fake, a shameless exploitation.
   In the late 1950s, right-wing newspapers in Austria and Norway
published attacks on the diary, insisting the ideas expressed were
far too sophisticated for a teen-age girl. In the mid-'70s, a German
publishing house began distributing pamphlets repeating charges that
Otto Frank, Anne's father, had written the diary with the help of a
New York playwright.
   Upon Frank's death in 1980, the original manuscripts were turned
over to the Netherlands war documentation institute; work on the
critical edition began the following year. One of the book's
editors, Gerrold van der Stroom, insisted in a recent interview that
the diary is indeed authentic.
   ``We asked the Dutch forensic laboratory of the Ministry of
Justice, which does the same work for police, to check the paper and
ink. They found that all the paper and all the ink, were very common
for the first half of the 1940s,'' he said.
   ``They also compared the letters before the war, postcards, etc.,
that she had written to her grandmother in Switzerland, with the
handwriting in the diaries. They found that the same person wrote
everything.''
   The Franks lived in Frankfurt, Germany, until 1933 when they
emigrated to Amsterdam after Hitler took power. The Nazis occupied
the Netherlands in 1940, and began imposing ever harsher anti-Jewish
laws, forcing Jews to wear a yellow six-pointed star.
   When the SS, the Nazi military police, issued a call-up notice to
Frank in July 1942, the family was forced into hiding. For more than
two years, the Franks and four others were holed up in a ``Secret
Annexe,'' located upstairs from Frank's warehouse in Amsterdam.
   They relied on friends, notably Miep and Jan Gies, to bring them
food and supplies, and prayed that the Allied troops would liberate
their country before the Nazis could find them.
   Police raided the annex on Aug. 4, 1944, and the prisoners were
sent off to Westerbork, a Jewish transit camp. Anne and her sister,
Margot, were later shipped to the notorious death camp, Auschwitz,
and eventually to Bergen-Belsen, where they contracted typhoid fever
and perished within days of each other in the winter of 1945. Their
mother died at another camp.
   After the arrest, Miep Gies gathered up Anne's papers and kept
them under lock and key. When Frank returned to Amsterdam in June
1945, he headed straight for the Gies home and was presented with
his daughter's journals.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I see the eight of us with our `Secret Annexe' as if we were a
little piece of blue heaven, surrounded by heavy black rain
clouds,'' Anne Frank wrote on Nov. 8, 1943.
   ``The round, clearly defined spot where we stand is safe, but the
clouds gather more closely about us and the circle which separates
us from the approaching danger closes more and more tightly.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In 1947, a Dutch edition of the diary was published to
overwhelming acclaim. The book has since been printed in more than
30 countries, including West Germany, Finland, Spain, Argentina,
Iceland and Japan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for AMs Thurs June 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-GreenRocks Adv26   06-20 1119</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Green Rocks, Adv 26,1149</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Monday June 26 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Intoxicating `Green Rocks' Part of Juarez's Plague of Waste</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gilberto Campos was alarmed when he
found his sons sniffing green rocks that kids carried away from the
municipal dump.
   Fourteen-year-old Luis and 18-year-old Jose lurched and stumbled
in the unpaved streets, occasionally pulling a sock out of a pocket
and sniffing it. The socks held a bright green, rocky substance that
smelled like airplane glue or spray paint. When crushed and sniffed,
it gave the same cheap highs.
   The rocks surfaced in March and quickly became the drug of choice
around the vast dump, an area where the well-off live in cinderblock
houses and others make do with cardboard huts. Young children
flocked to it, according to dozens of worried parents interviewed by
Juarez newspapers.
   ``It makes people stupid and aggressive _ more aggressive than a
drunk,'' said the Campos, whose sons shoved and hit him when he
confronted them. They ``would lie on the couch and wouldn't get up.''
   The green rocks proved to be toxic waste dumped by a
``maquiladora,'' one of 275 U.S.-owned factories located in Juarez
to take advantage of cheap labor. Mexican environmental suspect
maquiladoras improperly dispose of half their hazardous waste. That
would be hundreds of tons a year in Juarez alone.
   The officials in Juarez say they have gotten rid of the green
rocks and cracked down on toxic wastes at the dump, but gangs of
toughs known as ``cholos'' still collect and sell intoxicating
substances.
   Campos didn't know any of that in late March when he took some of
the rocks to a reform school principal. She didn't know what they
were.
   About the same time, a woman walked into the Centro de
Integracion Juvenil, a drug treatment center for children, and told
psychologist Raul Bueno that her 10-year-old son was sniffing green
rocks. ``She said that at the dump, there were lots of other
children who used this.''
   Bueno, who estimates that about 200 children experimented with
the substance, sent it to the Secretariat Urban Development and
Ecology, or SEDUE _ the beleaguered equivalent of the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency.
   SEDUE identified it as solidified Kaltex, an industrial solvent
containing toluene, a petroleum derivative that can cause lung
damage.
   A doctor told Campos him the Kaltex did more than that to his
sons. ``When they get married, they can't have children,'' Campos
said.
   Infertility is one possible side effect when adolescents use
inhalants like toluene, said Dr. Antonio Carrasco of the La Fe
family clinic in south El Paso, where inhalant abuse is widespread.
If users don't become infertile, their children are likely to be
deformed.
   Inhalants harm the liver and kidneys and can cause organic brain
syndrome _ characterized by loss of coordination, irritability,
chronic confusion and nerve injury, Carrasco said. And they can
destroy tear ducts.
   ``After a while, they can't even cry, and they're subject to eye
infections,'' he said. ``I think inhalant abuse is one of the worst
_ and it's one of the most available for young kids.''
   Parents reported seeing cholos jumping onto trucks turning off
Avenue of the Aztecs onto the dirt road leading to the dump. The
cholos would toss five-, 10- and 20-gallon plastic buckets of waste
off to sell. When SEDUE officials inspected the dump April 6, they
found dozens of buckets of Kaltex.
   Campos, who kept several chunks of Kaltex as souvenirs, said a
piece the size of his foot goes for 10,000 pesos _ about $4.35.
   In late April, SEDUE traced the Kaltex to Outboard Marine de
Mexico, which makes parts for Johnson and Evinrude outboard boat
engines.
   Officials at the Waukegan, Wis.-based manufacturer referred all
questions to Tim Anklam, manufacturing engineer in the Juarez plant.
   Anklam said news reports about the solvent residue had been
greatly exaggerated and that representatives from the factory and
SEDUE scoured the dump in late April and found three five-gallon
plastic buckets that had originated at Outboard Marine de Mexico,
called Omex for short.
   ``Omex accepts the possibility that the three pails ... could
have been dumped by accident at the Juarez landfill. It was just a
human error, if in fact it is ours. A lot of companies use similar
materials around here,'' said Anklam, adding that Omex is
cooperating with SEDUE and acting legally.
   Mexican law requires hazardous waste from maquiladoras to be
returned to their place of origin, usually the United States. U.S.
law requires companies returning hazardous waste to Texas to notify
the Texas Water Commission, which shares information with the EPA.
   But Roger Meacham, EPA spokesman in Dallas, said tracking waste
through paperwork is time-consuming _ and even if the EPA had no
record of a company returning waste to the United States, it
wouldn't mean much.
   ``If the wastes are from raw materials from Mexico, they can be
disposed of in Mexico,'' he said. ``Or if it's recyclable, it can be
recycled in Mexico. Or they can store their waste on-site in Mexico
indefinitely.''
   Rosa Manuela Salas, chief of SEDUE's office in Juarez, said Omex
is complying with Mexican law. She referred all other questions to
Carlos James, communications chief for SEDUE. James did not return
numerous calls to his home and office from The Associated Press.
   Ms. Salas told the newspaper Diario de Juarez that Omex was the
first maquiladora to be caught throwing toxic waste into the Juarez
dump. ``To ensure this doesn't happen again, we're giving an
identification number to each business that generates waste, to make
it easier to watch them.''
   But it is difficult for SEDUE to keep watch. The agency has 10
inspectors in Juarez to monitor 275 maquiladoras and at least 100
Mexican-owned factories. Faced with a crushing national debt, a
severe housing shortage and a population boom that adds 1 million
people to the work force a year, Mexico's government has not been
able to make environmental protection a high priority.
   So far, SEDUE's plan doesn't seem to be working. Luis Hernandez,
the dump's foreman, said he doesn't know what's in the scores of
trucks that deposit waste in the landfill daily. Neither do the
drivers, he said.
   But the cholos seem to know. They still wait at the corner where
trucks turn to go to the dump. They still jump on, and they still
toss buckets off the speeding trucks for collection later.
   Luis Campos takes part.
   ``There are 10 other kinds of intoxicants there,'' Gilberto
Campos said. ``Paint, adhesive ....''
   He shrugged helplessly, lowered his gaze, and sighed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for AMs Monday June 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
