<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00-1stLd-Writethru b0804 06-20 0840</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00-1st Ld-Writethru, b0804,0881</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to CORRECT spelling of its and SUBS 5th graf, The
first ..., to fix awkward sentence.</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Stealing Home'' (Warner Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated
PG-13.)
   
   ``Stealing Home,'' with its baseball underpinnings, is a sweet
little tale of coming-of-age in middle-class America, a place with
proms and summer at the beach.
   It's good stuff for a family Saturday night viewing, but you
might need a bit of parental guidance for the younger set.
   Mark Harmon stars as the would-be baseball hero and Jodie Foster
as a free spirit who commits suicide. She was his baby sitter as a
child and sometime lover as a young adult.
   But there are two major problems with the film.
   The first is that Foster's character, Katy Chandler, never really
gets a chance to develop. We see far too little of her in the movie
to really understand her motivation and direction or to explain her
suicide.
   The other problem is the overwhelming use of flashbacks. The
whole thing is a flashback, with flashbacks inside the flashback,
which really jumbles the timing.
   The story unwinds through Harmon, who daydreams as he sits on a
minor league bench. Harmon, as Billy, the charming all-American kid,
does a neat job of coming back from a ne'er-do-well to cleancut
baseball player after he returns home to dispose of Katy's ashes.
   The daydream proceeds through the odyssey of growing up and, of
course, the greatest of all youthful experiences _ stealing home
from third base.
   _ By Chris French, Associated Press Writer
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Torch Song Trilogy'' (RCA-Columbia Pictures Home Video.
VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated R.)
   
   ``There are easier things in life,'' says Arnold, as he sits at
his dressing table making up to perform as Virginia Hamm, ``than
being a drag queen. But you see, I ain't got no choice. ... I can't
walk in flats.''
   And, throughout ``Torch Song Trilogy,'' it's clear there are
easier things than living openly as a homosexual who demands the
love and respect of the people he loves.
   But Arnold Beckoff (Harvey Fierstein) persists, and his joys and
sorrows make a funny and moving film, adapted from the Broadway play
for which Fierstein received acting and writing Tony awards.
   As Arnold searches for domestic happiness, first with a bisexual
teacher (Brian Kerwin) who cannot commit, then with a young model
(Matthew Broderick) who is only too happy to do so, it becomes clear
his toughest challenge is his mother.
   Arnold performs at Club East 4th, a good-natured club of female
impersonators who act as surrogate family to one another in pre-AIDS
New York. He hopes for a spouse and to adopt a child.
   Fierstein does not avoid or minimize the pain Arnold causes his
parents or the pain they cause him.
   ``It kills me to think they look at me and wonder what they did
wrong,'' he says one day to his brother. ``You call this a life, I
call it a sickness,'' his mother (Anne Bancroft) screams at one
point.
   Arnold is streetwise and vulnerable, and Fierstein is capable of
an amazing range of facial expression. His performance is moving and
endearing. Broderick and Bancroft also are excellent, directed by
Paul Bogart.
   _ By Mary MacVean, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Daffy Duck's Quackbusters'' (Warner Home Video. VHS-Beta,
$19.98.)
   
   Adult Merrie Melodies mavens will be disappointed by ``Daffy
Duck's Quackbusters,'' a newly animated feature-length video that
strings together snippets of old Daffy classics with newer material
meant to be a send-up of ``Ghostbusters.''
   This formula is already familiar on television, as Bugs Bunny
Christmas or Thanksgiving shows or the like.
   But the sad result is that you have cartoon classics, with their
sophisticated wit and superior animation and voice characterization,
patched together by fair-to-middling new animation.
   The satiric bite that made Warner Bros. cartoons fun for all ages
is now largely missing. ``Daffy Duck's Quackbusters'' is OK for the
kids, but for adults there are certainly better video anthologies
around.
   Even more sadly, what everyone will notice is that Daffy just
doesn't sound like his zany self. Nor do the other characters like
Porky and Bugs. The great Mel Blanc, who has been the voice of
nearly all the Warner Bros. cartoon characters for some 50 years, is
now 80.
   Unfortunately, this 1980s vintage Daffy seems like the pug who
didn't know when to hang up the gloves.
   By Lee Mitgang, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
