<SECOND>PM-Pope-Bankers,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Urges U.S. Bankers to Be Compassionate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II has urged U.S. bank
executives to be compassionate in dealing with poor nations' debts,
saying the problem threatens world peace.
   The pope made the appeal Monday while receiving members of the
board of Chase Manhattan Bank at the Vatican.
   He said there are some who believe that ``today's economic,
political and social programs are so vast and impersonal as to be
beyond effective control.''
   But he said, ``attitudes and decisions of leaders like yourselves
do make a profound difference for good or ill in shaping the future
of humanity. I am confident ... that you will not fail to be
compassionate as well as responsible.''
   John Paul told the bankers that the international debt question
``remains a serious threat to the peace and progress of the human
family.''
</TEXT>
