<FIRST>r f PM-Colgate-Palmolive     06-20 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colgate-Palmolive,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colgate Buying Back $410 million in Stock, Expanding ESOP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colgate-Palmolive Co. says it will buy back $410
million worth of its shares, or approximately 2 percent of
outstanding stock, and expand its employee stock ownership plan.
   The consumer product company's shares closed up $1 a share at
$50.87{ in New York Stock Exchange trading Monday.
   Colgate said Monday the moves would increase the value of its
stock. However, many companies, even those not facing takeover
threats, have been buying their own stock and setting up or
expanding employee stock plans recently, in part because of their
value as takeover defenses.
   With fewer shares on the market, a company is less vulnerable to
a takeover threat. Furthermore, employees who hold stock in a
company are considered more likely than other shareholders to to
side with management in a takeover fight.
</TEXT>
