<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern     06-20 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Plans New Expansion; Pilots Skeptical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines says that by Aug. 1 it
will offer five times as many flights as currently scheduled, but
striking pilots were skeptical of the plan.
   Eastern, whose operations were virtually grounded by the walkout
that started March 4, is flying only 79 flights daily. It said
Monday it plans to increase that number to 226 by July 2 and 390 by
Aug. 1.
   The strike by the Machinists union, which has been supported by
pilots and flight attendants, forced Eastern to seek bankruptcy
protection from creditors on March 9.
   ``We're on target with the buildup outlined in our April business
plan,'' said George Brennan, Eastern's vice president of marketing.
``By August we'll be at mid-point with the addition of 21 new
cities.''
   In April, Eastern's management proposed a plan to rebuild as a
carrier about two-thirds its original size and to sell about $1.8
billion in assets to pay off debts. The plan still must be approved
by federal bankruptcy court and a committee representing Eastern's
major creditors.
   Hank Weber, a spokesman for the pilots union, said Eastern does
not have enough newly hired pilots to support even the July 2 level
of 226 flights.
   ``We're just a little bit skeptical,'' Weber said. ``They'll need
400 pilots and they simply haven't got them.''
   He said the carrier would need at least 800 pilots to reach the
Aug. 1 levels but has only 350.
   Eastern could reach the July 2 level for a few days by mobilizing
all management and training pilots, but the company could not
sustain that number of flights, Weber said.
   Eastern said it will increase the number of cities it serves from
27 now to 49 on July 2 and and 70 on Aug. 1.
   Before the strike, Miami-based Eastern, a subsidiary of Texas Air
Corp. of Houston, served 118 cities with 1,040 flights daily.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
