<DOCNO> AP890620-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BladeBattle     06-20 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blade Battle,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wilkinson Sword Responds to Gillette Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wilkinson Sword Inc. has taken a swipe at
Gillette Co. in an escalation of their legal wrangle over razor
blade claims.
   Gillette accused Wilkinson Sword in a suit filed last month in
U.S. District Court in Manhattan of falsely advertising its new
Ultra Glide razor as the ``smoothest, most comfortable shave known
to man.''
   On Monday, Wilkinson Sword filed legal papers in which it
defended its advertising, asked that the suit be dismissed and
accused Gillette of false advertising for calling its Atra Plus
shavers ``The best a man can get.''
   Wilkinson Sword also said Gillette was using monopolistic
practices in suing Wilkinson and ``attempting to intercede'' with
the television networks and independent stations to prevent
Wilkinson from running its commercials.
   Atlanta-based Wilkinson began running ads on May 22 that compared
its Ultra Glide razor with Gillette's Atra Plus. The ad has been run
on several cable TV networks and several local stations.
   Boston-based Gillette said the response from Wilkinson was an
attempt to ``confuse the issue'' of Gillette's false advertising
claim.
   Spokeswoman Michele Szynal said Gillette had filed challenges to
the Wilkinson Sword ads with the networks but said that was a normal
procedure.
   Wilkinson is a small player in the $750 million wet-shave razor
market with about a 4 percent share, compared with more than 60
percent for Gillette.
   Hearings in the case were scheduled to begin Thursday in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OPEC-Subroto     06-20 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OPEC-Subroto,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Secretary-General: World Will Become More Dependent On OPEC
Oil</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subroto, one word, is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN GRIFFITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPARKS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite its recent loss of influence, OPEC
will become a more important source of the world's oil in the 1990s,
its secretary general says.
   In a speech to a group of U.S. oil producers, Subroto said Monday
he thinks the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries will
satisfy up to half of the world's oil demand in the next five years,
up from about 40 percent today.
   ``In OPEC, we see the projected increase in our market share as
leading to the restoration of the influence which is our due,''
Subroto said.
   Conversely, he said, he expects oil production in non-OPEC
countries to fall by about 1 million barrels per day from present
levels during the first half of the 1990s.
   Subroto said no major oil discoveries have been made in non-OPEC
areas and production could drop even more with accidents due to
aging production facilities in the North Sea.
   ``With about 84 percent of the world's total reserves, our member
countries are well placed to support the expansion in world oil
demand projected for the early 1990s,'' he said.
   He added that the 13 OPEC nations are striving for a stable oil
market and he foresees no drastic price hikes over the next five
years.
   Subroto predicted ``only moderate increases in real oil prices''
over the period, but said OPEC's future market behavior will depend
on a variety of factors, including cooperation from independent oil
producers.
   He made his remarks to the U.S. Interstate Oil Compact
Commission, which represents U.S. oil producers. The commission's
semi-annual gathering will be held through Wednesday.
   Its chairman is Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper, who gave an overview
Monday of the Exxon Valdez oil spill in Prince William Sound and its
cleanu-up efforts.
   Cowper said the spill pointed out the need for more environmental
safeguards but warned they would drive up oil production costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
