<FIRST>r f PM-MortgageFund     06-20 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mortgage Fund,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>$570 Million Foreign-Invested Mortgage Fund Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese investors will buy more securities
backed by mortgages on American homes through a $570 million fund,
two Wall Street firms said.
   Salomon Brothers Inc. and Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., the agents who
raised the money, said Monday the fund is the largest investing
primarily in U.S. mortgage securities ever offered outside the
United States.
   The Blackstone Fund for Fannie Mae Mortgage Securities, is
designed to attract more international capital, especially Japanese,
to American mortgage securities markets, the companies said.
   The fund's investment adviser is Blackstone Financial Management,
an affiliate of The Blackstone Group that has net assets of $2.2
billion.
   Fannie Mae, the Federal National Mortgage Association, is a
government-sponsored, privately owned corporation and the nation's
largest investor in home mortgages.
   The principals in the fund said it is part of Fannie Mae's
attempt to broaden the investor base for its mortgage-related
securities in foreign capital markets.
   Fannie Mae Chairman David O. Maxwell said, ``The ultimate winners
will be U.S. home buyers who will enjoy yet another source of
funding for mortgages.''
</TEXT>
