<DOCNO> AP890620-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Banks-Securities     06-20 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Banks-Securities,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Gives Morgan Subsidiary Permission to Underwrite Corporate Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board has given final
permission to a subsidiary of J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. to underwrite
corporate debt, the first time the agency has granted that power to
a commercial bank.
   In January, the Federal Reserve authorized J.P. Morgan and four
other large banks to expand their securities underwriting, but
withheld final approval until it could review the management and
financing of the banks' securities subsidiaries.
   That approval was given to J.P. Morgan on Monday. Morgan is the
first to get the final nod.
   The others with pending applications are Citicorp, Chase
Manhattan Corp., Bankers Trust New York Corp. and Security Pacific
Corp.
   Banks for some time have had the power to buy and sell U.S.
government securities and to underwrite and deal in general
obligation municipal bonds. In January, the Fed ruled that banks
could also underwrite corporate debt provided that the activity did
not generate more than 5 percent of all securities income.
   Corporate debt underwriting within that limit will not violate
the Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act, which separated commercial
from investment banking, the Fed ruled.
   The agency is expected to decide early next year whether banks
can engage in limited underwriting of corporate stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
