<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-NorthwestChronology     06-20 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Northwest Chronology,0300</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of events in the takeover battle for NWA
Inc., parent of Northwest Airlines:
   March 28 _ After months of takeover rumors, NWA Chairman Steven
Rothmeier announces that an unnamed investment group has accumulated
4.9 percent of the company's stock and approached NWA about a
possible acquisition. Rothmeier later identifies the suitor as a
friendly group led by Alfred Checchi of Los Angeles.
   March 30 _ Oil billionaire Marvin Davis offers $2.67 billion, or
$90 a share, to buy NWA.
   April 20 _ Davis launches hostile $70 a share tender offer after
the NWA board rejects his buyout proposal. The board later advises
shareholders not to sell to Davis.
   May 9 _ Pan Am Corp. Chairman Thomas Plaskett announces his
company's interest in acquiring Northwest.
   May 15 _ NWA holds its annual meeting in relative quiet after
Davis drops his threatened proxy fight to gain control of the board
of directors in order to join the formal bidding process outlined by
NWA's board.
   May 30 _ Davis, Checchi, Pan Am, the International Association of
Machinists, and MEI Diversified Inc., run by Minneapolis banker Carl
Pohlad, meet NWA's first deadline for bids.
   June 6 _ NWA rejects all bids, but invites revisions.
   June 16 _ Davis, Checchi, Pan Am and machinists' union confirm
they've met the deadline for revised bids; sources also say New York
investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. submits a proposal.
MEI drops out.
   June 18 _ Checchi's group meets in New York with NWA.
   June 19 _ NWA and Checchi sign a deal at 1 a.m. EDT under which
his group would buy the airline for $121 a share, or about $4
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
