<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time     06-20 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Look to Delaware Court For Key Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speculation is growing that the courts may be the
next key arena in the fight for control of media giant Time Inc.
   Time's stock price fell again Monday following the company's
rejection last week of a $10.7 billion takeover bid by Paramount
Communications Inc. and its announcement of its own $14 billion,
$70-a-share tender offer for Warner Communications Inc.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Time lost $5.62{ a
share to close at $156.87{. It declined $9 a share Friday.
   Warner Communications rose 37{ cents a share to hit $59.62{, and
was the most active NYSE issue. Paramount shares gained $2.37{ a
share to close at $60.50.
   Either deal would create one of the world's largest entertainment
and media concerns, ensuring that an American company would be among
the global communications giants in the 1990s.
   Time and Warner announced in March that they planned to merge in
a stock swap transaction and amended that deal Friday to provide
that Time would offer $70-a-share for half of Warner's 200 million
shares followed by a merger in which Time would pay $70 in cash and
securities for the rest.
   Paramount has vowed to press ahead with its efforts to acquire
Time.
   Securities analysts said they expect Paramount to ask the
Chancery Court in Delaware, where all three companies are
incorporated, for a decision on the legality of the Time offer for
Warner.
   ``The game isn't over yet,'' said Dennis McAlpine, a media
analyst for Oppenheimer &amp; Co. ``Clearly, the court is the next
issue.''
   Analysts expect Paramount will ask the court to determine whether
Time put itself up for sale by agreeing to merge with Warner
initially and whether Time directors acted appropriately by agreeing
to make the cash offer for Warner.
   Time has insisted it has not put itself up for sale, and that the
cash offer for Warner represented a revision of its original merger
plan.
   Paramount has argued that Time has put itself up for sale,
because Time stockholders would have only had about a 40 percent
interest in the merged company under the old plan. As a result,
Paramount is expected to argue that Time should be subject to an
auction _ including any Paramount bid.
   Ken Noble, who follows media stocks for PaineWebber Inc., said
his analysis indicated that stock in the resulting Time-Warner
combination would be valued by the market at about $173 a share.
   But he said the fact that Warner still was trading well below the
$70-a-share offered price ``implies there is still a lot of
speculation about all three stocks and about what will really
happen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
