<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UAWConvention Bjt   06-20 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAW Convention, Bjt,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Strikes Against Dissident Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs lead planned; Convention session starts at 3 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With two strikes against it, a dissident
movement within the United Auto Workers union will try again,
perhaps today, to make itself felt at the union's constitutional
convention.
   The New Directions movement is proposing a resolution that would
limit ``jointness'' in auto plants. The aim is to limit the growing
practice of union and management joining together on a variety of
projects inside and outside factories.
   It's a key issue for the strongest organized dissent in the 1
million member union in 40 years _ since the mid-1930s when Walter
Reuther took the reins of the union.
   If the voting on the ``jointness'' issue goes the way of other
New Directions-backed resolutions, the movement may strike out at
the convention. However, its leader, Jerry Tucker of St. Louis, has
said there is more grass-roots support for the movement than what
shows up at the convention.
   The forces of the Administration Caucus, led by UAW President
Owen Bieber, have easily put out any fires of dissent on the
convention floor. While hard voting figures are not available
because tallies are taken by a show of hands, New Directions hasn't
received support from more than 20 percent of the 2,000 delegates
attending the convention.
   On Monday, New Directions forces were turned back in an attempt
to require rank-and-file elections for the union's top national
officers, including the president, secretary-treasurer and vice
presidents. Currently those offices are filled through voting by the
delegates at constitutional conventions. Bieber is expected to win a
third three-year term in balloting Wednesday.
   Backers of the New Directions movement said a ``one-man,
one-vote'' policy would make the union's leadership more accountable
to the members. Administration Caucus members said nationwide
campaigning would be too time consuming. Besides, they said, the
system seems to be working now.
   But that didn't satisfy Dan Mallett of Local 31 in Fairfax, Kan.
   ``They pay their union dues, they deserve the right to vote,'' he
said from the floor during debate on the issue.
   But Jim McNeil of Local 600 in Dearborn, Mich., reading from the
convention's constitution committee report, said: ``A referendum is
only the outer shell of democracy. The convention system delivers
the substance.''
   The effort was defeated on a show-of-hands vote.
   On Sunday, the first day of the week-long convention, delegates
turned aside another New Directions move challenging the seating of
several local delegations from regions covering eight south-central
states and parts of metropolitan Detroit.
   Also Monday, delegates heard a campaign-style speech by U.S. Rep.
Richard Gephardt, an unsuccessful candidate for the 1988 Democratic
presidential nomination. Gephardt, in his first major speech since
being elected majority leader of the House of Representatives two
weeks ago, sounded themes similar to ones he and others raised
during last year's campaign.
   As he did during the campaign, he focused on the nation's trade
deficit, saying the Bush administration has ``made some good sounds
on trade.''
   ``It remains to be seen if they are tough,'' he added. ``If not,
we're going to have the Gephardt amendment or something like it.''
   The congressman from Missouri based a large part of his
unsuccessful presidential campaign last year on trade issues. The
legislation he proposed would have forced the president to take
action against countries that traded unfairly with the United States.
   ``You cannot compete against unfair competition,'' he said.
   Gephardt also criticized the Bush administration, saying the
nation needed to develop a comprehensive energy policy and to divert
spending from military hardware to education and the fight against
drugs.
   ``This is our time ... to make America great and good and strong
again,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
