<DOCNO> AP890620-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DiaperChanges Bjt   06-20 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Diaper Changes, Bjt,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>P&amp;G Looking For Ways Of Disposing Disposable Diapers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New conference scheduled for 10 a.m. EDT; will be led. Also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest maker of disposable
diapers said today it will begin searching for ways to transform
billions of dirty didies from an ecological problem into recycled
flower pots, building insulation and lush highway medians.
   Procter &amp; Gamble Co. announced it is backing research to see if
dirty disposable diapers can be cleaned and their components
recycled. The cost of the program was not immediately available.
   In a statement issued prior to today's scheduled news conference
at Washington's National Press Club, Bob Greene, P&amp;G's associate
director of research, said the company hoped to find ways of
handling ``disposable diapers and other materials in municipal solid
waste in ways that can bypass landfill disposal and recover valuable
resources.''
   The research, to be done in Minnesota, Wisconsin, Washington,
Florida and other states, comes as public concern is growing over
the 16 billion disposable diapers dumped annually in the nation's
overflowing landfills.
   While not the biggest component in the U.S. garbage pile _ waste
paper, bottles and cans are bigger contributors _ diapers cannot be
recycled like other trash.
   Environmentalists have warned that the plastic-coated disposable
diapers do not decompose, making their contents potential breeding
grounds for dangerous viruses and bacteria that cause polio,
hepatitis, meningitis and other diseases.
   As a result, lawmakers in Nebraska have banned the sale of
non-biodegradable diapers by 1993 and legislators in Iowa,
Washington and Oregon have considered similar action.
   The P&amp;G announcement detailed three separate projects. The first,
in cooperation with Seattle's Solid Waste Utility and Rabanco Co. of
Seattle, will collect used diapers from 1,000 households, wash and
sanitize them, then separate them into plastic and pulp.
   The plastic will be recycled into flower pots, garbage bags and
ersatz lumber used for landscaping. The pulp will be made into
cardboard boxes, building insulation and wallboard liner.
   ``Our aim is not to get into the diaper recycling business,''
project director Nancy Eddy said. ``Rather, we want to demonstrate
that the technology is feasible and encourage entrepreneurs to get
involved in this business.''
   In another project with the recycling firm Recomp Inc. of St.
Cloud, Minn., diapers will be put through a process that churns
garbage into a soil used to reclaim salt-tainted lands along
highways.
   The diaper giant also will finance research at the University of
Wisconsin that, over the next five years, will bury and exhume
regular and biodegradable disposable diapers at landfill sites in
Wisconsin, Florida and the Northeast.
   This landfill archeology will see if products touted as
biodegradable actually decompose any faster than the regular
disposable diapers made by P&amp;G.
   The stakes are high. P&amp;G owns a majority portion of the $3.5
billion disposable diaper industry. But that market share is being
threatened by a growing environmental awareness and aggressive
marketing by biodegradable diaper manufacturers and cloth diaper
services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0726EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     06-20 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major foreign
currencies in early European trading today. Gold prices were little
changed.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's short-term trend is downward
as a result of confusion created by last week's selloff. But they
said the outlook for the longer term remains bullish as there's
still underlying demand for dollars.
   One trader in Rome said the dollar-yen exchange rate has remained
surprisingly stable because of continued strong demand for dollars
out of the Far East, adding to the market's general confusion.
   He predicted that the dollar's downward correction could last one
week, before bullish sentiments would take the upper hand again.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.70 yen to a closing 143.80 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 143.63 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.9708 West German marks, down from 1.9735; 1.7047
Swiss francs, up from 1.7045; 6.6810 French francs, down from
6.6940; 2.2205 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2351; 1,427.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,439.75; and 1.1985 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1991.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5575 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5485 late Monday.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price for
gold of $366.50 an ounce at midmorning, unchanged from late Monday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $366.50 compared with $366.25 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 93 cents to close at a bid
$367.70.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.35 a troy ounce,
down from Monday's $5.37.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 0728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-20 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Tumbles, Japanese Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply against the Japaense yen
today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rebounded.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 220.29 points, or 0.67
percent, finishing at 33,233.47.
   The dollar closed at 143.80 yen, down 1.70 yen from Monday's
145.50-yen finish. It opened at 143.75 yen and moved between 143.25
yen and 144.00 yen.
   Traders said most investors were adjusting their dollar holdings,
mainly because of uncertainties over the direction of the dollar-yen
rate after large swings last week.
   The dollar closed Thursday at 151.30 yen, its highest in almost
two years, and then fell 6.25 yen the next day.
   Yoshitsugu Hanada, a Mitsui Bank trader, said investors were
buying dollars at the 143-yen level, while Japanese trading houses
were selling as the dollar approached 144 yen.
   ``In mixed trading, the dollar has been gradually falling,''
Hamada said, adding that most investors no longer are looking for an
abrupt rise against the yen. But this does not mean bullishness
about the dollar has been totally reversed, he said.
   ``Now is the adjustment phase after the dollar's rapid rise to
the 151-yen level last week,'' said Hamada.
   The Bank of Japan reportedly was selling dollars to support the
yen, but the amount was not known. The central bank does not comment
on its foreign exchange activities.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the yen's surge against the
dollar reassured Japanese investors, encouraging stock purchases.
   Nomura Securities analyst Masahiro Umemori said, ``The market
rebounded by itself mainly because of recent stability in foreign
exchange.''
   ``It's too early to say the strong yen is back, but the foreign
exchange's stability was at least good news for stock trading,'' he
said, noting that the index had fallen more than 1,100 points last
week because of the dollar's sharp rise against the yen.
   Trading, however, was still inactive due to lingering
uncertainties over currency movements, Umemori said.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 700 million shares,
up from 450 million the previous day.
   Among gainers were electricals including Sony and Sharp, as well
as steel and shipbuilding issuees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
