<HEAD>London Shares Higher At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were firmer but below their intraday
peaks at midday Tuesday after new British money supply data for May
showed a higher-than-expected rise in bank and building society
lending.
   Dealers said prices were still underpinned by some moderate
futures-related buying and a general shortage of stock, which tended
to push prices higher.
   The market also drew comfort from another steady performance by
sterling, easing earlier fears that base lending rates would have to
be lifted above the current 14 percent level to defend the currency,
dealers said.
   Lending by banks and building societies rose by 6.7 billion
pounds, or $10.4 billion, in May, higher than market expectations of
around 5.9 billion pounds.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 16.4
points, or 0.7 percent, at 2,171.1 at midday.
   Volume was a moderate 321.5 million shares compared with 214.0
million shares at the same time Monday.
