<HEAD>Societe Generale Offering 11 Percent of Stock to Public</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sodinvest SA will sell its nearly 11
percent stake in Societe Generale de Belgique next week, boosting
the public's share in Belgium's top holding company to 13 percent,
officials said Tuesday.
   The offer for the 7 million shares will be officially launched
Monday.
   Sodinvest is an investment concern jointly owned by Group AG of
Belgium and Compagnie Financiere de Suez of France, who effectively
control Societe Generale.
   The public currently has a 2 percent share of Societe Generale.
Most of Societe Generale's shares were bought by institutions after
Italian financier Carlo De Benedetti launched a hostile takeover bid
for the company in January 1988.
   That battle left Suez and its allies with a 50.5 percent
controlling stake. An alliance of Belgian and Luxembourg companies
led by Group AG holds 16 percent, while Cerus SA, De Benedetti's
investment concern, holds 15 percent. Another 5 percent stake is
held by an anonymous investor.
