<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-LotusSoftware 1stLd-Writethru   06-20 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lotus Software, 1st Ld-Writethru,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lotus Ready To Ship Long Delayed Spreadsheet Software</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede CAMBRIDGE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with announcement at annual meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 18 months of delays, Lotus Development Corp.
said today it has begun shipping its Release 3, an improved version
of the best-selling 1-2-3 computer software.
   Jim P. Manzi, the company's 37-year-old chairman, made the
announcement at Lotus' annual meeting in Boston.
   With the embarrassing delays last year, ``Lotus and Release 3 had
become the moral equivalent of the Boston Red Sox in the World
Series,'' Manzi said.
   ``We have come through a very tough period, and I believe we have
proved our mettle,'' he said.
   A key feature of the new software is the ability to display data
in three dimensions.
   Other computer spreadsheets show information along two axes,
allowing, for example, a store manager who wants to analyze his
seasonal sales pattern to put products along one axis and time
periods along the other.
   If he has several stores, however, the manager faces an
additional headache. With Release 3, he can cure it by creating a
third axis, representing various stores or geographic regions.
   After three years and tens of millions of dollars in development
costs, Lotus is betting that 3-D software, unlike movies, will turn
out to be more than a quick fad. Not everyone is sure.
   ``I think three dimensionality is a desirable function for a
certain percentage of the market, but what percentage, I don't
know,'' said Richard Sherlund, an analyst for Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co.
in New York. ``Not everyone needs it.''
   Lotus, founded in 1982, has grown from a handful of employees to
more than 2,600 worldwide on the strength of 1-2-3, its original
product and still the source of nearly two-thirds of its sales,
which are projected at more than $500 million this year.
   But to keep ahead of competitors like Microsoft Corp. of Redmond,
Wash., and Borland International Corp. of Scotts Valley, Calif.,
Lotus has had to continually upgrade the program's features.
   For the top-secret Release 3 project, which Lotus code named
``Godiva,'' the firm three years ago assembled a small team of
engineers that quickly grew to more than 100 people. A confident
Manzi announced in April 1987 that Release 3 would be out in early
1988.
   But design and management problems, about which the company has
said little, intervened.
   Lotus said in February 1988 that Release 3 would not be ready
until late in the second quarter of 1988. A month later, the target
date was pushed back to the fourth quarter. Then, last October, the
company announced a further delay, until the second quarter of 1989.
   With its repeated failure to meet its own deadlines, Lotus'
earnings and stock price plunged, and its competitors picked up
market share.
   Manzi, a former management consultant who had taken over from
Lotus founder Mitch Kapor in 1986, was stung by intensely personal
negative publicity. Charles Digate, the executive in charge of
spreadsheets, resigned.
   Industry wags said the company was pioneering a new class of
products called ``vaporware'' _ software that disappears every time
it is about to be introduced.
   But Lotus apparently turned the corner last year when it brought
in W. Frank King, a former IBM manager, to head up the project. He
injected discipline into the project team and got Release 3 into
field test in February.
   As a result, Lotus stock has largely recovered, trading recently
at around $26 a share, close to its 52-week high of $26.75 and far
above its low for the year of $14.75.
   Competitors are still close on the firm's heels, with Microsoft
steadily enhancing its Excel software, the No. 2 spreadsheet on the
market, and Borland reportedly working on a 3-D version of its
Quattro program.
   At Lotus' annual meeting today in the Berklee Performance Center
attended by more than 400 people, the company showed a wide-screen
television transmission from its manufacturing center in Cambridge
with boxes of Release 3 rolling off an assembly line and being
packed for shipment to customers across the country.
   The delays have ``cost them a lot of clout in the market and
tarnished their reputation,'' Sherlund said in advance of the
announcement. ``Now it's their time to shine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-HBJ-ThemeParks     06-20 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HBJ-Theme Parks,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Selling Theme Parks in Four States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc. announced
today it will sell its Sea World theme parks in four states and two
other Florida attractions to help retire the huge debt it incurred
in fighting off a 1987 hostile takeover attempt.
   The sale of the Sea World marine parks in Florida, Texas, Ohio
and California and Boardwalk &amp; Baseball and Cypress Gardens in
Central Florida is the only way HBJ ``can substantially reduce the
company's obligations'' and make the necessary investments in its
publishing and insurance divisions, a company statement said.
   In midmorning trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Harcourt
rose $3 a share to $13.12{ after the disclosure.
   The decision came about after recent talks between HBJ's
chairman, William Jovanovich, and its new president, Ralph D. Caulo,
according to the announcement.
   The statement said Caulo ``is prepared to leave HBJ in order to
manage these businesses under new ownership.''
   The brief announcement made no mention of a possible buyer for
the six parks, and a tract of land next to Orlando International
Airport.
   ``The HBJ directors have authorized this sale, which is subject
to the approval of HBJ's lenders,'' the statement said. ``Mr.
Jovanovich and Mr. Caulo have agreed that Mr. Caulo will direct the
sale of these assets, whether made to a corporation or to a
syndicate of investors.''
   There was no further comment from the company. Jovanovich was
unreachable for comment and Caulo did not immediately return
telephone calls to his office.
   HBJ, a Fortune 500 company and the nation's largest textbook
publisher, fought a hostile takeover by British publisher Robert
Maxwell in 1987 by adopting a costly defense known as a
recapitalization.
   It financed the plan by borrowing from banks and selling
so-called junk bonds, ballooning its debt to $2.9 billion.
   HBJ lost $126.5 million, or $2.04 a share, last year compared
with a 1987 profit of $64.4 million, or $1.34 a share. The loss came
despite increased sales of 17 percent, to a record $1.78 billion,
over 1987.
   The improved sales were caused by strong demand for HBJ's
textbooks and insurance policies, plus the opening of its new Sea
World theme park near San Antonio, Tex., according to analysts.
   During its first quarter, HBJ reported larger-than-usual losses
in its publishing division. It lost $46.2 million in the first three
months of the year, or nearly $19 million more than in the same
period a year earlier.
   The company recently underwent a reshuffling of that division,
relocating sales and marketing personnel and eliminating some 200
jobs.
</TEXT>
