<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rolls-Royce PLC announced Tuesday that Trans World
Airlines has chosen its most powerful long-haul engine to power
recently-ordered Airbus A-330 airliners in a deal worth over $620
million.
   TWA has agreed to buy 20 of the A-330 twin-engined aircraft along
with an option for 20 additional aircraft, making it the largest
A-330 order to date, worth up to $4 billion.
   TWA is scheduled to take delivery of the planes in late 1994. The
contract between TWA and Airbus, a European aircraft-building
consortium, was signed Tuesday.
   The aircraft-engine combination will likely be used on longer
A-330 operations over the Atlantic, Rolls-Royce said.
   TWA is the third airline to specify the RB211-524L engine for its
aircraft since its launch last year.
