<FIRST>r f AM-BPRefinery     06-20 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BP Refinery,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>BP Plans To Upgrade Refinery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OREGON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A subsidiary of British Petroleum America
Inc. will spend $102 million for improvements to a 31-year-old
refinery in this Toledo suburb, a company official said Tuesday.
   The project is intended to reduce operating costs, improve air
quality and reinforce the refinery's competitive position, said
Clare Tyler, manager of BP Oil Co.'s Oregon refinery. It involves
replacing four refining operations with one unit.
   No increase in employment is expected, Tyler said. The refinery
employs 470 people. Construction is to begin after Oct. 1, and
should be complete by the end of 1991.
   Eric Schwamberger, vice president of Local 7-346 of the Oil,
Chemical &amp; Atomic Workers International Union, said BP's plans could
improve the union's relations with the company.
   ``If BP is willing to sink this kind of money into this project,
it should translate into job security,'' Schwamberger said.
   The former Standard Oil refinery has been the site of at least
three bitter strikes since 1975, including a four-month strike in
early 1988 when the company tried to reduce wages and beneifts.
</TEXT>
