<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Dip On Wetter Outlook, Technicals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices dropped
substantially Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as wetter
weather forecasts for the Corn Belt took the edge off drought fears.
Wheat futures also retreated.
   The corn and soybean markets lost about half of the ground they
gained Monday, when the Midwest looked to be due for an extended
spell of hot, dry weather.
   Tuesday's forecasts predicted rain in the northern and western
reaches of the Corn Belt by the end of this week, and selling
pressure was strong from the opening bell.
   Analysts also cited technical resistance to a further advance
after Monday's strong rally, which followed four days of gains in
the corn and soybean pits.
   ``The market needs to test support and find out that it's solid
before it tries to move up again,'' said William Biedermann,
director of research at Allendale Inc., a futures brokerage in
Crystal Lake, Ill.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 2 cents lower with July at
$3.95{ a bushel; corn was 2} cents to 5{ cents lower with July at
$2.67 a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 4 cents lower with July at
$1.68\ a bushel; soybeans were 8 cents to 12{ cents lower with July
at $7.36 a bushel.
