after hovering in a narrow range through most of the trading session.
   The market ``is fatigued if not exhausted,'' said Michael Metz,
an analyst for Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   ``I think we've entered the summer doldrums early,'' he said,
referring to Wall Street's customary summer slowdown that usually
starts in early July.
