<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-20 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Oil Plunges; Refined Products Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil prices plunged more than $1 a barrel in
thin trading Tuesday while other petroleum products ended mixed.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, finished $1.33
lower at $19.53 a barrel, after gaining 91 cents on Monday. Other
contract months were mixed.
   Peter Beutel, an energy analyst with Elders Futures Inc.,
attributed the sell-off in crude to the fact that the near-month
contract was set to expire on Tuesday.
   He noted that prices started out sharply higher, with the July
contract up as much as $21.30 a barrel, but that they plunged later
in the session as demand fizzled.
   ``There really were no fundamental reasons'' for the decline,
Beutel said.
   The drop in crude helped pull down heating oil. The July contract
for wholesale No. 2 heating oil slipped 0.37 cent to 45.69 cents a
gallon, after settling 0.86 cent higher on Monday.
   Among other refined petroleum products, unleaded gasoline for
July delivery rose 0.17 cent to 59.17 cents a gallon. The contract
was up 0.86 cent the previous session.
</TEXT>
