<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1747EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-LotusSoftware     06-20 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lotus Software,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lotus Ships Long-Awaited Release 3 Spreadsheet Software</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After an 18-month delay that drove down its stock
and depressed its earnings, Lotus Development Corp. said Tuesday it
has begun shipping an improved version of its best-selling 1-2-3
computer software.
   More than 400 stockholders burst into cheers at Lotus' annual
meeting as a live video hookup showed boxes of the long-awaited
spreadsheet program, named Release 3, rolling off an assembly line
at the company's Cambridge manufacturing center.
   With that triumph behind him, Jim Manzi, Lotus' 37-year-old
chairman, was able to talk about the embarrassing delays with humor.
   ``Lotus and Release 3 had become the moral equivalent of the
Boston Red Sox in the World Series,'' he said. ``... We have come
through a very tough period, and I believe we have proved our
mettle.''
   Teresa Lotzgesell, an analyst with the Seattle brokerage house of
Ragen Mackenzie, said the delay in producing Release 3 was a boon to
competitors like Microsoft Corp. of Redmond, Wash., and Borland
International Corp. of Scotts Valley, Calif.
   Lotus, founded in 1982, once had a near lock on the $600
million-a-year market for computer spreadsheets. Now, Microsoft's
Excel program has about 12 percent of the market, Borland's Quattro
has between 5 and 10 percent, and various other programs have about
10 percent, Lotzgesell said.
   ``Wih people waiting and waiting and waiting (for Release 3),
Lotus did lose customers,'' she said. ``Now they may win some back.''
   Release 3 originally was due out in early 1988. When Lotus
delayed its arrival three times, reportedly because of problems
transferring the basic machine code into the computer language
``C,'' many analysts cut their 1989 earnings projections by 20
percent or more.
   Lotus stock also plunged, although it has since bounced back to
about $26 a share from a 52-week low of $14.75.
   Now, said analyst Richard Sherlund of Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. in New
York, the question is whether Release 3 can recapture the momentum
for Lotus, which has 2,600 employees and reported sales of $468.5
million last year.
   One of the key advantages of Release 3 is the ability to display
data in three dimensions, showing a row of up to 256 spreadsheets.
But that ability makes the program something of a memory hog; to run
it efficiently, a computer must have the latest generation of Intel
286 or 386 microchips and more than 1 megabyte of random access
memory.
   Release 2.2, a version for less powerful, IBM XT- and
PC-compatible machines, is due out later this year. Other versions,
including one rich in graphics and one for Apple Macintosh
computers, also are planned.
   Manzi, who took over from Lotus founder Mitchell D. Kapor in
1986, endured harsh criticism for the company's delays and for his
compensation, which totaled more than $26 million in 1987. But on
Tuesday, he was clearly enjoying himself.
   Thanking the team of more than 100 engineers and programmers who
produced Release 3, he told stockholders that ``These people have
shown unbelievable dedication, unbelievable skill, and an equally
unbelievable ability to eat cold pizza late at night.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
