<FIRST>r f AM-Population-Youth     06-20 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Population-Youth,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Survey Says Shrinking Youth Population Changing Consumer Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decline in America's young adult population
will be accompanied by a rise in average household income so the age
group's buying power will hold steady, a research group said Tuesday.
   The Conference Board said the pool of young people will shrink
significantly as the 20th century comes to a close due to a slowdown
in the birth rate that began in the 1960s.
   The number of people between the ages of 20 and 35 will fall by
about 10 million during the next 15 years from about 63 million in
1985, forecasts say.
   Fabian Linden, executive director of the Conference Board's
consumer research center, said over the past decade and a half young
people have been the biggest growth segment of the U.S. consumer
market.
   ``But in the years ahead they will hold considerably less promise
for marketers of a wide variety of products and services,'' Linden
said.
   He estimated that currently one out of every four dollars of
total household income flows to homes headed by persons under 35
years old. The amount is expected to fall to less than one dollar
out of every five by the year 2000.
   However, the real buying power of this age group isn't expected
to contract.
   ``The increase in average household earnings over the next decade
will offset the decline in the number of households,'' Linden said.
``Additionally, because there will be fewer available American
workers between the ages of 20 and 35, they will likely receive
higher pay.''
   The Conference Board is a nonprofit research-oriented group
supported by businesses, trade and professional organizations,
government agencies, unions and others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
