<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-20 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher in U.S. Trading; Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained against major foreign
currencies in domestic dealings Tuesday after a mixed performance
abroad.
   Gold prices posted minor changes. Republic National Bank of New
York quoted a bid of $365 for a troy ounce of gold at 4 p.m. EDT, $1
lower than Monday's late bid.
   New York-based currency dealers said the dollar closed at the
high end of the range within which it has traded recently.
   ``Basically, it was a reasonably quiet day but the dollar did
move well in its range,'' said Samuel Lek, a managing director in
the foreign exchange department of Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.
   Lek said there was no fundamental reason for the dollar's gain.
Dealers probably decided the time was right to increase their dollar
holdings after lightening them in recent days, he said.
   Lately when the dollar has staged a strong advance, central banks
have stepped into the market to knock it down by selling dollars.
Lek said there may have been a modest amount of intervention on
Tuesday.
   The dollar began its trading day in Tokyo by losing ground. The
dollar closed there at 143.80 Japanese yen, down from 145.50. In
London, the dollar headed slightly higher, to 143.85 yen. It climbed
further to 144.90 yen in later New York trading, up from 144.60
Monday.
   Reports of dollar sales by the Bank of Japan contributed to a
mixed showing for the dollar in European trading.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5553 late Tuesday, up from
Monday's late bid of $1.5485. Later, sterling fetched $1.5405 in New
York, down from $1.5430 on Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Monday's
rates, included: 1.9870 West German marks, up from 1.9785; 1.7205
Swiss francs, up from 1.7090; 1.19875 Canadian dollars, up from
1.19865; 6.7315 French francs, up from 6.7155; and 1,440.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,431.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Monday's levels were:
1.9775 West German marks, up from 1.9735; 1.7110 Swiss francs, up
from 1.7045; 6.7025 French francs, up from 6.6940; 2.2255 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.2351; 1,431.75 Italian lire, down from
1.439.75; and 1.2000 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1991.
   Gold bullion prices finished unchanged to slightly lower.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $366.30 a troy ounce, down from $367.10. Gold
closed in London at a bid of $366.50 an ounce, unchanged from late
Monday. The late bid price in Zurich was $366.00 an ounce, down from
$366.25.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $366.95 an ounce, up from
$366.25.
   Silver prices declined a bit. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery fell to $5.234 a troy ounce from Monday's
settlement of $5.323. Silver bullion traded in London at $5.34 a
troy ounce, down from $5.37.
</TEXT>
