<DOCNO> AP890620-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Princeton-Newport 1stLd-Writethru   06-20 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Princeton-Newport, 1st Ld-Writethru,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government: Racketeering Defendants Made Illegal Trades Like a Yo-Yo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 21 grafs to RECAST lead, UPDATE throughout with defense
lawyers opening statements, more prosecution arguments, CORRECT yo-yo quote;
PICKS UP 13th graf pvs, `Much of...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government prosecutor charged Tuesday that
officials of Princeton-Newport Partners LP and Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. illegally bought and sold stocks in a widespread tax
fraud scheme amounting to ``plain, old-fashioned cheating.''
   In opening arguments in the first racketeering case ever
involving securities trading, Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Hansen
said the six defendants engaged in a ``very simple criminal scheme''
between 1984 and 1986 to generate phony tax losses.
   He also said prosecutors would play incriminating tapes in court,
one of which includes a Drexel trader telling a Princeton-Newport
partner, ``Welcome to the world of being a sleaze.''
   ``This is a case about cheating,'' Hansen said in a packed
courtroom at U.S. District Court in Manhattan. ``These defendants
are wealthy, successful men, men who decided they were above the
law, who decided they could break the law without being caught.''
   On trial are five officials of the defunct investment partnership
and former Drexel trader Bruce Lee Newberg. The case overlaps the
government's indictment of former Drexel financier Michael Milken.
Neither of the firms is on trial.
   Hansen alleged that Drexel via Newberg purchased stocks from
Princeton-Newport, then sold them back a short time later to create
bogus losses that Princeton-Newport declared as tax deductions. The
indictment in the case, handed up last August, alleged $13 million
in bogus tax losses.
   Moving his left hand up and down, Hansen equated the alleged
illegal trades with the motion of a yo-yo.
   ``These sales were on a string,'' he said. ``When the
Princeton-Newport defendants sent those securities out, they sent
them out waiting for the moment when they could bring them back with
a little tug of the hand.''
   ``When Princeton-Newport defendants went to the government and
took that tax deduction, that was a fraud,'' Hansen added.
   But Theodore Wells, attorney for Princeton-Newport managing
partner James Sutton Regan, said the tax trades were ``appropriate,
proper and lawful'' and made in response to changes in federal tax
laws in June 1984.
   ``Each loss involved in this case is a real loss,'' he said.
   In another alleged scheme, Hansen claimed Newberg, with the help
of the Princeton-Newport defendants, illegally drove down the stock
price of C.O.M.B. Co. in 1985 before a Drexel offering of $25
million in bonds to the Minneapolis-based merchandiser. Hansen did
not explain the motivation for the alleged scheme.
   Hansen also told the jury of nine women and three men that the
alleged bogus stock ``parking'' trades also involved Merrill Lynch &
Co. and Akroyd &amp; Smithers Securities. Those two firms cooperated
with the government. They were not charged.
   In an illegal ``parking'' deal, one party agrees to purchase a
block of stock under an agreement to sell it back at a prearranged
time and price, usually to skirt federal tax or stock ownership
disclosure laws.
   In addition to Newberg and Regan, on trial are Jack Z.
Rabinowitz, Charles M. Zarzecki and Paul A. Berkman, all partners in
the investment firm; and Steven B. Smotorick, Princeton-Newport's
comptroller.
   Hansen said prosecutors would play tapes of conversations between
Newberg and Princeton-Newport employees discussing the alleged
illegal deals. The tapes, made as part of normal Princeton-Newport
business activities, were seized during a raid on the firm's
headquarters in December 1987.
   Hansen said one tape contains Newberg telling Zarzecki after the
latter made a C.O.M.B transaction in April 1985: ``You're a
sleaze-bag.''
   ``You taught me, man,'' Zarzecki is said to reply on the tape.
   ``Welcome to the world of being a sleaze,'' Newberg said,
according to Hansen.
   Much of the evidence in the Princeton-Newport case also is
expected to be used against Milken, the former head of Drexel's junk
bond department, who was charged in March in a separate 98-count
racketeering indictment. Newberg also is charged in that case.
   The charges against Milken include dealings he allegedly had with
Princeton-Newport, which was based in Princeton, N.J., and Newport
Beach, Calif., and went out of business shortly after its officials
were indicted last August.
   Hansen conceded that none of the defendants made any money in the
alleged illegal deals, but attributed that to accountants' errors.
He said that fact did not exonerate the men.
   The Princeton-Newport trial is the first in which the
racketeering statute, which carries heavy sentences, fines and
forfeiture of alleged illicit profits upon conviction, has been used
against officials of a securities firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
