<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 1824EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HollyFarms Bjt   06-20 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms, Bjt,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tyson Increases Bid For Holly Farms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc., the nation's largest
poultry processor, pressed its attempt Tuesday to take over Holly
Farms Corp. by raising a tender offer for Holly stock to $70 a
share, a bid worth more than $1.2 billion.
   Tyson of Springdale, Ark., has been trying to take over Holly
Farms since last October, and the Memphis-based Holly has been
struggling since November to merge with ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb.
   ``We are delighted that Tyson has now decided to raise its bid,''
Holly Farms lawyer Kenneth Nachbar said in a letter to the Delaware
Chancery Court that has refereed the Tyson-Holly-ConAgra squabble.
   ``We do expect the Holly Farms board to meet within the next five
business days to consider the proposal,'' Nachbar said.
   Holly urged its 5,500 shareholders to hold on to their 18.1
million shares until the company's board meets to review the latest
Tyson bid.
   In raising its tender offer from $63.50, Tyson also said its new
bid was no longer conditioned on removal of an asset sales agreement
established late last year between Holly and ConAgra.
   That agreement is at the heart of a legal fight launched by Tyson.
   The latest merger proposal for ConAgra and Holly Farms was
announced May 20 and is based on a stock swap, while Tyson's bid is
for cash.
   Holly and ConAgra expect to call shareholder votes next month on
their proposed merger. When the proposal was announced, Holly said
it was worth $74 a share based on market prices at the time. The
Delaware court has been told, however, that the offer likely would
be worth around $68 a share by the time the agreement could be
settled.
   In addition to raising its offer, Tyson also filed a court
petition Tuesday seeking to force Holly to dissolve a shareholder
rights plan containing a ``poison pill'' aimed at making a takeover
more costly for an aggressor.
   Vice Chancellor Maurice Hartnett rejected a similar Tyson attack
on that plan June 14 while clearing the way for shareholder votes on
the proposed merger.
   The shareholder rights plan, adopted in October, would give Holly
stockholders a price break on additional shares in the event of a
takeover.
   The battle for Holly Farms began last year when Tyson offered a
deal valued at $49.50 a share through a cash and stock swap.
   Holly managers rejected that offer as insufficient and have
pointed out several times during the ensuing takeover attempt that
their resistance has raised the amount of money their stockholders
will make if the company is sold.
   ConAgra's original merger offer called for swapping 1.875 shares
of ConAgra stock for each Holly Farms share traded. The current
proposal calls for a swap of 2.1 shares.
   Tyson Foods processes 16.5 million chickens a week and has
announced expansion plans to push that to 17.5 million by the end of
next month.
   Holly Farms is a diversified company heavily involved in fresh
chicken sales. ConAgra is a diversified company specializing in food
and agricultural services.
</TEXT>
