<FIRST>u f AM-HBJ-ThemeParks 1stLd-Writethru   06-20 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HBJ-Theme Parks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publisher Will Sell 6 Family Parks in 4 States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 11-13, It added ..., with comment from HBJ; picks
up 14th graf, Among the ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc. put its four
Sea World parks and two other attractions on the market Tuesday to
help extricate itself from a $2.5 billion debt brought on by a 1987
hostile takeover attempt.
   The company said selling the marine parks in Florida, Texas, Ohio
and California and Boardwalk &amp; Baseball and Cypress Gardens in
central Florida was the best way to meet debt obligations and
concentrate on its publishing and insurance divisions.
   Estimates of the value of the properties ranged from $1 billion
to $2.5 billion.
   Wall Street applauded the move. HBJ's stock closed up $3.75 a
share Tuesday to $13.87{ in active trading on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   ``It's a positive development for the company because of its weak
balance sheet,'' said Robert Dunlap, a securities analyst with Brown
Brothers Harriman &amp; Co. in New York. ``Clearly, something had to be
done.''
   Elizabeth Bramwell, of the New York firm Gabelli &amp; Co., said HBJ
``shouldn't have been doing all these (other) things. The first love
of this company is publishing.''
   HBJ, the nation's largest textbook publisher, has struggled with
a $2.9 billion recapitalization program over the past two years by
disposing of trade-magazine and school-supply interests,
streamlining its parks division and reshuffling its publishing
operations _ all of which included huge reductions in personnel.
   HBJ restructured its operations, through bank loans and high-risk
junk bonds, to fend off a hostile takeover attempt by British
publisher Robert Maxwell in 1987.
   The decision to sell the theme parks and real estate holdings
followed recent talks between HBJ's longtime chairman, William
Jovanovich, and the company's new president, Ralph D. Caulo,
according to a three-paragraph statement by HBJ.
   ``The HBJ directors have authorized this sale, which is subject
to the approval of HBJ's lenders,'' the announcement said.
   It added that Caulo ``is prepared to leave HBJ in order to manage
these businesses under new ownership.''
   The parks will be sold as a package to an investor that ``wants
to invest in them and continue to see them grow,'' Bob Evanson, head
of the theme parks division, said in an interview.
   Evanson said the company had spoken to ``quite a few'' potential
buyers of the parks, which brought in an estimated $388 million in
revenue last year, and a separate tract of land near Orlando
International Airport.
   Among the possible buyers mentioned by analysts, however, were:
Anheuser-Busch Cos., which owns Busch Gardens in Tampa; British
entertainment magnate Robert Earl, who has restaurant and nightclub
properties in the area; Paramount Studios, which reportedly is
interested in Boardwalk &amp; Baseball; and the prosperous Walt Disney
Co., which just opened its third theme park in the Orlando area.
   HBJ's trade-magazine and school-supply operations were sold to
Edgell Communications Inc. for $334 million in late 1987. That was
the beginning of the effort to repay some of the debt associated
with the costly takeover defense.
   HBJ lost $126.5 million last year compared with a 1987 profit of
$64.4 million, or $1.34 a share.
   The company paid about $313 million in interest last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
