<FIRST>u f AM-Time-Warner-FCC     06-20 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-Warner-FCC,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount, Warner Trade Charges in Time Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Longer version on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc., pursuing Time
Inc. with a a $10.7 billion takeover bid, has asked federal
regulators to set aside rulings allowing Time to transfer control of
its cable TV systems to the company Time wants to create by buying
Warner Communications Inc.
   Lawyers for Warner, meanwhile, argued that Paramount's plans for
creating a voting trust to take temporary custody of Time stock
violates cable laws that give local authorities the right to approve
transfers of cable licenses.
   The filings at the Federal Communications Commission were the
latest round in the manueverings over whether Paramount can acquire
Time or whether Time buys Warner in deals that would create the
world's largest entertainment and media conglomerate.
   Lawyers for Paramount said in documents filed with the FCC that
Time had misrepresented to Time stockholders the nature of the
transfer of control.
   Paramount also said Time had written to state attorneys general
asking them to oppose Paramount's proposal without notifying
Paramount of the letters.
   These actions ``raise substantial and material questions about
Time's character qualifications,'' Paramount said in asking the FCC
to set aside its previous approval of the license transfers pending
an FCC investigation.
   Time and Warner announced in March they had agreed to merge in a
stock swap, and proceeded to secure appropriate regulatory
clearances.
   Paramount launched its hostile bid for Time on June 6, just 17
days before Time and Warner shareholders were to have voted on the
merger.
   Time rejected Paramount's offer and revised its merger agreement
with Warner to call for a $14 billion tender offer for Warner.
   The battle is expected to be waged in court in Delaware, where
all three companies are incorporated.
   Paramount earlier this month asked the FCC for permission to
deposit any Time shares it may acquire in a voting trust that would
be headed by former Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld pending FCC
approval of the transfer of 99 cable television franchises and
licenses held by Time's 82-percent-owned subsidiary, American
Television and Communications Corp.
   Art Harding, an attorney for Warner in Washington, said Tuesday
that Paramount's request ``would violate the recent cable act
because Rumsfeld hasn't gotten consent from any of these cities for
the transfers.''
   Harding, echoing assertions Time made in a June 13 filing with
the FCC, said Paramount's plan would ``undermine the delicate
balance'' established in the 1984 Cable Act for regulation of cable
systems by local authorities.
   Warner asked the FCC late Monday to deny the application made by
Paramount for expedited consent for the trust arrangement for
temporary custody of any Time shares that Paramount acquires.
   Warner said Paramount's plan called for an ``unprecedented
extension'' to the cable TV industry of FCC rules that cover hostile
tender offers for broadcast licenses.
   ``Such an extension of the FCC tender offer policy would
emasculate the significant role in cable franchising mandated for
local authorities by the Cable Communications Policy Act of 1984,''
Warner said.
   Warner also said, among other things, that Paramount's plan was
faulty because Rumsfeld was being paid $250,000 and thus was not an
independent trustee; that a voting trust was invalid because Time's
cable systems were affiliated with Paramount's Madison Square Garden
and USA networks; and that Paramount might end up owning TV and
cable systems in the same region in violation of federal
cross-ownership regulations.
   ``Paramount's so-called tender offer is so riddled with
conditions, loopholes and escape hatches as to be essentially
illusory,'' Warner said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
