<SECOND>BC-TV-Ad Boycott,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Religious Group Plans to Announce Advertiser Boycott Plans July 17</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A religious group that plans to target one or
more advertisers for a boycott based on the television shows the
companies sponsor said Tuesday they plan to announce their selection
July 17.
   The group, Christian Leaders for Responsible Television or
Clear-TV, said it is analyzing data collected during from the recent
TV sweeps period to compose its list.
   Billy Melvin, executive director of the National Association of
Evangelicals and chairman of the group, said the data was collected
by about 3,000 people watching TV in 33 states.
   He said network advertisers were asked three times before the
sweeps period, April 27 through May 24, to be responsible in the
placement of their commercials by avoiding programs with gratuitous
sex, violence, profanity and anti-Christian stereotyping.
   Some industry watchers say efforts in the early 1980s to boycott
advertisers failed. But advertisers have in recent months cancelled
ad plans following complaints from some individuals or groups
unhappy with the content of programs such as NBC's ``Saturday Night
Live'' and the Fox television network's ``Married ... with
Children.''
   Clear-TV, based in Wheaton, Ill., says it is a coalition of 1,600
Christian leaders with constituencies totaling 60 million people.
