<FIRST>u f AM-UAWConvention 1stLd-Writethru f0260 06-20 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAW Convention, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0260,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAW Convention Defeats Third Motion By Dissident Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to RESTORE overline, LaserPhoto line.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ANS1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to the United Auto Workers
convention turned aside Tuesday an attempt to limit joint
labor-management programs at auto plants, dealing a dissident group
its third major defeat in as many days.
   In a show-of-hands vote, delegates to the union's triennial
constitutional convention rejected a move that would have forced the
international union to support locals that oppose the team
management style.
   The so-called jointness resolution is a cornerstone of the
disagreement between the New Directions movement and the UAW's
leadership.
   The dissidents claim the joint programs endanger jobs and rob the
union of its strength. The Administration Caucus, which represents
the union's administration, contends that change in the workplace is
necessary, and that New Directions supporters don't recognize that.
   ``It makes me wonder where they (dissidents) have been in the
last 15 years,'' delegate John Nolan of Local 1895 in Broken Arrow,
Okla., area said during debate on the matter.
   But New Directions member Frank Hammer, president of Local 909 in
Warren, Mich., said the joint programs represent a union-breaking
strategy.
   ``I submit to you that jointness is their attempt to co-opt our
union,'' he said.
   The joint labor-management programs grew out of the auto
industry's slump in the early 1980s and the threat of foreign
competition.
   The New Directions effort also suggested that the union abandon
its seat on the Chrysler Corp. board of directors, now held by union
President Owen Bieber.
   Bieber bristled at the suggestion. ``It's a lonely place on that
board ... but it's the only voice of the workers,'' he said.
   After the loss, Jerry Tucker of St. Louis, the leader of the New
Directions movement, said he thought the debate was worthwhile and
that he hoped delegates would return to their locals and talk about
the convention with the rank and file.
   ``The rank and file ultimately will find ways to express
themselves,'' he said.
   Tucker declined to say exactly how or when that expression may
come. He did say he expected there would be a New Directions
presence at UAW prebargaining meetings next year. The UAW's
contracts with the Big Three automakers expire on Sept. 14, 1990.
   Before the debate, the third day of the convention got off to a
loud start as a parade of dissidents marched into the hall, waving
signs and shouting.
   It was the first organized demonstration during the convention by
New Directions forces, the strongest voice opposing UAW leadership
in 40 years.
   New Directions, which has about 20 percent of the delegates in
its corner, lost votes on two other major issues it brought to the
convention.
   One involved a credentials fight over certain delegates from UAW
regions in the Southwest and metropolitan Detroit. The other would
have required that the union abandon its practice of electing top
national officers at conventions and substitute for it a national
referendum of the rank and file.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890620-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-20-89 2245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HSN-GTETrial 1stLd-Writethru f0198 06-20 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HSN-GTE Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0198,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legal Fight Between Home Shopping Network, GTE Goes To Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 8th graf pvs, `GTE Florida ...,' to UPDATE
with GTE statement to jury. Picks up 9th graf pvs, `HSN's original ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home Shopping Network lost $400 million
in profits because its telephone equipment was inadequate to handle
the volume of calls, an attorney said Tuesday.
   The hefty loss was suffered over a 14-month period as the St.
Petersburg-based television retail giant went through a huge spurt
of growth, Chet Kamin, a lawyer for HSN, told a jury.
   GTE Corp. and its subsidiaries knew about the problems _ that a
staggering number of calls were not getting through _ but lied to
the company and persuaded HSN instead to buy even more equipment to
try to resolve the dilemma, he said.
   ``Home Shopping's like Mother's Day, every day,'' said Kamin,
referring to the high number of calls from viewers who may only
purchase items while they are being displayed on the screen.
   ``What happened as a result of GTE blocking calls and not telling
us is that we lost millions and millions of calls,'' Kamin said in
opening statements.
   A jury of five women and one man was seated Tuesday in a $1.5
billion battle between the corporate giants, HSN and GTE Corp.
   HSN sued GTE Florida, its parent GTE Corp., and other subsidaries
in 1987, alleging a number of misdeeds linked to what it claimed was
inadequate service and faulty phone equipment.
   GTE Florida and its parent company, a multibillion-dollar
telecommunications firm based in Stamford, Conn., have denied any
wrongdoing and said there was nothing wrong with their equipment.
They filed a countersuit alleging slander and libel and claimed that
HSN executives engaged in a ``blame the telephone company scheme to
mask HSN's poor market and financial performance ...''
   GTE counsel Roy Reardon told the jury that HSN's charges were
``absolutely baseless.''
   HSN had 4 million subscribers when it talked to GTE about
telephone service in 1985, Reardon said. That grew to 9 million by
August 1986, and one year later the number skyrocketed to 46.5
million, he said.
   Sales soared from $11 million in 1985 to $582 million by August
1987 _ all with the GTE telephone network in place, he said.
   ``We don't believe you just cover your own problems of
mismanagement ... by blaming other people. There was no fraud ... no
coverup,'' Reardon said.
   HSN's original 12-count complaint has been reduced to four
charges _ fraud, negligent misrepresentation, breach of trust and
confidence and breach of fiduciary duty.
   Pinellas Circuit Judge Howard Rives combined both suits in what
is expected to be a six-week trial.
   Although there are no phone company records showing the precise
number of calls in question, Home Shopping expects to show evidence
that 42 million calls were not completed betweeen February 1986 and
April 1987, Kamin said.
   He added that not all lost calls would have translated into sales.
   Kamin presented what he said was an internal GTE memo that noted
as many as 26,000 overflow calls in a one-hour period.
   The in-house document asks what are GTE subsidiaries
responsibilities to the customer and the efficiency of his service,
and notes that HSN ``is not aware that its calls are restricted.''
   ``It was in a sense a disaster waiting to happen,'' Kamin told
the six-member jury and five alternates.
   After April 1987 surveys showed HSN was losing 50 percent of its
calls the company switched carriers to MCI Communications Corp.,
Kamin said, adding the call completion rate now is over 90 percent.
</TEXT>
