<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0324 06-20 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0324,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firm, Stock Prices Slip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar held firm against the Japanese yen
Friday morning, while stock prices shed about half their early gains.
   The dollar was changing hands at 144.80 yen at late morning.
After opening at 144.85 yen, up 1.05 yen from Tuesday's close of
143.80 yen, the currency ranged from 144.73 to 144.95 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 220.29 points
Tuesday, lost 56.05 points, or 0.16 percent, to finish the morning
session at 33,177.42. The index gained 111.22 points during the
early morning session.
   Kinji Ishizuka, of Daiwa Securities Co., a major Japanese
brokerage, said the market experienced ``strong buying at the start,
but later weakening with many investors taking a wait-and-see
position'' in the absence of major market-affecting news.
   ``The market is not now reacting too much even if exchange rates
fluctuate at a margin of one yen or so,'' Ishizuka said.
   In the currency market, traders said the dollar was firm during
the morning session following its overnight firmness in overseas
markets.
   ``Investors still want to invest in dollar assets, but it fell so
suddenly last week that they cannot buy it up too aggressively,''
said a dealer of a major Japanese bank, who spoke anonymously.
   The dollar fluctuated wildly last week, with the currency closing
Thursday at 151.30 yen, its highest level in almost two years. The
dollar fell 6.25 yen Friday.
</TEXT>
